    <h2>
      CHAPTER I.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      Many loved Truth, and lavished life&rsquo;s best oil
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Amid the dusk of books to find her.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      But these our brothers fought for her,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      At life&rsquo;s dear peril wrought for her,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      So loved her that they died for her,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Tasting the raptured fleetness Of her divine completeness:
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Their higher instinct knew
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Those love her best who to themselves are true,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And what they dare to dream of dare to do.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      They followed her and found her Where all may hope to find&mdash;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Not in the ashes of the burnt-out mind,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      But beautiful with danger&rsquo;s sweetness round her,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Where faith made whole with deed
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Breathes its awakening breath
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Into the lifeless creed;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      They saw her plumed and mailed,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      With sweet, stem face unveiled,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And all-repaying eyes look proud on them in death.
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Lowell.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>here had been a
      heavy fall of snow in Hereford during the night, but the south walk in Dr.
      Harford&rsquo;s garden had been swept, and the still, frosty air and mid-day
      sunshine made the place as pleasant a playground as could be wished. The
      merry voices of a boy and girl had rung for the last half-hour in the
      pleasance, and the joys of snowballing were far too keen to allow the
      little couple to notice even for a moment the beauty of the wintry scene,
      with the rime-covered trees and bushes bordering the river, and in the
      background the cathedral, its massive tower surmounted in those
      seventeenth century days by a lofty spire covered with lead which
      glittered in the bright sunshine.
    </p>
    <p>
      Presently the two playmates grew tired of snowballing and retired to a
      little arbour, commonly called the sun-trap, for here on the coldest days
      warmth could generally be found. There was a lull in the merry sounds, but
      it was only the calm which precedes a storm, for before long came a
      vehement expostulation, &ldquo;Gabriel! Gabriel! let me have it. I <i>will</i>
      have it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not till you have promised,&rdquo; was the teasing retort, and from the arbour
      there sprang out a small boy, with the most winsome and mischievous face,
      his hazel eyes sparkling with elfish mirth, while he held high above his
      head a wooden puppet, as dear to its small owner as the loveliest of
      modern dolls.
    </p>
    <p>
      The bereft mother refused to enter into the game; it might be sport to
      him, but it was death to her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I won&rsquo;t promise!&rdquo; she said, angrily. &ldquo;Give me my babe.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; said Gabriel, laughing. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t have you chopping and changing. You
      said yesterday you would, and now you have changed your mind. Come,
      promise, Hilary, and I&rsquo;ll give you the puppet.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never!&rdquo; said Hilary, furiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      With a teasing laugh he tossed the puppet high in the air, intending to
      catch it as it fell; but, Hilary, frantic at this treatment of her
      Bartholomew babe, charged him with fury like a little goat, and the next
      minute both children were rolling in the snow..
    </p>
    <p>
      By the time they had picked themselves up the whole situation had changed,
      for, much to their astonishment, a huge mastiff came bounding through the
      garden and, seizing the puppet on the path, began to worry it.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a minute both paused, the girl aghast, the boy with knitted brows. It
      was well enough to tease his small playmate now and then, but he had not
      reckoned on this four-footed intruder. A sob from Hilary made him fly to
      the rescue.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Leave go, you brute!&rdquo; he shouted, trying in vain to drag back the mastiff
      by his collar.
    </p>
    <p>
      This was clearly hopeless. He pulled and tugged with all his might, but
      the dog unconcernedly chewed the doll.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, my babe&mdash;my poor babe!&rdquo; wailed Hilary.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whereupon Gabriel, pricked at heart, made a valiant snatch at the puppet,
      got it firmly by the head and succeeded in wrenching it from the very jaws
      of death.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There!&rdquo; he said, flinging it towards the little girl in triumph; but the
      triumph was short-lived, for it was now the turn of the dog, who,
      defrauded thus unceremoniously of his toy, seized angrily on the arm of
      the knight-errant.
    </p>
    <p>
      A scream of genuine terror from Hilary brought Dr. Harford rushing from
      the house, and in his wake followed a grave, stately gentleman whom the
      little girl at once recognised as Sir Robert Harley, of Brampton Bryan.
      Apparently the mastiff belonged to him, for at his stern summons it came
      to heel obediently, while Dr. Harford began to examine his son&rsquo;s arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How did you anger him, child?&rdquo; he asked, deftly unfastening Gabriel&rsquo;s
      dripping sleeve.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was my fault, sir,&rdquo; replied the boy, trying bravely to stiffen his
      lip. &ldquo;I threw up the puppet, and then the dog worried it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I trust Nero has not hurt him much,&rdquo; said Sir Robert, concerned to see
      the wound on the small, shapely arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, we&rsquo;ll soon set it right,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford, leading the child to the
      house; &ldquo;but with dog-bites you should never take half-measures. I must put
      a hot iron to it, so screw up your courage, laddie, and think how brave
      Cranmer thrust his hand into the flames.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel&rsquo;s heart sickened at the prospect before him, but he held up his
      head and stepped out more briskly, while Hilary crept after him with
      tearful eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will excuse me, Sir Robert, if I see to this matter at once,&rdquo; said
      the doctor, &ldquo;for delays are dangerous. I ran forth in such haste on
      hearing little Hilary Unett&rsquo;s scream that I have not yet even asked
      whether you will not lie here this night.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, I am to be the guest of Sir Richard Hopton at Canon Frome,&rdquo; said Sir
      Robert, seating himself by the fire in the doctor&rsquo;s study and watching his
      host&rsquo;s rapid movements as he prepared to dress the child&rsquo;s wound.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I did but come to bear to you and to Doctor Wright the news of Sir John
      Eliot&rsquo;s death.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What! Is he indeed gone?&rdquo; said Dr. Harford, sorrow clouding his fine,
      thoughtful face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Here is a letter I received last night from London,&rdquo; said Sir Robert. &ldquo;An
      you will I will read it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir John Eliot, one of the Members for Cornwall in the last Parliament,
      died this 27th day of November, after nigh upon four years&rsquo; imprisonment
      in the Tower, for refusing to answer for his conduct in Parliament
      anywhere but in Parliament itself, this being, he maintained, one of the
      inalienable rights of the English people, without which a just liberty
      would be impossible. Having incurred the displeasure of His Majesty on
      this account, and for his fearless unveiling of divers other Court abuses
      and irregularities, the King refused to release him, and, indeed, for the
      last year did keep him close prisoner in a dark, cold and wretchedly
      uncomfortable room, denying him, even at his physician&rsquo;s request, air and
      exercise, and forbidding him to see any save his sons. His health was thus
      undermined, and a fortnight since, when he did petition for a temporary
      release to recover from his sickness, the request was refused by His
      Majesty, and now that he lies dead the King will not grant his sons&rsquo;
      petition to carry the body for burial to Port Eliot, but orders that Sir
      John shall be buried in the church within the walls of the Tower. This
      harshness hath greatly angered all who knew the late Member for Cornwall,
      and, knowing him, could but admire his integrity, his courage and his
      patriotic devotion.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A brave man&mdash;a truly great man,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford. &ldquo;Sir John Eliot
      is the martyr who by his blood will safeguard our Parliamentary rights.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As he spoke he took the hot iron from the fire and drew Gabriel gently
      towards him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now, my son,&rdquo; he said, in the voice which by its tender but firm
      cheerfulness had nerved many a sufferer, &ldquo;what a joy it will be to your
      father if you follow in that great man&rsquo;s steps. Nothing could daunt Sir
      John; cost what it might he was ever true.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The boy being of a highly-strung, nervous temperament turned deathly
      white, but never flinched as the hot iron seared his flesh; only a stifled
      moan escaped him, and Hilary through her tears saw the strangest look of
      triumph in his dilated eyes&mdash;a look that made her heart throb with
      love and admiration. In a few minutes more the arm was carefully bandaged,
      the two gentlemen continuing meantime their grave talk.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will send word to Frank Unett that you are here, sir,&rdquo; said Dr.
      Harford, &ldquo;for he, too, is one that deplores the present illegal rule
      without a Parliament; he will mourn Sir John&rsquo;s death.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We call it a death,&rdquo; said Sir Robert, &ldquo;but he has been as surely murdered
      by the rigours of imprisonment as though he had been stabbed in the Tower.
      Well,&rdquo; with a sigh, &ldquo;the day of reckoning cannot long be delayed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There, laddie,&rdquo; said the doctor, drawing the sleeve gently over the
      bandage, &ldquo;you have borne it like an Englishman; now run off into the fresh
      air and forget your troubles.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With respectful salutes to their elders the children returned to the
      garden; Hilary, with her pretty eyes still tender and subdued, slipped her
      arm caressingly round her playmate&rsquo;s neck. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry, Gabriel,&rdquo; she said,
      in a tremulous voice, &ldquo;and all the time I didn&rsquo;t really mean it. I will be
      your little wife.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel turned and kissed her soft, rosy cheek with great frankness and
      warmth. &ldquo;If you will,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll promise not to worry your puppets
      any more. I don&rsquo;t know how it is,&rdquo; he continued reflectively, &ldquo;but there&rsquo;s
      something that makes a boy feel to a puppet like a dog does to a cat&mdash;he
      <i>must</i> worry it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There was the one you roasted last Lammastide,&rdquo; said Hilary, sadly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you know it did make a glorious bonfire, and you enjoyed that part of
      it,&rdquo; said Gabriel, with mirth in his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But I wanted the puppet back again afterwards.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, well, I must try to remember you like the wretches. And you must
      really remember your promise, and not chop and change any more!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What does chop mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go up and down like the sea; don&rsquo;t you know how old Nat the sailor says
      the sea was a bit choppy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I won&rsquo;t be like the sea,&rdquo; said Hilary, her lovely little face flushing
      and her eyes shining. &ldquo;I give you my real true promise to be your wife.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel did not repeat the kiss, for at that moment there flashed into his
      mind a fresh idea.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hilary,&rdquo; he exclaimed, &ldquo;let us build a snow monument to Sir John Eliot;
      he shall lie in effigy like Bishop Swinfield in the cathedral.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But your arm?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can work with the right one,&rdquo; he replied, cheerfully, and the two were
      soon as happy as could be fashioning their recumbent snow man.
    </p>
    <p>
      Later on Dr. Harford, passing down the south walk arm-inarm with Hilary&rsquo;s
      father, and still discussing the sad news brought by Sir Robert Harley,
      drew his friend&rsquo;s attention to the busy little pair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They make excellent playmates,&rdquo; said Frank Unett. &ldquo;What would I not give
      for the hope of living to see my little maid grow up! But it will not be;
      Sir John Eliot&rsquo;s malady will carry me off long ere that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Harford knew only too well that his companion spoke the truth, but he
      answered cheerfully, &ldquo;You cannot look forward to long life, but with care
      you will be spared to us for some years, I trust.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should not dread leaving my wife and child behind were not the times so
      dark,&rdquo; said the invalid. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis true my father-in-law is a learned
      and worthy man, but his views are not mine. Do what you can for them,
      Bridstock, they will need staunch friends.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, sir,&rdquo; said Gabriel, running towards them, &ldquo;pray do come and see the
      monument we have made to Sir John Eliot.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The two gentlemen praised the work.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And what do you know of Sir John?&rdquo; said Mr. Unett, with a smile.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know how brave he was,&rdquo; said Gabriel, &ldquo;and that he died to save us from
      being made slaves.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He heard Sir Robert reading the news-letter,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford, putting
      his hand tenderly on Gabriel&rsquo;s head. &ldquo;Somehow a child always contrives to
      go straight to the mark and grasp the essential point of a tale.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Out of the mouths of babes and sucklings,&rdquo; murmured Frank Unett, glancing
      from the eager-faced children to the snow effigy&mdash;the only monument
      brave John Eliot was like to have in the land for which he died. &ldquo;But
      what&rsquo;s amiss with your arm, lad?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir Robert&rsquo;s dog bit it, but my father has cured it again,&rdquo; said Gabriel,
      sturdily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was my fault, father,&rdquo; said Hilary; &ldquo;we were quarrelling.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Eh? What was the disputed point? You two are for ever arguing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yet their greatest punishment is to be apart,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford, with his
      genial laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I said I wouldn&rsquo;t be Gabriel&rsquo;s wife,&rdquo; said Hilary, hanging her head. &ldquo;But
      we&rsquo;ve made it up again, and I have given him my promise.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, you have, have you?&rdquo; said her father, laughing; &ldquo;and without so much
      as a &lsquo;by your leave&rsquo; to me? Well, I could wish you no better lot. He will
      make a rare good husband, an I am not much mistaken.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come, Frank, you ought not to stand still this cold day,&rdquo; said the
      doctor; &ldquo;&rsquo;tis time you were in the house again.&rdquo; They moved on, the
      invalid still smiling over his daughter&rsquo;s words.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The little minx!&rdquo; he continued. &ldquo;How innocently she said it. I should be
      heartily glad should their childish notion be carried out later on.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Stranger things have happened, Frank,&rdquo; said the doctor, with a smile;
      &ldquo;and I should be glad to have pretty Hilary for a daughter-in-law.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder what she will grow up?&rdquo; said the invalid. &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; with a sigh,
      &ldquo;I shall not be here to see.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Look, here comes that bustling housekeeper of yours,&rdquo; said the doctor,
      not sorry to turn the conversation. &ldquo;Well, Mrs. Durdle, are you come to
      upbraid the physician for keeping your master out of doors?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A stout, buxom, cheery-looking woman came hurrying towards them through
      the wicket-gate which led into the adjoining garden.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, no, sir,&rdquo; she said, breathlessly, &ldquo;though if I may make bold to say
      so, I think master would be a deal better by the hearth than out in the
      sun this December day; but the Christmas puddings, sir, are ready for
      stirring, and I was coming to bid the children take their turn, or they
      will have no luck at all next year.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Heathen superstition, Mrs. Durdle,&rdquo; said the doctor, with a smile. &ldquo;But
      make not over-much of the bite Gabriel hath received, for in this case,
      truly, least said soonest mended. Tell him no tales about those that die
      of a dog-bite.&rdquo; The housekeeper promised and went in search of the
      children.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not but what I know many a tale,&rdquo; she reflected. &ldquo;And, Lord! what a
      terrible thing it would be if the doctor should lose his son that way.
      They would bury the little lad in the cathedral, doubtless, for the
      Harfords, they come of a great family, as old as any in the county. I
      should go myself to help lay him out&mdash;that servant of theirs is a
      feckless wench. Oh, gracious me! Why, they&rsquo;re already making his tomb!&rdquo;
       and in amaze she looked at the two children, who were putting the last
      touches to their snow monument.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lor&rsquo; bless my heart, dearies!&rdquo; exclaimed Mrs. Durdle, &ldquo;what do you make
      that corpse-like thing for? Why couldn&rsquo;t you keep to an honest Jack Frost
      with a pipe in his mouth?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, Durdle, &rsquo;tis Sir John Eliot, the Parliament man. We&rsquo;re making
      his monument.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, what can put such an idea into the child&rsquo;s head as to make a
      monument to a Parliament man? We&rsquo;re not going to have no more Parliaments
      they tell me, and a good job, too. Done without them these many years well
      enough, says I. Come in now, my dearies. Come and stir the Christmas
      puddings&mdash;here&rsquo;s nigh upon a week past since &lsquo;Stir-up Sunday.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The children were always glad of an excuse to visit the kitchen, where
      Durdle, a cheerful, chatty soul, ever gave them a hearty welcome. They
      wanted no second bidding, and were soon perched on the table with the huge
      pudding-crock between them and two strong wooden spoons.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wish, Hilary; it&rsquo;s no good stirring unless you wish,&rdquo; said Gabriel,
      swinging his legs, while he meditated what gift to ask of fortune.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish for a beautiful new puppet at Christmas,&rdquo; said Hilary, without the
      smallest hesitation.
    </p>
    <p>
      A flush rose to Gabriel&rsquo;s forehead; he felt pricked at heart, and was on
      the point of assuring her that he himself would make that wish true. But
      the old loathing of puppets died hard. He remained prudently silent.
    </p>
    <p>
      Next came Mrs. Durdle herself with a wish about her valentine in the
      coming year, which the children thought profoundly uninteresting. What
      could a widow of thirty have to do with valentines, indeed?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And now, Master Gabriel, for <i>your</i> wish,&rdquo; said Durdle, as the boy
      still hesitated.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, Gabriel, yours&mdash;be quick!&rdquo; adjured Hilary.
    </p>
    <p>
      He grasped the spoon and stirred the pudding vigorously, with an odd,
      far-away look on his intent face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; asked his companions, &ldquo;what did you wish?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, that,&rdquo; said Gabriel, colouring as he slipped down from the table&mdash;&ldquo;that&rsquo;s
      my secret.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And neither Durdle&rsquo;s cajoling nor Hilary&rsquo;s earnest entreaties could make
      him say another word about the matter.
    </p>
    <p>
      Before long, moreover, Hilary was summoned to her mother&rsquo;s room, and
      Gabriel ran home through the garden, pausing for one last look at the snow
      monument by the south walk.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish to be like you,&rdquo; he whispered to the effigy of Sir John Eliot; &ldquo;I
      wish to give my life for the country&rsquo;s freedom.&rdquo; Then, without a thought
      of what his wish might involve, he ran cheerfully home along the frosty
      paths singing a snatch of the old Bosbury carol:
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;Oh! praise the Lord with one accord,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      All you that present be;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      For Christ, God&rsquo;s Son, has brought pardon
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      All for to make us free.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /> <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0002" id="link2HCH0002"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER II.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      From all vain pomps and shows,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      From the pride that overflows.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And the false conceits of men,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      From all the narrow rules
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And subtleties of schools,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And the craft of tongue and pen;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Bewildered in its search,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Bewildered with the cry
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;Lo, here! lo, there, the Church!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Poor, sad Humanity
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Through all the dust and heat
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Turns back with bleeding feet,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      By the weary road it came,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Unto the simple thought,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      By the great Master taught,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And that remaineth still:
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Not he that repeateth the name,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      But he that doeth the will!
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Longfellow.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">F</span>rank Unett had
      spoken truly&mdash;it was impossible that he should live to see his child
      grow up; yet he made a hard fight with death, and, thanks to the tender
      nursing of his wife and the rare skill of his friend, Dr. Bridstock
      Harford, lived for some time after that December day when Hilary&rsquo;s future
      had been spoken of.
    </p>
    <p>
      It always seemed to Gabriel that their childhood ended at his funeral, for
      then it was that they learnt of the separation in store for them. Hilary
      was to go with her mother for a long visit to some of her father&rsquo;s
      kinsfolk, and by the time she returned his own schooldays would have
      begun, Dr. Harford having decided to send him to Gloucester with Sir
      Robert Harley&rsquo;s son Ned, a boy some eighteen months his junior.
    </p>
    <p>
      Very sorrowfully did the playmates take leave of each other, and Gabriel
      moped about sadly, understanding for the first time what it meant to be an
      only child.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was on one of the days when he was missing his playfellow most that
      Hereford was thrown into a state of unwonted excitement by a visitation
      from Archbishop Laud. Gabriel found great relief and satisfaction in the
      crowded streets and the gala aspect of the city with its flags and
      decorations. But he was disappointed to find that the Archbishop himself
      was a little hard-featured, cold-eyed man in whom he could feel no
      interest at all.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There was nothing to see but clothes,&rdquo; he said afterwards to his father.
      &ldquo;Except for them his Grace was just a common little man, much like Dickon,
      the tailor, in Eign street.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Harford laughed. &ldquo;I do not think his Grace is a large man either in
      body or mind,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;But there is no doubt he is a good man, Gabriel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You do not, then, hold with Sir Robert Harley,&rdquo; said his wife, &ldquo;that the
      Archbishop would fain hand England over to the Pope.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, no, Elizabeth; Sir Robert is ever haunted by that terror. &rsquo;Tis
      a view held, indeed, by many, and doubtless the Archbishop&rsquo;s innovations
      and unwise ceremonies give colour to the charge. Also he deals out harder
      measure to the sectaries than to the Papists. But though I loathe his
      ear-croppings and nose slittings, I don&rsquo;t believe him to be a traitor to
      Protestantism,&rdquo; said the doctor. &ldquo;On the contrary, I know of a gentleman
      of this county whom he dissuaded from becoming a Papist.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It chanced the next morning that Dr. Harford had to visit a patient in the
      direction of Brampton Bryan, and the day being very fine he told Gabriel
      that he would take him as his companion, and that afterwards he should see
      his future schoolfellow. There were few treats the boy enjoyed more than a
      ride with his father, for Dr. Harford was a great naturalist, and there
      were countless things to interest him in the Herefordshire lanes&mdash;details
      that Gabriel would never have observed at all if left to himself. They had
      not gone far along Bridge street that morning, however, when a messenger
      came running across the road with a paper, which he thrust into the
      doctor&rsquo;s hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am loth to be the bearer of this, sir, but a man must do the work of
      his office,&rdquo; he said, apologetically.
    </p>
    <p>
      The doctor reined in his horse to read the paper, and Gabriel, glancing up
      at him from his sturdy little pony &ldquo;Joyce,&rdquo; saw a look of intense
      annoyance upon his face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When am I to come?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At once, sir, if you please,&rdquo; said the messenger, respectfully. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis
      very much against the will of every Hereford man, you may be sure, sir,
      but we have no choice in the matter.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I will go without delay; &rsquo;tis at the Archdeacon&rsquo;s court, I
      suppose?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The messenger replied in the affirmative, and the doctor touched up his
      horse and went off at such a brisk pace that Joyce&rsquo;s short legs had some
      difficulty in keeping abreast of his roan mare. Arrived at his
      destination, he dismounted and threw the reins to his groom.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall not be long, Gabriel,&rdquo; he said, looking round at his son as he
      entered the building.
    </p>
    <p>
      A vague uneasiness filled the lad&rsquo;s mind. What was the matter, and why was
      Simon the groom speedily surrounded by a small crowd of eager questioners?
      Among them he could see old Nat the sailor, his wrinkled face bearing a
      look of indignation which he had never before seen there.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nat,&rdquo; he called, &ldquo;pray come and speak with me. What does it all mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, master,&rdquo; said the old man, &ldquo;it means that Archbishop Laud has
      summoned the best man in all Hereford because, forsooth, he does not bow
      his head to order in the church.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! Nat, you don&rsquo;t think they&rsquo;ll cut off his ears, do you?&rdquo; said the boy
      in an agony, remembering in a flash all the gruesome and, alas! true tales
      he had heard of such practices.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know, master, but Simon here thinks it&rsquo;s a matter of paying a
      fine. I&rsquo;m going into the court to see for myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      In a trice Gabriel had dismounted. &ldquo;Take me with you, Nat&mdash;please
      do,&rdquo; he said. He was small for his years, and doubted whether the
      officials would let him pass alone, but his confidence in the old sailor
      was unbounded, and Nat made no objection, but led the boy into the
      Archdeacon&rsquo;s court, where on the very last bench they found a spare place.
    </p>
    <p>
      However small, however ill-furnished, there is generally something
      impressive about a court. To-day, moreover, all the diocesan officials
      were removed from their customary places, while raised above the ordinary
      mortals Archbishop Laud sat in a great chair of state. In the next tier
      were seated his vicar-general and various subordinate officials; while to
      the left side, at a lower level, stood Dr. Bridstock Harford. The doctor,
      who had married extremely early in his medical student days, was now not
      very much over thirty, a vigorous, intellectual-looking man, with one of
      those strong, quiet faces which inspire confidence. As Nat and Gabriel
      entered he had been asked what he had to say in defence, and Gabriel&rsquo;s
      heart pounded in his breast as he listened to the calm, courteous reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your Grace,&rdquo; said the doctor, &ldquo;it is true that I have never practised any
      bowings or genuflexions, and for these reasons: First, nothing in Holy
      Writ seems to warrant it, the oft-quoted verse, &lsquo;At the Name shall every
      knee bow,&rsquo; being, as all Greek students are well aware, truly the
      assertion that <i>in</i> the name of Christ all shall pray or worship. In
      another Scripture I read that God doth in no wise care that a man should
      bow his head like a bulrush; and in yet another that &lsquo;God hath made men
      upright, but they have sought out many inventions.&rsquo; But, your Grace, what
      chiefly moves me to shun these formal bowings is the belief that in all
      matters of religion there should be a deep reserve betwixt the soul and
      God. Surely a reverence that is both sincere and profound seeks rather to
      express itself by inward and spiritual adoration than by any muscular
      movements, or ceremonies that are visible to others and which may become
      as like as not either Pharisaical or merely automaton-like. Christ spoke
      of a worship that should be in spirit and in truth, but gave us only two
      ceremonies, and those the simplest conceivable. For these reasons I object
      to complying with the order.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The harsh voice of the Archbishop broke the silence which followed. It was
      utterly impossible for him to understand any side of a question but his
      own, and his fatal lack of sympathetic insight blinded him to the noble
      nature of the man he was dealing with.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your arguings, sir,&rdquo; he remarked, &ldquo;are what I should have expected from
      one of the teachers of science, falsely so called. Well was it written,
      &lsquo;Knowledge puffeth up.&rsquo; How intractable, how lacking in humility is your
      nature I call on all here to witness.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The doctor&rsquo;s colour rose a little. He seemed about to reply, but thought
      better of it and held his peace. From the back of the court, however, came
      angry murmurs, for few men were more popular in Hereford. The people did
      not trouble at all about his views, but almost all of them knew what he
      was in times of sickness or distress. Nat, the sailor, swore beneath his
      breath in a soft monotone which seemed to relieve him, and Gabriel, with
      eyes like two live coals, slipped quietly through the crowd and made his
      way to his father&rsquo;s side, craving to be as near him as possible.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you solemnly undertake never again to offend in this matter?&rdquo; was
      the next question.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your Grace,&rdquo; replied the doctor, &ldquo;I can undertake nothing of the sort,
      but do claim my right to stand fast in the liberty wherewith Christ hath
      set us free, and not to be entangled again in the yoke of bondage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then every time you do not bow at the sacred Name be well assured that
      you will be fined,&rdquo; was the sharp retort, and sentence of the Court with
      the amount of fine was duly pronounced.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel breathed more freely. It was not a question of earcropping; but
      his heart burned with wrath at the way in which the Archbishop rebuked his
      father, and drawing nearer to him, he caught his hand in his and kissed it
      with a devotion and reverence that touched more than one spectator.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your own son teaches you that outward ceremonies are not valueless,&rdquo; said
      the Archbishop.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your Grace,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford, looking up with an unusual light in his
      quiet eyes, &ldquo;should I value my little son&rsquo;s demonstration if there were
      compulsion in it&mdash;if it were a ceremony performed at fixed moments?
      And would it be worth aught to me if he were fined so many shillings for
      omitting it? Pardon my outspokenness, but your Grace, though a learned
      man, knows naught of fatherhood.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Remove this prating Puritan and let the next case be called,&rdquo; said the
      Archbishop, harshly.
    </p>
    <p>
      And as Dr. Harford and Gabriel moved away, the court rang with the clerk&rsquo;s
      stentorian voice shouting, &ldquo;Mary Boswood, on a charge of refusing to wear
      a white veil when returning thanks after childbirth.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As they passed down the gangway they met the unlucky matron with flushed
      face and tearful eyes making her way to the place they had quitted, and
      deeming it a very hard thing that she, who had been a virtuous wedded wife
      for years, should be dragged into court for refusing to wear, as she
      expressed it, &ldquo;a thing as like as two peas to the white sheet in which bad
      women did penance.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel gave a gasp of relief when once more they breathed the fresh outer
      air. He ran to Joyce and patted her neck and fondled her soft ears before
      mounting. Then in silence the father and son rode away together, not
      speaking at all until they had left the city and had had a good gallop
      over the broad strip of grass that bordered the road to Brampton Bryan.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That has refreshed you, lad,&rdquo; said the doctor, glancing at the grave face
      beside him, &ldquo;and yet you look as though you had something on your mind.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Father,&rdquo; said Gabriel, vehemently, &ldquo;I hate Archbishop Laud with my whole
      heart! Yet you said he was a good man!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Indeed I believe him to be a very good man, but he hath more zeal than
      discretion, and forgets that &lsquo;the end of the commandment is charity out of
      a pure heart.&rsquo; Dr. Laud will one day find that he is making a great
      mistake. He is trying with all his might to make folks better by outward
      observances, by making clean the cup and the platter; that is to put the
      cart before the horse. You must first make them pure within, or you will
      but breed up a generation of ceremonious hypocrites and Pharisees.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is because of the discourteous way he spoke to you, sir, that I hate
      him,&rdquo; said Gabriel, fiercely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, hate him not; I fared much better than I should have done had I been
      a parson. They tell me that twenty clergy have been deprived of their
      livings, only for this refusal to bow. As for the Archbishop&rsquo;s
      discourtesy, which makes him so much disliked by the gentry of the land,
      that is not altogether his fault, perhaps, for he had neither good birth
      nor good breeding. He said that &lsquo;Knowledge puffeth up,&rsquo; and I was much
      minded to quote him the rest of the verse&mdash;&lsquo;but love buildeth up.&rsquo;
      Depend on it, my son, &rsquo;tis that love alone which can save our
      unhappy country in these difficult times.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will they still be difficult when I am a man?&rdquo; asked Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I fear they will,&rdquo; said the doctor, gravely. &ldquo;Therefore remember that you
      hate no man, howsoever his sayings and doings may offend you. Have your
      own faith, but see that you force it not on others, as is too much the
      custom; for Dr. Laud is wrong&mdash;compulsion never yet helped the good
      cause. What would you think of a physician who thought all men&rsquo;s ailments
      were to be treated alike? Men&rsquo;s souls are as different as their bodies,
      and their minds are cast in many moulds. The wise servant of Christ knows
      this, and seeks not to browbeat all men till they conform to one method.
      Never forget, lad, that your meat may be another man&rsquo;s poison. There is
      only one infallible remedy, and as the proverb hath it, &lsquo;<i>Amor vincit
      omnia!</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      By this time they had reached the house of the first patient, and Gabriel
      was sent on with the groom to the neighbouring inn to order their noontide
      meal. When this had been discussed, and he had listened to the cheerful
      talk between his father and the landlord on the prospects of the crops, he
      had altogether forgotten Dr. Laud and his harsh words, and thought the
      world once more a pleasant place.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was much, too, to divert his mind when they reached Brampton Bryan
      Castle. He quickly fraternised with Ned, the eldest son, and quite lost
      his heart to sweet-faced Lady Brilliana, Sir Robert&rsquo;s wife. She had
      travelled much, and had lived for many years in Holland, so that her talk
      was infinitely more easy as well as more interesting than that of any
      other lady he had met. Moreover, while Sir Robert was of the somewhat hard
      and narrow Puritan school, she was surely the gentlest Puritan dame that
      ever breathed, and seemed full of kindness to all, whatever their views.
      He began on that day, as they wandered about the castle, a friendship with
      Ned which was to last all through his life, and his pity for his father
      was great when, on returning from the most delightful scramble about the
      battlements, they found Sir Robert Harley still discoursing on the
      vestments&mdash;and what he indignantly called the &lsquo;altar-ducking&rsquo;&mdash;which
      Archbishop Laud had ordered in Hereford Cathedral.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was destined to hear much more of the Archbishop when, his schooldays
      ended, he was sent, at the age of fifteen, to Oxford with Ned Harley. They
      were entered at Magdalene Hall, at that time an especially Puritan
      college, and here his distrust of Dr. Laud and his ways increased not a
      little. For he rebelled with all his might against the Archbishop&rsquo;s notion
      of driving and coercing men into the ways he deemed best for them. Dr.
      Laud might, as his father always maintained, be a good man, but he was
      good after a fashion which stirred up all the combative elements in
      Gabriel&rsquo;s nature.
    </p>
    <p>
      Meanwhile Hilary Unett was being educated after a very different fashion.
      On her return from visiting her Unett kinsfolk she scarcely stirred from
      home, and her interests were entirely bound up in the quiet cathedral
      town. It chanced that after two or three rapid changes at the Palace her
      grandfather, Bishop Coke, had been translated from Bristol to the see of
      Hereford. He was a good and kind-hearted man, with a great reputation for
      learning; but now that Mr. Unett was dead, and Gabriel only in Hereford at
      rare intervals, it naturally followed that every influence round the girl
      was ecclesiastical. She therefore almost inevitably fell into the way of
      looking at all questions from the palace point of view.
    </p>
    <p>
      Now and then, as he watched her, Dr. Harford would recall her father&rsquo;s
      words on the day they had heard of Eliot&rsquo;s death; but as he thought how
      the paths of the boy and girl were already beginning to diverge, that
      dream of a future union looked less and less probable.
    </p>
    <p>
      He sighed as in imagination he looked down the vista of the coming years,
      plainly foreseeing that stormy times were in store for the nation, and
      that grave troubles and divisions awaited every household in the land. But
      he was not a man of many words, and he kept his musings to himself.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0003" id="link2HCH0003"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER III.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      This is the time when bit by bit
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      The days begin to lengthen sweet,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And every minute gained is joy,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And love stirs in the heart of a boy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      This is the time the sun, of late
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Content to lie abed till eight,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Lifts up betimes his sleepy head,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And love stirs in the heart of a maid.
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Katherine Tynan Hinkson.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">I</span>t was in the
      spring of 1640, just when King Charles had dissolved the Short Parliament,
      after its three weeks&rsquo; existence, that Hilary made a discovery. She
      possessed a voice, a voice which, after a few lessons from the Cathedral
      organist, proved to be a source of real pleasure to herself and others.
      This event meant much more to her than the fact that England had again
      relapsed into the woeful plight of the last eleven years, and was once
      more without a Parliament. At every spare minute she was practising her
      guitar, or singing scales and songs, and thus it very naturally fell about
      that Gabriel, returning from Oxford that summer, was greeted, as he
      hastened along the south walk to the little gate which made the boundary
      between the two gardens, by a song &ldquo;more tuneable than lark to shepherd&rsquo;s
      ear.&rdquo; Stealing quietly forward, he could catch the words, which were set
      to the pathetic air of &ldquo;Bara Fostus&rsquo; Dream&rdquo;;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Come, sweet love, let sorrow cease,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Banish frowns, leave off dissension,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Love&rsquo;s wars make the sweetest peace,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Hearts uniting by contention.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Sunshine follows after rain,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Sorrows ceasing, this is pleasing,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      All proves fair again,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      After sorrow soon comes joy;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Try me, prove me, trust me, love me,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      This will cure annoy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      The voice was a mezzo-soprano, with that strange gift of individual charm,
      without which far finer voices fail to please. It seemed to witch the very
      heart of the listener, and Gabriel, determined as he was not to disturb
      the song, was all on fire to see the singer.
    </p>
    <p>
      As she played the interlude on the guitar at the end of the first verse he
      stole over the grass, and, climbing up the old filbert tree, swung himself
      noiselessly on to the wall, and looked down eagerly through the leafy
      branches. Not far off, at the opposite end of a grassy glade, sat Hilary,
      her soft brown curls, held back by a snood of pink ribbon, but falling
      nevertheless about her comely face as she bent over the guitar. She wore a
      pale grey gown with dainty trimmings of pink, and the delicate colouring
      of her sweet womanly face made one think of apple-blossom.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel&rsquo;s heart throbbed fast. Was this the child he had once teased? The
      companion he had sometimes wished a boy to share his rougher sports? The
      playmate he had quarrelled with so often, and kissed with careless
      kindliness when the dispute had ended? How had he ever dared to do it all?
      Then again the song thrilled him
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Winter hides his frosty face,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Blushing now to be more viewed:
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Spring return&rsquo;d with pleasant grace,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Flora&rsquo;s treasures are renewed;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Lambs rejoice to see the spring,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Skipping, leaping, sporting, playing,
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      Birds for joy do sing.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      So let the spring of joy renew,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Laughing, colling, kissing, playing,
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      And give love his due.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel&rsquo;s longing to see the singer&rsquo;s downcast eyes almost overcame him
      but he waited while once more the bird-like voice rang through the quiet
      garden&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Then, sweet love, disperse this cloud,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      That obscures this scornful coying;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      When each creature sings aloud,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Filling hearts with over-joying.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      As every bird doth choose her mate,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Gently billing, she is willing
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      Her true love to take.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      With such words let us contend
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      (Laughing, colling, kissing, playing),
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      So our strife shall end.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel swung himself down by the filbert tree, brushed the dust from his
      dark green doublet, set his broad-brimmed hat at the correct angle with
      unusual care, and made his way through the gate as though he had never
      climbed a tree or lounged upon a wall in his life.
    </p>
    <p>
      Who would have dreamed that to walk down that familiar glade to greet
      Hilary, would ever have caused his throat to grow dry and his breath to
      come in so strange a fashion, for all the world as though he were running
      a race! At last she looked up, and with a glad cry rose to welcome him;
      the guitar slipped unheeded on to the grass, and both her hands caught
      his, while her dark grey eyes smiled in a way that fairly dazzled the
      youth, who had but just realised that he was her lover.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So you have come from Oxford at last,&rdquo; she cried. &ldquo;How long it is since
      we met!&rdquo; He stooped to kiss her hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Surely it was in some other life!&rdquo; he said, with a strange feeling that
      suddenly all things had become new.
    </p>
    <p>
      She laughed gaily as they sat down side by side. &ldquo;Here, at any rate, is
      the same old stone bench where you and I used to learn our lessons,&rdquo; she
      said. &ldquo;And yonder is the stump to which you tied my puppet the day you
      played at Smithfield martyrs.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What a little brute I was.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You were a rare hand at teasing; but I&rsquo;ll never forget it to you that you
      rescued my Bartholomew babe from the power of the dog. How the wretch bit
      your arm!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am much indebted to him,&rdquo; said Gabriel, smiling, &ldquo;and would not for the
      world lose that honourable scar. Nothing would please me more than to
      suffer again in your service.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His face was aglow, and Hilary, with a little stirring of the heart,
      turned from him and plucked a rose from the great hush of sweet-briar
      growing near the bench.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was a minute&rsquo;s silence, broken by the snapping of one of her guitar
      strings. She took a fresh string from the case, and was about to put it
      on, when she found the guitar quietly taken from her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let me do that,&rdquo; said Gabriel, pleadingly; and Hilary, with a novel sense
      of pleasure in being helped, allowed him to have his way, glancing now and
      again at his intent face, which was the same, yet not the the same, she
      had known all her life.
    </p>
    <p>
      Truth to tell, Gabriel was no lover of books; he had not at all the look
      of the pallid student, and had burnt no midnight oil at Oxford. But the
      University life had changed him from boy to man, his chest was a good two
      inches broader from rowing; he had an air of health and vigour, and the
      clearly-cut features, which were of the Roman type, had kept their
      refinement, but had lost the stamp of physical delicacy they had once
      borne.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How well I remember Nero&rsquo;s onslaught that day,&rdquo; said Hilary. &ldquo;It was the
      day we heard of Sir John Eliot&rsquo;s death in the Tower.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did you hear that Mr. Valentine and Mr. Strode, who were imprisoned at
      the same time as Sir John Eliot, were released last January? They had been
      in gaol nigh upon eleven years,&rdquo; said Gabriel; and as he looked up from
      the guitar, Hilary saw an indignant gleam in his hazel eyes which startled
      her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now you look as you used to look when we quarrelled,&rdquo; she said, smiling.
      &ldquo;By the bye, what did we quarrel about the day the dog bit you? I have
      quite forgot.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We wrangled over something in the sun-trap,&rdquo; said Gabriel, his eyes
      growing tender once more. &ldquo;What was it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Laughingly they both turned their minds back to the days when they had
      been children together, and presently, in a flash, the whole scene came
      back to them. Once again Hilary saw her father&rsquo;s look of amusement as she
      gave her childish explanation of the dispute, &ldquo;I said I wouldn&rsquo;t be
      Gabriel&rsquo;s wife, but we have made it up again, and I have given him my
      promise.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The colour surged up into her face as for an instant she met Gabriel&rsquo;s
      eyes, for in their liquid depths she could read love and eager hope, and
      withal just a touch of the mirthful expression which she knew so well of
      old. She knew that he, too, had heard that voice from the past.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dropping the briar rose and hastily taking the guitar, she began to tune
      the string he had just fixed. The sound awoke Gabriel to the consciousness
      that they were not alone in the world, that the garden was no Garden of
      Eden, and that lovemaking was not so simple as in the days of their
      childhood. He remembered Mrs. Unett and Bishop Coke, who would assuredly
      have much to say as soon as this Midsummer&rsquo;s dream had formed itself into
      words. &ldquo;Sing to me,&rdquo; he said, when the string at length was in tune. &ldquo;So
      far I have but heard <i>Bara Fostus</i> from the other side of the wall&mdash;a
      sweet air, but somewhat melancholy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary racked her brain for a song which was not a love song, but failed
      to find anything better than &ldquo;Phyllis on the New-Mown Hay,&rdquo; which she sang
      with a spirit so gay and <i>debonnair</i>, and a voice so exquisitely
      fresh, that Gabriel&rsquo;s passion was increased ten-fold. Like the lover in
      the song, he bid fair to be a most &ldquo;faithful Damon,&rdquo; and Hilary knew it,
      and wondered how it had come to pass that but an hour before they had been
      well content to think of each other merely as old friends and playfellows.
    </p>
    <p>
      They were deep in conversation when, looking up, Hilary saw her
      grandfather slowly pacing down the garden. The Palace was not far from
      Mrs. Unett&rsquo;s house, and the old man loved to escape from the state and
      ceremony that surrounded him, and to enjoy the quiet of his daughter&rsquo;s
      home. Gabriel, who had been much away from Hereford, had only met the
      Bishop occasionally. But when at Oxford he had heard complaints of the
      tyranny, the mischief-making and the political intrigues of bishops in
      general, he had always looked on their own Bishop as a remarkable
      exception to the general rule. Glancing now at the stately old man, whose
      scholarly face bore a striking resemblance to that of his brother, Sir
      John Coke, the recently-dismissed Secretary of State, he knew that he was
      confronting the arbiter of his fate, and noted with relief the kindly look
      in the Bishop&rsquo;s eyes as he caught sight of them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So, Mr. Harford, you are returned to us once more,&rdquo; said the old man,
      giving him a courteous greeting. &ldquo;I heard my granddaughter&rsquo;s voice, but
      did not know of your arrival.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The plague is increasing at Oxford, my lord,&rdquo; said Gabriel; &ldquo;and it was
      thought best that we should not remain there. I returned to Brampton Bryan
      with Ned Harley.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The name of Harley brought a shadow over the Bishop&rsquo;s face, for Sir
      Robert&rsquo;s Puritanism met with little favour in the county. He reflected
      with some uneasiness that Gabriel Harford was of the same persuasion, in
      all probability, and not altogether a good companion for Hilary.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sing to us, child,&rdquo; he said, glancing at his granddaughter and Hilary,
      who had noted his change of expression, began his favourite air
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;Hark, hark, the lark at heaven&rsquo;s gate sings!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      The song soon lulled the old Bishop into tranquility; he had taken out his
      ivory tablets with the intention of making some such entry as this: &ldquo;Mem:
      to warn my daughter not to countenance any matrimonial proposal in respect
      of G. H. and Hilary.&rdquo; For was it not well known that Dr. Harford had
      spoken strongly against the war in Scotland&mdash;&ldquo;the Bishops&rsquo; war,&rdquo; now
      in progress&mdash;and who could tell what difficulties might arise in the
      future? But somehow, as the song proceeded, he slid into a state of dreamy
      content, and noted instead on the tablets a fresh idea for his treatise on
      the Epistle to the Colossians, which was suggested in part by the music
      and in part by the faces of Gabriel and Hilary. He looked benevolently
      across at the two young people, his mind hovering betwixt heaven and earth
      and the grievous divisions of his day all forgot.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus it chanced that through the halcyon days of that wonderful summer,
      Gabriel wooed Hilary in peace until, one morning, early in September, he
      found the present not sufficient for him, but must needs try to ensure the
      future, and hear from her own lips the promise that would set him at rest.
    </p>
    <p>
      They had been out riding with the doctor, but had found the day hot, and,
      leaving the horses with the groom, had wandered across a bit of wild
      country bordering the road, to find rest and shelter in a little wood.
      Great beech trees made a solemn shade over the russet carpet of last
      year&rsquo;s leaves, and here and there the sunbeams slanting through the
      branches turned the russet to gold and threw a silvery sheen over the
      brake fern growing around. The robins sang cheerfully overhead, and now
      and then a squirrel would dance from branch to branch scampering the
      faster as it caught sight of the two intruders resting in the shade
      beneath.
    </p>
    <p>
      The very quiet of the place made Gabriel think involuntarily of the
      strange contrast to be found in &ldquo;towered cities&rdquo; amid &ldquo;the busy hum of
      men.&rdquo; Surely never again would he find so sweet a paradise in which to
      speak his love. The audacity of his childhood filled him now with amaze.
      What would he not have given for the easy flow of words which had then
      been at his command?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This is perfection,&rdquo; said Hilary, taking off her hat and fanning herself
      leisurely with a great fern.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There is one thing wanting,&rdquo; said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are exacting,&rdquo; said Hilary, with a little rippling laugh. &ldquo;What more
      can heart desire?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A bliss that would last,&rdquo; said Gabriel, his voice trembling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah! but that is asking too much,&rdquo; she answered, musingly. &ldquo;Nothing
      lasts.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing but love,&rdquo; he said, in a tone that made her lift her eyes to his,
      and speedily drop them.
    </p>
    <p>
      The colour rushed to her face, but her confusion seemed to cheer him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hilary,&rdquo; he exclaimed, &ldquo;do you not know that I love you? You who first
      wakened love in me&mdash;who first made me truly live&mdash;surely you
      must know? I love you with all my being; only be mine&mdash;be mine.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am your friend,&rdquo; she faltered&mdash;&ldquo;have ever been your friend.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Friendship is not enough,&rdquo; he said, eagerly; &ldquo;that was for childish days,
      but now&mdash;now&mdash;it is death to me to be without you. I am yours,
      body and soul. Give me hope, Hilary; give me hope!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She raised her head and looked into his eager, hazel eyes, reading there
      the utter devotion of a first genuine passion, &ldquo;I give you my heart,&rdquo; she
      said in a voice so soft that the words seemed more breathed than spoken,
      and the robin which had been the sole spectator of this love scene
      ventured a little nearer, even as she spoke, only taking flight when
      Gabriel caught her in his arms for what seemed the first kiss he had ever
      given her, so strangely did it differ from the careless salute of their
      childhood.
    </p>
    <p>
      The robin sang overhead now, and sang so blithely that even the happy
      lovers gave heed to the song.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis the sweetest I ever heard,&rdquo; said Hilary. &ldquo;Or is it that all
      things seem more beautiful because of love?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That must be it. Hitherto we have but dreamed; now we are awake, and this
      is the joy that lasts.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      So they lived through that exquisite dawn of love, and their bliss knew no
      alloy until the ruthless groom strode into the wood.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I ha&rsquo; tethered the horses to the gibbet, sir,&rdquo; he said to Gabriel, &ldquo;and
      ha&rsquo; come to tell ye that the doctor is in sight.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The lovers started to their feet. Suddenly to see Simon&rsquo;s uncomprehending
      face; suddenly to hear the ill-omened word &ldquo;gibbet,&rdquo; roused them roughly
      enough from their paradise. They hurriedly left the little wood, not once
      even looking back, for was not Simon tramping heavily behind them, driving
      them forth into the thorns and thistles of the world just as effectually
      as if he had been the angel with the flaming sword!
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
