    <h2>
      CHAPTER IV.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      He cannot lie a perfect man
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Not being tried and tutored in the world.
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      Two Gentlemen of Verona.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">I</span>n the seventeenth
      century marriages, as a rule, were arranged in a very formal fashion by
      parents or guardians; then, after letters relating to money matters had
      passed on both sides, the young people were encouraged to meet. But the
      lifelong intimacy between Gabriel and Hilary had set ordinary customs
      aside, and before Mrs. Unett had in the least awakened to the idea that
      the old friendship had changed and developed, the morning in the wood had
      altered the whole course of her daughter&rsquo;s life.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the Palace at Hereford it chanced strangely enough that on that very
      day another matrimonial project was being discussed, for late in the
      previous evening Dr. William Coke, of Bromyard, one of Hilary&rsquo;s uncles,
      had unexpectedly arrived to see the Bishop, bringing with him a formal
      letter of proposal for the hand of his niece from one Mr. Geers, of
      Garnons, a rich squire who had long been his friend. At the precise moment
      when Gabriel was confessing his love in the uninterrupted quiet of the
      coppice, and Simon the groom shrewdly guessing as he waited at the gibbet
      that &ldquo;young maister was lommaking in the ripple,&rdquo; a grave discussion was
      going on in the Bishop&rsquo;s study.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You see, daughter,&rdquo; said the old man, persuasively, &ldquo;this proposal
      deserves consideration. Mr. Geers is a worthy man, and the settlement he
      would make is altogether satisfactory.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yet he is over old for Hilary,&rdquo; sighed the mother. &ldquo;He would wish to wed
      without delay, and how can I spare my child?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She would still be in the county,&rdquo; said her brother cheerily; &ldquo;however, I
      don&rsquo;t wish to plead for the gentleman, I am but his ambassador, not his
      advocate.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Unett looked with relief at the speaker. The parson had always been
      her favourite brother. He had appreciated her husband and had shared to a
      certain extent in his views, which had not been the case with any other
      member of the Coke family. Then, too, he was so kindly, so genial; he had
      such a keen enjoyment of life and contrived to make his antiquarian
      pursuits so extremely amusing to other people. Unlike some hobby-riders,
      he was never a bore, and to see his good-natured face beam with
      satisfaction when he discovered a treasure for his collection was a thing
      to remember. His rare visits to Hereford never failed to delight both
      Hilary and her mother.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Tell me what you advise, brother,&rdquo; said Mrs. Unett.
    </p>
    <p>
      The parson laughed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You could not appeal to a worse man,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I am an indifferent good
      judge of old oak, and know something of fossils, but of love matters I am
      as ignorant as a child of seven. It seems that worthy Mr. Geers wants a
      wife, he is not blessed as I am with the love of antiquities, and he finds
      his country mansion wondrous dull. If Hilary pines for a husband, why,
      then, I should advise you to let the gentleman woo her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am very sure she is in no haste to wed,&rdquo; said Mrs. Unett, &ldquo;she is not
      yet eighteen, and would be loth to leave her home.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear, &rsquo;tis a good offer, and should not lightly be
      disregarded,&rdquo; said the Bishop. &ldquo;In many ways it would be well that Hilary
      should be established, and her future happiness secured.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is that so easily done?&rdquo; said Dr. Coke, with a quizzical smile. &ldquo;Future
      happiness comes not with broad lands and a full purse. Perchance pretty
      Hilary would find the great mansion dull; or, again, she might, like a
      dame I once met, confess that the estate was all that could be wished, and
      that for the man&mdash;why, he was but a passing evil, and came of a
      short-lived family.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Unett smiled at his droll voice as he quoted the philosophical wife.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hilary is not made after that pattern,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Truth to tell, the
      maid has a will of her own, and is a trifle fastidious.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear,&rdquo; said the Bishop, &ldquo;she is a good, obedient maid, and if we show
      her that this arrangement is for her good, I make no doubt she will accept
      Mr. Geers&rsquo; suit.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Coke smiled at his sister&rsquo;s dubious expression.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are we so sure it is for her good?&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Let the little maid see her
      suitor and judge for herself. But I must not stay talking any longer of
      marrying and giving in marriage, for I am to visit Sir Richard Hopton at
      Canon Frome on my way home. Do you entrust me with a message to the owner
      of Garnons? He comes to stay with me to-morrow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank him for his courtesy, and say that we shall gladly receive him as a
      guest next week, if it suits his convenience,&rdquo; said the Bishop. &ldquo;The two
      had best meet as you suggest, and we shall see what time will bring
      forth.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He returned to his treatise on the Colossians, and William Coke ordered
      his horse, kissed his sister, and, noticing her wistful expression, racked
      his kindly brain for some word that would cheer her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am a doited old bachelor,&rdquo; he said, smoothing back his grizzled hair
      and adjusting his wide felt hat. &ldquo;But I somehow fancy Hilary will be in no
      haste to leave her mother for this worthy gentleman.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Unett sighed. Her voice had a mournful tone in it as she replied, &ldquo;It
      is, after all, the way of the world, and what mothers must expect.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He moved towards the door, but suddenly returned to her side with a broad
      smile on his ruddy face, and a world of fun in his twinkling eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Make yourself easy,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think she will accept him. I am
      the man&rsquo;s ambassador, but there is one trifle I had forgot&mdash;I
      honestly admit that he squints.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He rode off laughing to himself, and gave little more thought to the
      matter, for, as he had very truly remarked, love affairs were not at all
      in his line, and some interesting relics at Canon Frome drove both Hilary
      and her suitor from his mind.
    </p>
    <p>
      The poor Bishop, however, was not long allowed to dwell on the spiritual
      characteristics of the men of Colosse; for in the late afternoon Dr.
      Harford craved an audience of him, and after due apologies for Gabriel&rsquo;s
      impetuous love-making, told Hilary&rsquo;s grandfather of Mr. Unett&rsquo;s words in
      the past, and begged his consent to the union of the two old playmates.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Bishop was dismayed at the proposal, and ruefully remembered that the
      dangers of constant intercourse had struck him when Gabriel returned from
      Oxford, but that a sudden idea as to the position of &ldquo;Tychicus, a beloved
      brother and faithful minister,&rdquo; had driven out the prudent reflection. His
      treatise had prospered wonderfully that summer, but meanwhile his
      granddaughter had been free to see as much as she pleased of the
      physician&rsquo;s son.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To be frank with you, sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I have other plans for Hilary, and
      am at this moment in treaty with Mr. Geers of Garnons. But even if she
      declines his suit, I am fain to confess that a marriage with your son is
      not what I should wish for her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My lord, it was her father&rsquo;s wish,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, but times have changed since the death of my son-inlaw. We do not
      think alike, either in religion or in politics, sir; and I should hesitate
      to give my grandchild in marriage to one likely to oppose me in matters
      both of Church and State.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The lad is scarce eighteen,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford, &ldquo;and is as yet a mere
      observer of current events. He hath, I am well assured, nought but respect
      and affection for you, my lord, and his whole heart is set on wedding
      Hilary. Other proposals may be in a worldly way more desirable, but the
      children have loved each other, if I mistake not, all their lives, and &rsquo;tis
      ill meddling with hearts.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The matter shall be referred to my daughter,&rdquo; said the Bishop, rising.
      &ldquo;Personally, I have nothing against your son; on the contrary, I think him
      full of promise. But he is over young to marry, and there are many
      objections to a long betrothal.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Harford could only withdraw, and the Bishop, chafing a little at
      having to spend his time on these mundane matters, went to his daughter&rsquo;s
      house to tell her what had passed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Unett had, however, already heard Hilary&rsquo;s version of the story, and
      the thought of giving her daughter to Gabriel was so much more congenial
      to her than any notion of entertaining Mr. Geer&rsquo;s proposal, that the
      Bishop found an opponent where he had looked for an ally. After a
      prolonged discussion, Mrs. Unett&mdash;never well able to resist the
      opinion of a man&mdash;sent for her daughter by way of support, and
      Hilary, who, after telling her mother of the events of the morning, had
      gone to her own chamber to dream it all over again, came down to the
      withdrawing room in no small trepidation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Child,&rdquo; said the Bishop, &ldquo;I have had a proposal for your hand.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, my lord,&rdquo; she said, curtseying as she approached him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sit down, my dear, and let me tell you of the gentleman.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary&rsquo;s eyes widened. Was Gabriel a gentleman she needed telling about?
      She could have laughed at the notion had not good manners obliged her to
      wait dutifully for the next remark.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;His estate is very large, and is in this county; although some years your
      senior, he is still only in middle life, and will, I am assured, make you
      an excellent husband.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mother!&rdquo; gasped Hilary, in dismay. &ldquo;What does it mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your grandfather refers to an offer from Mr. Geers, of Garnons, which he
      received before that of Mr. Harford. I think, my dear, you must at least
      see the gentleman next week when he stays at the Palace.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly,&rdquo; said the Bishop, with decision. &ldquo;And I must tell you, Hilary,
      that his offer is not to be lightly refused. I cannot approve of any
      betrothal between you and Gabriel Harford, though very naturally some idle
      thoughts of love may have arisen from your being so much together.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary&rsquo;s breath came fast. There was a choking feeling in her throat,
      nothing but pride kept her from tears&mdash;pride and a determination
      that, cost what it might, she would never yield.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My lord,&rdquo; she said, quietly; &ldquo;I will certainly see Mr. Geers if it is
      your wish, but do not lead him to think that I shall accept his offer&mdash;that
      were impossible.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I very much wish you to accept the offer, but of course, I will not
      compel you, my child,&rdquo; said the Bishop. &ldquo;As to this other offer, however,
      I altogether disapprove of the notion, and I beg that you will discontinue
      all intercourse with Gabriel Harford.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My lord, he is the man my father wished me to marry,&rdquo; said Hilary. &ldquo;Does
      that count for nothing? He is the man to whom I have given my heart, does
      that weigh nought with you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a break in her voice, and a quivering of her lip as she spoke.
      The Bishop took her hand caressingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Child, you are young&mdash;you are young,&rdquo; he said, tenderly. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis
      an easy matter to let the heart go to the first handsome face and the
      first flattering tongue that appeals to you. Believe me you have not yet
      seen enough of the world to judge. Gabriel Harford has a winsome way with
      him, but he is as yet wholly unformed, you cannot tell what he will grow
      into.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I love him&mdash;and can afford to trust the future,&rdquo; said the girl,
      confidently.
    </p>
    <p>
      The old Bishop shook his head sadly; nevertheless, the depth and reality
      of Hilary&rsquo;s love had touched his heart.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let us leave it in this way,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;See no more of the young man
      while he remains in Hereford. Give Mr. Geers a fair and unprejudiced
      hearing, and let us see what time will bring forth.&rdquo; He rose to take leave
      of them, pausing at the door to counsel Mrs. Unett to send a letter
      without delay to Dr. Harford, acquainting him with their decision.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is better so, my child,&rdquo; said the mother, when once more the two were
      by themselves. &ldquo;Your grandfather is no doubt right. Gabriel is very young,
      and you cannot tell what manner of man he will be. I must write to his
      father. To do that does not rob you of all hope, it merely means that we
      must have good proof of Gabriel&rsquo;s constancy before making promises as to
      the future.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We can wait,&rdquo; said Hilary, firmly. But then she remembered the rapture of
      the morning, and the confident tone of Gabriel&rsquo;s voice, as he said: &ldquo;This
      is the joy that lasts.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Alas! How soon had their day been over-clouded! She turned aside to the
      window and looked out at the cathedral through a mist of tears, hearing
      the scratching of her mother&rsquo;s pen with a dull heartache. Presently down
      in the street below she saw a very carefully-dressed, spruce little lady,
      with grey curls and a benevolent face. It was kind-hearted Mrs. Joyce
      Jefferies, speaking to a little bare-footed lad and making him happy with
      a penny. In taking out her purse she dropped her handkerchief, and Hilary,
      running swiftly out of the room, threw open the front door and hastened to
      restore the handkerchief to its owner, The old maiden lady thanked her,
      but noticed the sad look in her eyes. &ldquo;What is amiss, child?&rdquo; she asked,
      stroking the girl&rsquo;s cheek. &ldquo;I met you riding this morning with a very
      different face.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing lasts!&rdquo; said Hilary, with tears in her voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, one thing,&rdquo; said Mrs. Joyce Jefferies, a light dawning in her kind
      eyes. &ldquo;There is an old poem in which you will find a truer saying, &lsquo;All
      goeth but Godde&rsquo;s will.&rsquo;&rdquo; The gentle little lady walked on, but although
      she said nothing, she was able to make a shrewd guess that her god-son,
      Gabriel Harford, was in some way the cause of Hilary&rsquo;s trouble, and on
      reaching her house in Widemarsh street, she penned him a note inviting him
      to dine with her one day in the next week.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary did not return to the withdrawing-room for fully half-an-hour, and
      then found that her mother was only just folding the formal letter, which
      had been hard to write. &ldquo;May I enclose this to Gabriel, ma&rsquo;am?&rdquo; said the
      girl, putting a tiny sealed packet on the table.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do not think your grandfather would approve of a correspondence between
      you,&rdquo; said Mrs. Unett, hesitating.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis not a letter&mdash;I will show it to you, if you wish,
      mother.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The mother looked up into the dark eyes, saw the traces of tears, and
      forgot the Bishop&rsquo;s prudent objections.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will send it, child,&rdquo; she said, kissing her tenderly. &ldquo;Do not think
      that I have forgot my own young days. And bear not so sad a face, Hilary,
      for I have great confidence in Gabriel, and would spare you to him in the
      future, more willingly than to any other man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary&rsquo;s face lighted up at these comfortable words. Surely time would
      prove to everyone&rsquo;s satisfaction that they were indeed well suited to each
      other.
    </p>
    <p>
      To fill up the hours of waiting Gabriel had gone out fishing, and when the
      light failed he lay on the bank of the river watching the dark trees as
      they stood out russet, grey and purple against the mellow evening sky,
      their heavy summer foliage hardly moving, so still was the air. All the
      world seemed beautiful, and he was far too happy to have any doubts. What
      could stand in his way when Hilary herself had owned her love? Not all the
      bishops in England could really interfere between them! And over and over
      in his mind there rang her softly spoken words, &ldquo;I give you my heart.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      By this time surely his father&rsquo;s visit to the palace would be well over,
      and the consent won? He sprang to his feet, shouldered his rod, and, with
      a glance at the fish he had caught, closed the basket, resolving to carry
      it to old Durdle, the housekeeper, for Mrs. Unett&rsquo;s breakfast.
    </p>
    <p>
      As he walked through the fields he whistled, &ldquo;Phyllis on the New Mown
      Hay,&rdquo; for sheer light-heartedness, and had some difficulty in pacing
      gravely through the streets when he reached the city. Old Nat, the sailor,
      meeting him in High Town, noticed his blithe face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good e&rsquo;en to you, sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;you&rsquo;re looking piert and heartful. Have
      ye had good luck?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay!&rdquo; he replied, &ldquo;it has been a lucky day with me. Look!&rdquo; and he opened
      the basket. &ldquo;You must have one of these fellows for your supper.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With a cheery &ldquo;Good night!&rdquo; he passed on, leaving the old sailor divided
      between admiration of the trout and its donor.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Takes after his father, he does,&rdquo; muttered the old man, &ldquo;an open hand and
      a good heart. But it&rsquo;ll go hard with him in times like these, for he&rsquo;s
      independent, and none too fond of knocking under to great folk.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Twilight reigned in the house when Gabriel closed the front door behind
      him, but a streak of lamp-light came from the region of the study-door,
      and on entering the room he found his father and mother gravely discussing
      an open letter. Something in their faces struck a chill to his heart.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did you see the Bishop, sir?&rdquo; he asked, eagerly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sit down, lad,&rdquo; said the doctor, pointing to a chair by the table which
      his patients were wont to occupy while he interviewed them. &ldquo;Yes, I saw
      him; our talk was not satisfactory. Still, I would not have you lose heart
      altogether.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The reaction from the morning was too great, however. Gabriel turned
      deathly white; he could not frame his lips to the question he longed, yet
      dreaded to put. The pain carried him back curiously to a former scene in
      that very room, when in an agony of nervous anticipation he had waited for
      the hot iron to be put on his mangled arm, and again he seemed to hear the
      words: &ldquo;Nothing could daunt Sir John Eliot; cost what it might, he was
      ever true!&rdquo; With an effort he pulled himself together.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;May I hear, sir, what actually passed?&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      And the doctor hastened to tell him all, then placed Mrs. Unett&rsquo;s letter
      in his hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was a kind, incoherent, weak letter, but Gabriel saw with relief that
      the writer did not at all favour the suit of Mr. Geers of Garnons. His
      mother, however, quickly dispelled what little consolation he had gained.
      There had never been much love lost between the two ladies.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never mind, my son,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;In my opinion, you are very well out of
      the whole affair. Hilary is an only daughter, and has been spoilt and
      indulged by an over-fond parent, till she thinks everything must give way
      to her whims. Depend upon it, she would have been ill to live with.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will wed none other,&rdquo; said Gabriel, passionately, and, finding the
      discussion intolerable, he rose to go.
    </p>
    <p>
      The doctor put a little packet into his hand. &ldquo;It is for you,&rdquo; he said.
      &ldquo;Courage, lad! After all, the Bishop can but enforce a certain time of
      waiting on you if you are true to each other.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The words carried some comfort with them, and hope rose again in his heart
      as he strode hurriedly through the garden to the south walk, where he
      eagerly opened the packet directed to him in Hilary&rsquo;s somewhat laboured
      handwriting. The moon had just risen, and by its soft light he saw a curl
      of dark hair tied with a narrow ribbon, on which some letters were traced.
      With no little difficulty he made out the motto, &ldquo;All goeth but Godde&rsquo;s
      will.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The message brought him fresh courage. It seemed to put everything in a
      true light. After all, what were differences of opinion on religious
      matters when words such as these could be their mutual comfort? He had
      never troubled to think whether they differed or not. The mere fact that
      the Bishop was one of the Laudian prelates, and that his father objected
      to the tendency to revert to Medivalism in the English Church, could not
      surely affect the question of his marriage with Hilary? It was sheer
      nonsense to think that such a thing could part them when they were united
      already by love, and by trust in the Divine will, which could not fail.
      So, although he was sore-hearted and downcast, he was far from hopeless,
      and after a while was ready to throw himself with ardour into his father&rsquo;s
      plans for his future.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
