    <h2>
      CHAPTER XIII
    </h2>
    <p class="indent20">
      &ldquo;But I am ty&rsquo;d to very thee
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      By ev&rsquo;ry thought I have;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Thy face I only care to see,
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      Thy heart I only crave.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p class="indent40">
      Sedley.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">I</span>n an hour&rsquo;s time
      the preparations were made, and, furnished with a pass from Waller, the
      two friends, with Morrison, Captain Heyworth&rsquo;s servant, in attendance,
      rode through the sleeping city and, after a brief delay at the gate,
      passed out into the open country.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel forgot his fatigue in the excitement of this unexpected quest. The
      night was very still, and little fleecy white clouds floated in the
      moonlit sky; he began keenly to enjoy the prospect of thwarting Colonel
      Norton, whose brutal words to Major Locke had stirred up in him a
      resentment which was all the fiercer because he had at first been deceived
      by the pleasant voice and the buoyant cheerfulness of their visitor. Here
      was a man who might easily enough betray a young and ignorant girl. He
      could fancy only too well how Hilary would have been attracted by this
      light-hearted officer, with his ready smile and his merry-looking eyes;
      and the thought made him all the more eager to rescue little Helena Locke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has the Major only this one child?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay,&rdquo; replied Joscelyn Heyworth, &ldquo;&rsquo;tis a case of
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      &lsquo;One fair daughter and no more,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The which he loved passing well.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      She inherits the estate, and doubtless Colonel Norton has an eye to that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They had ridden for some two hours, when Gabriel pointed to a tower darkly
      outlined against the pale sky. &ldquo;Yonder lies the church,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We take
      this turning to the right. What is that ahead? Surely I saw a light
      through the trees.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Corpse candles in the churchyard, maybe,&rdquo; said Joscelyn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, &rsquo;twas not near the church, but yonder. See, &rsquo;tis a
      light in a cottage; &rsquo;tis the gatehouse of the Manor.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;All the better,&rdquo; said Joscelyn, &ldquo;they will be ready to open to us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Without replying, Gabriel dismounted and looked closely at the marks on
      the road near the gate. &ldquo;A couple of horsemen have just entered, I should
      say by these hoof-prints,&rdquo; he exclaimed. And picking up a pebble he threw
      it against the lighted window of the gate-house.
    </p>
    <p>
      Immediately the door of the lodge was cautiously opened, and an old
      white-haired man put out his head. &ldquo;Who goes there?&rdquo; he cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We have a message from your master, Major Locke, and have ridden in haste
      from Gloucester,&rdquo; said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      The old man, looking much perturbed, took up his lantern and came out to
      the gate. &ldquo;Why, that be strange,&rdquo; he said, scratching his head, as he
      noted the orange scarves with which their buff coats were girt, &ldquo;you bring
      a message from master at Gloucester, and but ten minutes since I let in
      two gentlemen who brought a message from him at Little Dean, where they
      tell me he lies wounded and a prisoner.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Was the messenger you admitted Colonel Norton?&rdquo; asked Joscelyn Heyworth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, &rsquo;twas young Squire Norton that lives over at Crawleigh Park;
      known master all his life he has, and was willing to show him a kindness
      and take Mistress Helena to him ere he die.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Man,&rdquo; said Gabriel, impatiently, &ldquo;&rsquo;tis all a pack of lies. We
      serve under Major Locke and have left him but now in sound health at
      Gloucester; he knows that Colonel Norton means to entrap his daughter,
      and, being unable to come, has sent us to escort her safely to Alderman
      Pury&rsquo;s house. Here is a letter for her in your master&rsquo;s own hand if you
      doubt me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The old man raised the lantern, but his eyes were fixed on Gabriel&rsquo;s face,
      not on the letter. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t read writing,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;but the Almighty&rsquo;s
      given me some skill in reading faces, and yours, sir, has truth in every
      line. I blame myself for trusting young Squire Norton, but the news that
      the master was at death&rsquo;s door dithered me, and that&rsquo;s a fact.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let us lose no time,&rdquo; said Gabriel, eagerly. &ldquo;Will Colonel Norton have
      been long at the house?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, sir; for it will take my son, who went with him, a bit of a time to
      rouse the household. Belike they may be still outside.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good; then let us leave the horses without the gate in charge of
      Morrison,&rdquo; said Joscelyn Heyworth, &ldquo;and do you guide us to the house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We must steal in without noise,&rdquo; said Gabriel, quickly, &ldquo;and, if
      possible, convey Mistress Helena away before Colonel Norton sees her.
      Where does that light come from?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It be in the window of the dining-hall,&rdquo; said the gatekeeper, keeping up
      with the two young officers by means of a shambling trot, which made his
      words come in a series of jerks and gasps. &ldquo;But as sure as my name&rsquo;s Amos
      I don&rsquo;t see how you are to get speech of Mistress Helena now that Squire
      Norton has the start of you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will see how the land lies,&rdquo; said Gabriel, lowering his voice as they
      drew near to the house. &ldquo;Should Colonel Norton be in the hall you can
      surely convey us upstairs without his knowledge?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll do my best, sir, but &rsquo;twill be a difficult matter,&rdquo; said
      Amos.
    </p>
    <p>
      They were walking, not on the carriage road, but over the bowling-green,
      and Gabriel now hastened noiselessly forward, and, swinging himself up by
      a sturdy little hawthorn which grew close to the house, he looked
      anxiously into the hall. It was a great, bare place, wainscotted with
      black oak, and lighted only by a couple of candles. A flagon of wine stood
      on the long, narrow table in the centre, and the visitors were refreshing
      themselves after their long ride. The Prince&rsquo;s messenger had his back to
      the window, and little was visible of him but his long dark lovelocks.
      Norton, at the opposite side of the table, lay back in a carved
      elbow-chair, a silver cup in his shapely hand, and the candle light full
      on his handsome, reckless face.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel saw at a glance that the hall was constructed on the usual plan of
      mediaeval houses, with a minstrels&rsquo; gallery at the end nearest the outer
      door of the mansion, and beneath the gallery two open archways leading
      through the wooden screen to a passage traversing the house from front to
      back. Across one of the archways hung a thick crimson curtain, but the
      archway nearest the main door was exposed to view, the curtain having
      evidently been half drawn back on the arrival of the midnight guests.
    </p>
    <p>
      He dropped down noiselessly from his post of observation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The two of them are in there drinking,&rdquo; he said, in a whisper. &ldquo;Mistress
      Helena hath not yet come down. Is there any means of reaching her by the
      stairs leading to the gallery?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, sir, the little stone stair leads up to the gallery, and on beyond to
      the upper rooms,&rdquo; whispered Amos, his shrewd old face lighting up as he
      began to hope for a successful issue.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good; then let us off with our boots, and steal through to the gallery
      stairs without a sound.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Amos stepped out of his broad low-heeled shoes easily enough, but the high
      riding-boots and spurs of the two young knights proved a more difficult
      matter, and Joscelyn Heyworth waxed so merry over their struggles that
      they came perilously near to an audible laugh. Their preparations made,
      the gatekeeper led the way up the steps to the main entrance, softly
      opened the door and admitted them into a flagged passage; a broad stream
      of light fell athwart the white stones from the archway on the right
      leading into the hall; they paused a moment before advancing, and to their
      relief heard that Norton and his companion were talking&mdash;under cover
      of their voices it would be easier to risk the perilous crossing to the
      stairs.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This fair damsel takes a great deal of rousing,&rdquo; said the Prince&rsquo;s
      messenger. &ldquo;Doth she intend to make a full toilette before coming down to
      hear of her father&rsquo;s plight?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We won&rsquo;t grudge her time to doff her nightcap,&rdquo; said Norton, &ldquo;for i&rsquo;
      faith, Tom, she hath the prettiest golden locks you ever saw. What shall I
      tell her of the old Major&rsquo;s wound? Shot through the lungs, eh? Life hangs
      on a thread? By the Lord Harry! I only wish it did,&rdquo; and he laughed
      boisterously.
    </p>
    <p>
      Taking advantage of this noise, Gabriel put his hand on old Amos&rsquo; arm and
      walked swiftly past the archway, and on beyond to the spiral staircase
      which lay concealed behind a door in the wainscot.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What&rsquo;s that?&rdquo; exclaimed Norton, &ldquo;I thought I saw a shadow in the
      passage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Patience, man,&rdquo; said the other. &ldquo;&rsquo;Twas doubtless the fellow that
      let us in. I faith I begin to think your love for this pretty maid is
      hotter than most of your fancies. She will come all in good time; I drink
      to the success of your enterprise!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And I drink to fair Mistress Nell, the Queen of my heart!&rdquo; said Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      He refilled his silver cup, and the three rescuers stole quietly up the
      dark staircase. Hardly, however, had they reached the level of the gallery
      when an exclamation from Norton crushed their hopes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And here in good sooth she comes!&rdquo; he said, as sounds of approaching
      footsteps made themselves heard, and a flickering light began to play on
      the dark oak wainscot at the further end of the hall near the entrance to
      the main staircase.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel signed to his companions to pause on the spiral steps, and going
      down on his hands and knees crept cautiously into the gallery, which lay
      in deep shadow, but commanded an excellent view of the hall between the
      posts of the massive oak balustrade. He clenched his hands in hot anger
      when he saw how young and innocent and helpless was Norton&rsquo;s victim.
    </p>
    <p>
      She came into the hall bearing a silver candlestick, and the flickering
      light revealed a face of childlike beauty, the cheeks still flushed with
      the sudden awakening from sound sleep, the blue eyes wide with anxiety and
      alarm. She had hurriedly thrown on a pink flannel sacque, and her fair
      hair hung in disorder about her shoulders. Norton stood still for a moment
      feasting his eyes on her loveliness, then he noticed that close behind her
      came a certain poor relation who had lived for many years at the Manor, a
      worthy lady of fifty, known as Cousin Malvina.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I grieve to be the bearer of ill news,&rdquo; he said, saluting both ladies
      with great courtesy.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, sir, tell me all, and tell me quickly. How doth my father?&rdquo; asked
      little Mistress Nell, her pretty eyes filling with tears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay,&rdquo; said Norton, &ldquo;be not so distressed. He was sorely wounded to-day in
      a skirmish&mdash;you may doubtless have heard that Sir William Waller cut
      his way right through Prince Maurice&rsquo;s army in the forest; your father is
      now our prisoner, and lies at the Prince&rsquo;s headquarters at Little Dean. If
      you will don your riding-gear at once I will have a pillion put on my
      horse and take you to him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; said Cousin Malvina, &ldquo;it is out of the question that Helena should
      go with you now. You must wait till morning, then I will bring her in the
      coach.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dear madam, by morning it will be too late; her father lies at death&rsquo;s
      door, and he himself implored me to bring her to him without delay. Can
      you not trust an old neighbour?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You were a neighbour that my kinsman sorely distrusted,&rdquo; said Cousin
      Malvina, her grave face bearing an expression of great perplexity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But much is changed when we have but a short time to live,&rdquo; said Norton,
      unblushingly. &ldquo;Come, madam, let bygones be bygones. You shall ride to
      Little Dean with us behind my friend.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dear Cousin Malvina, pray do not hinder us,&rdquo; said Helena, eagerly.
      &ldquo;Perhaps with good nursing we may yet save my father&rsquo;s life. Come, let us
      go upstairs and dress. Come, please, come!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The good lady was overpersuaded, and Norton, adjuring them to lose no
      time, accompanied them to the foot of the great staircase with so many
      signs of respect and kindly sympathy that Gabriel was fain to own him the
      cleverest as well as the most audacious villain he had ever encountered.
    </p>
    <p>
      Creeping noiselessly back to the dim spiral stairs he begged Joscelyn
      Heyworth to keep a watch on Norton&rsquo;s doings while Amos took him to the
      other floor to speak to the two ladies. The old gate-keeper, who was
      trembling with rage and excitement, whispered an assurance that he would
      return to Captain Heyworth when their plans were formed, and then led
      Gabriel to Mistress Malvina&rsquo;s room. The ladies had not yet returned, for
      the main staircase and the corridors made a much wider circuit.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You wait, sir, and I&rsquo;ll prepare them,&rdquo; said Amos, stealing along the
      passage, carrying his shoes in one hand, and raising a warning forefinger
      as little Mistress Nell approached.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hush, missie,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Yon wicked young Squire Norton has deceived you;
      here is a gentleman who hath brought you a letter from my master.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did I not tell you, child, that your father ever mistrusted Squire
      Norton?&rdquo; said Cousin Malvina, triumphantly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Helena, looking utterly bewildered, allowed Amos to usher her into the
      room where Gabriel stood waiting her approach. She lifted up her candle
      the better to see him, and something in his clear honest eyes brought her
      instant relief.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; she exclaimed, &ldquo;Amos says my father sent you hither.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, madam,&rdquo; he said, bowing low and handing her the Major&rsquo;s letter. &ldquo;You
      will recognise his handwriting, and pray read this quickly, for if we are
      to save you from Colonel Norton&rsquo;s vile plot we must lose no time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Read, child,&rdquo; said Cousin Malvina, &ldquo;and let us know at once what your
      father bids you do.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel took the candle from the girl&rsquo;s trembling hand, and held it for
      her while she read aloud the Major&rsquo;s brief note.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dear Daughter,&mdash;This letter is borne to you by Lieutenant Harford,
      who is accompanied by his friend, Captain Heyworth. I am unable to fetch
      you myself, but you must ride with them without a minute&rsquo;s delay to
      Gloucester, where Alderman Pury will shelter you. We have learnt of a
      probable attack to be made by the Prince&rsquo;s troops on the Manor; do not let
      the servants attempt a defence, it will be useless. A worse danger
      threatens you yourself from that vile profligate, Squire Norton. I had
      thought him safely disposed of during the war, but since he is in your
      neighbourhood, I dare not leave you at the Manor. Come at once to
      Gloucester, or I shall not have a moment&rsquo;s peace of mind. I shall be gone
      to the attack of Tewkesbury when you arrive, but Lieutenant Harford will
      place you safely under Alderman Pury&rsquo;s care. May God direct you.&mdash;Your
      loving father,
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Christopher Locke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Written at Gloucester, this evening, April 11, 1643.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is there a third staircase in the house?&rdquo; asked Gabriel, turning to Amos.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, sir, there be the kitchen stairs, but they be plaguy steep and apt to
      creak.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They are further from the hall,&rdquo; said little Mistress Nell, &ldquo;and we can
      slip out of the back door and through the shrubbery to the gate ere Squire
      Norton thinks us ready. Haste, haste, Cousin Malvina, here is your Lincoln
      green cloak and hood, do not let us lose a moment.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Summon Captain Heyworth,&rdquo; said Gabriel to Amos, &ldquo;and if possible get a
      couple of pillions, we will meet you by the back entrance. I will guard
      your door, ladies, while you don your wraps, but pray lose no time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He stood without in the corridor, each minute seeming agelong in the
      darkness and silence. Presently a faint sound of stealthy steps at a
      little distance warned him that Joscelyn and the gatekeeper were moving
      towards the back staircase, then came silence, broken only by the low
      tones of Mistress Malvina&rsquo;s agitated voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      At length, when his patience was well nigh exhausted,
    </p>
    <p>
      Helena in a long blue cloak and a close Puritan hood, opened the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We are ready, sir,&rdquo; she whispered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Can you find your way down in the dark?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      She nodded, blew out the candle, and with a child&rsquo;s ready confidence
      slipped her hand into his.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Take care,&rdquo; she said, beneath her breath, &ldquo;there are little steps up and
      down in this corridor, two up here, now one down, now turn to the left and
      tread softly, there are twenty-six stairs&mdash;very steep ones. Don&rsquo;t
      forget, Cousin Malvina, that the twenty-fourth step creaks.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Silently and with infinite care they went down the long descent, thankful
      for a gleam of moonlight from the window of the house-keeper&rsquo;s room down
      below. But, alas! Cousin Malvina, half paralysed with terror as they heard
      Norton&rsquo;s voice in the hall, lost count of the steps.
    </p>
    <p>
      The twenty-fourth stair creaked ominously as she trod on it, and the next
      moment to their horror, Norton&rsquo;s voice grew louder and clearer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They are coming at last!&rdquo; he exclaimed. &ldquo;I hear steps in the passage.
      What! no lights? Curse those servants! Why can&rsquo;t they bring a lamp? Hullo!
      who goes there? a petticoat an I mistake not. Tom, bring one of those
      candles; here&rsquo;s sport to pass the time of waiting.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Unluckily, as Norton&rsquo;s eyes grew more accustomed to the semi-darkness, he
      caught sight of three people rapidly crossing a patch of moonlight in the
      kitchen. He hurried forward, and was just in time to sec the little group
      of dusky figures stealing out of the house. Then the door closed behind
      them, and though he pulled with all his might at the handle, he could not
      make it yield, for Joscelyn Heyworth held on to it like grim death.
    </p>
    <p>
      Meanwhile, Gabriel had hurriedly pulled on his boots, and was
      half-leading, half-carrying, little Mistress Nell through the dark
      shrubbery, while Amos panted after him with Mistress Malvina.
    </p>
    <p>
      When Joscelyn rejoined them, the poor chaperon seemed almost at her last
      gasp, and the sound of Norton&rsquo;s steps gaining upon them took all the
      strength from her limbs.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Take a turn to the right and double back to the house with the lady,&rdquo;
       said Joscelyn; &ldquo;you will outwit them thus, and can ride later on to
      Gloucester.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It was no time to hesitate. Amos blindly obeyed, and dragged Mistress
      Malvina into the depths of the shrubbery, where she sank on to the ground
      unable to take another step, but listening in terrible anxiety to hear
      what would happen.
    </p>
    <p>
      Joscelyn, running like the wind, overtook his companions, and caught
      Helena&rsquo;s other hand in his, then, leaving the shrubbery, the fugitives
      rushed across the bowling-green. The moon shone only too brightly, but
      they were forced to risk shots from behind, for to drag the girl along the
      narrow half-overgrown path proved slow work, and their capture would have
      been certain.
    </p>
    <p>
      Surely Norton would hesitate to shoot. His feelings as a gentleman would
      probably be stronger than the savage lust of conquest, and the brute
      instincts which had prompted him to this night&rsquo;s work.
    </p>
    <p>
      But they had yet to learn his character; as long as his mind was fully
      bent on any desire, nothing could baffle him.
    </p>
    <p>
      A bullet whistled through the air, missing Joscelyn Hey-worth only by a
      hair&rsquo;s breadth. Little Nell gripped the hands of her rescuers with the
      intensity of one whose nerves are strained to the utmost, but otherwise
      she made no sign, and ran bravely on. A second bullet followed, but it
      glanced aside from Gabriel&rsquo;s corslet. Helena felt the shock of it in the
      hand which he grasped, and a stifled cry of horror escaped her. Had not
      her two protectors borne her on more and more swiftly she felt that she
      must have given up, and have thrown herself on Squire Norton&rsquo;s mercy.
    </p>
    <p>
      But now at last they were nearing the lodge, and, to their relief, at the
      sound of their approach, Morrison threw open the gate for them. Gabriel
      hastily mounted his horse and bade the man lift little Mistress Nell in
      front of him, for the pillions had been left with Amos in the shrubbery,
      and he dared not let her ride behind, when at any moment Norton or his
      companion might again shoot.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;ll take the gentlemen a few minutes to find their horses,&rdquo; said
      Morrison, lifting the trembling girl in front of Gabriel. &ldquo;They&rsquo;d left
      them on the other side of the gatehouse, and I&rsquo;ve put &rsquo;em down by
      yon pollard willow, and hobbled their hind legs with a bit of rope in a
      way that will make their riders swear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He chuckled softly to himself, and glanced at his master, who laughed
      outright as he mounted.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;re worth your weight in gold to me,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We shall baffle this
      villain yet, Gabriel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And setting spurs to their horses, the little cavalcade started at a sharp
      trot, which changed as soon as they heard sounds of pursuit, to a gallop.
      When at length they drew rein for a moment to breathe their panting
      horses, all was still, and it became clear that Norton and his companion
      had abandoned the chase.
    </p>
    <p>
      Joscelyn Heyworth glanced at the little slender figure which clung so
      closely to his comrade; in the moonlight her girlish face looked pale, but
      absolutely tranquil, and in her eyes he could read perfect trust in her
      rescuer. He felt convinced, that ere long such confidence would develop in
      the girl&rsquo;s heart into the utter devotion of love.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now, an&rsquo; my friend could but rid his heart of old memories, and forget
      that Mistress Hilary he raved about at Kineton in his fever, here is as
      winsome and sweet a bride for him as man could desire,&rdquo; thought Joscelyn.
    </p>
    <p>
      But Gabriel&rsquo;s expression was grave, and his eyes had an absent look in
      them. He paid very little heed to the Major&rsquo;s daughter when once assured
      of her safety and comfort, for the clasp of her arms about his neck only
      made him crave Hilary&rsquo;s presence the more, and he was dreaming his own
      dream of how one day it might be his happy fortune to rescue her from some
      deadly peril or save her from the machinations of such a man as Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
