    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXIV.
    </h2>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>To say kings are accountable to none but God, is the overturning of
      all law and government. For if they may refuse to give account, then all
      covenants made with them at coronation, all oaths are in vain, and mere
      mockeries; all laws which they swear to keep, made to no purpose.
      Aristotle, whom we commonly allow for one of the best interpreters of
      nature and morality writes that &lsquo;monarchy unaccountable is the worst sort
      of tyranny, and least of all to be endured by free-born men.&rsquo;&rdquo;</i>&mdash;Milton.
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>owards Christmas
      the fever abated, but the sufferings of the prisoners from the intense
      cold were very great. Gabriel, whose vigorous youth had hitherto withstood
      better than the rest the rigours of the life in the Castle, began now to
      show signs of all the long vigils he had kept with the sick and the dying,
      and Sandy, who was really fond of him, watched him with wistful eyes,
      feeling sure that he would before long succumb.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was not until Christmas Eve that Aaron&rsquo;s threat of filling up the gaps
      was fulfilled. Then, about two o&rsquo;clock in the afternoon the door was flung
      open and the gaoler pushed in a young, active-looking man, dressed in
      mourning attire which had evidently seen hard service.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good-day to you, gentlemen,&rdquo; he said, pleasantly. &ldquo;I am sorry to add to
      your number, and fear you will scarcely welcome a new-comer.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;On the contrary, sir,&rdquo; said Rawlyns of Marlborough, &ldquo;though sorry for the
      evil plight you find yourself in, we are right glad to welcome any visitor
      who can give us news.&rdquo; Gabriel made room on his bench for the new-comer,
      looking with a sense of relief at the well-clad figure, and at the
      refreshing cleanliness of his ruddy face and well-kept light-brown hair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are a prisoner of war, sir?&rdquo; he inquired, doubtfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Pon my life! I know not what I am,&rdquo; said the visitor. &ldquo;Save that I am
      one Humphrey Neal, burnt out of house and home at Chinnor last summer by
      the Royalists, and since then a wanderer. To-day, having business to see
      to in Oxford I rode into the city, and was promptly arrested as a spy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you for the Parliament?&rdquo; asked Rawlyns.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, sir, I have never meddled with matters of State, and have thought
      more of hawking and hunting than of politics; but it is true that since
      the wanton destruction of my house, the robbery of all my live stock, and
      the devastation of my crops I bear no good-will to the Royalists.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I heard of the burning of the village of Chinnor from my friend, Captain
      Heyworth,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;It was, if I remember right, on the night before
      Colonel Hampden got his death-wound at Chalgrove Field.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, you are a friend of Captain Heyworth,&rdquo; said Humphrey Neal. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis
      a small world, where we are for ever coming across unlooked-for
      connections. Your friend hath lately wedded a pretty kinswoman of mine,
      heiress to Sir Robert Neal, of Katterliam Court House.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel&rsquo;s face lighted up.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have heard naught of him since the battle of Lansdown, when we knew
      that he was grievously wounded. He recovered then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, he not only recovered, but served all through the siege of
      Gloucester, and as I say, wedded my cousin. I saw her at Katterham but a
      se&rsquo;nnight since.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And met her husband also?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, he had rejoined Sir William Waller, and was at Farnham, and by this
      time will most like be laying siege to Arundel Castle, which had been
      seized by my Lord Hopton.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir Ralph Hopton has been raised to the peerage, then?&rdquo; said Gabriel,
      remembering vividly his last sight of the Royalist general when he had
      saved him from bleeding to death after the explosion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, the King was anxious, they say, to show him some mark of favour to
      make up for the scurvy fashion in which Prince Rupert treated him at
      Bristol.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We have heard little of the outer world,&rdquo; said Gabriel, &ldquo;save some
      account of the fight at Newbury.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Belike you have not heard, then, of the death of Mr. Pym?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a suppressed exclamation of grief and dismay through the room,
      for in the death of the great Parliamentary Leader they all knew that the
      country had sustained an irreparable loss. Great soldiers were left to
      them, but the greatest statesman of the age had passed away.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He had been failing throughout the autumn, and died of an internal
      abscess the eighth night of this month,&rdquo; said Humphrey Neal. &ldquo;In company
      with my kinsman, Sir Robert, I was present at his funeral in King Henry
      VII.&lsquo;s chapel at Westminster&mdash;a great gathering it was, too, the
      Lords and Commons, the Assembly of Divines, and a host of people besides
      being there.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perchance your presence there was noted by some of the King&rsquo;s spies, and
      may account for your arrest to-day,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;Your kinsman, Sir
      Robert Neal, hath all his life opposed the Court party.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is true. Years ago he was imprisoned for refusing to pay one of the
      loans which the King illegally enforced, and hath ever since been a marked
      man. Doubtless, that explains the matter. What are the chances of escape
      here?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The only hope would be through Sandy, the half-witted lad who helps the
      gaoler,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;He hath a curious liking for me, which might prove
      of use. Otherwise, I see no possible way, though I have made many plans to
      wile away the time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The advent of this fresh, vigorous, well-fed man seemed to raise the
      spirits of all the half-starved prisoners, and Christmas Day found them
      almost cheerful. The friendly robin had never afforded them more
      amusement, and they were so intent on showing off his many tricks and
      accomplishments to Humphrey Neal that they never noticed the entrance of
      Aaron the gaoler. It was too late to conceal the bird, and certain that
      the brutal fellow would, if possible, kill it, Gabriel deliberately let it
      fly, and with satisfaction watched it perch on one of the rafters.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What mischief are you hatching?&rdquo; said Aaron, angrily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We did but watch a bird that hath harboured here,&rdquo; said Gabriel, watching
      the robin rather apprehensively as it flew about overhead. Aaron made
      ineffectual efforts to reach it with his rod, growing more surly with each
      failure.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Drat the bird,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t waste my time over it; but you can
      spend your Christmas in the sport of taking its life, and I shall expect
      you to hand it over to me when I next come in.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel made no reply, but secretly resolved to let the bird out of the
      window rather than place it in the hands of the gaoler. Aaron turned to
      vent his ill-humour on Humphrey Neal.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And as for you, sir, you&rsquo;d better make the most of this day, for &rsquo;tis
      like to be your last. We give spies short shrift in Oxford.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am no spy,&rdquo; said Humphrey, indignantly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Men say that the gentleman that journeyed from London t&rsquo;other day had
      only come on a matter of business about moneys due to him; but the
      Governor of Oxford, Sir Arthur Aston, had him racked nathless and hung him
      the day after,&rdquo; said Aaron, with a chuckle.
    </p>
    <p>
      Humphrey muttered an imprecation and turned away.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whereupon Aaron burst into a fit of laughter.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;d better have a care, sir, your fellow-prisoners don&rsquo;t allow profane
      words, and come from the ranks where twelve-pence is the fine for every
      oath. Oh, yes, I know you well, you dogs. And pray where is now your God,
      you Roundhead rogues? You prayed to the Lord to deliver you, and you see
      how He hath delivered you, ye rebels!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The prisoners maintained a resolute silence, but Gabriel&rsquo;s heart was
      cheered when, as if in reply to the taunt, the robin overhead burst into a
      song full of hope and glad confidence.
    </p>
    <p>
      The daily dole of food having been left, Aaron and Sandy withdrew, and the
      prisoners spent the greater part of the morning in discussing the
      possibility of escape for the newcomer, whose life was evidently in
      danger. About noon Gabriel reluctantly fed the tame robin for the last
      time, then climbing with Humphrey&rsquo;s aid up to the narrow, deeply splayed
      window, he let the bird out into the open, and with a sad heart watched it
      fly away over the snowy country.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I see the mill stream is frozen,&rdquo; he said, scrambling down again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Would the ice bear, think you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, the frost hath held these four days past,&rdquo; said Humphrey. &ldquo;But we
      can scarce look for skating,&rdquo; and he laughed forlornly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yet if we could only get hold of Sandy without Aaron, I think we might
      prevail on him to let you pass&mdash;and then to find the Castle ditch
      frozen might make all the difference to you. There is sure to be feasting
      among the guard on Christmas Day, and the watch will not be strictly
      kept.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why should you not all make a bold push for freedom?&rdquo; said Humphrey.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What, forty of us at one time?&rdquo; said Gabriel, his breath coming fast.
      &ldquo;Oh! if we could but do it! Yet I doubt most of the prisoners are overweak
      with illness and starvation. And then again all would hinge on Sandy&rsquo;s
      coming again ere night, and coming alone, which doth not often happen.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Nevertheless the matter was generally discussed, and though some were
      absolutely hopeless, others thought it might possibly be carried through.
      The lawyer was not among the sanguine ones, however.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are young, you are young,&rdquo; he said to Gabriel. &ldquo;Mr. Neal merely plans
      what is the first thought of every prisoner. I made such schemes myself
      once, but they availed naught Do me the favour, sir, to lend to me one of
      your books that I may solace myself with reading till the light fails.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel, somewhat damped by his friend&rsquo;s words, produced the little 12mo
      copy of the earliest edition of Owen Felltham&rsquo;s &ldquo;Resolves,&rdquo; which Falkland
      had given him, then again withdrew to his bench to talk with Humphrey
      Neal.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the afternoon, a little before sunset, the door was suddenly yet
      stealthily opened. Gabriel looked up hopefully, for sure enough Sandy
      appeared, but the next moment the unwelcome sight of Aaron close at his
      heels robbed him of all hope. The fellow had evidently been drinking, and
      was in his most dangerous humour.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now then, you rogues, hand over the bird,&rdquo; he said, glancing round the
      ward and eyeing the lawyer with special suspicion, for he had not failed
      to note that his hand had hastily sought his pocket. Gabriel stood up.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The bird is not here it has flown away these two hours or more.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You lie, you dog. I saw that traitor from Marlborough conceal it as I
      entered.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The bird has gone, we all saw it go,&rdquo; maintained the other prisoners
      unanimously.
    </p>
    <p>
      Aaron was not, however, to be convinced. He pounced on the lawyer, dragged
      the coat from his back, and plunging his dirty hands into the pockets drew
      forth&mdash;not, indeed, the bird&mdash;but Falkland&rsquo;s little book.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You dare to conceal books against the Provost-Marshal&rsquo;s rule!&rdquo; he
      exclaimed. &ldquo;You shall be soundly beaten for this, you numskull.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      But Gabriel, unable to bear the thought of such a punishment for the
      haggard and wan invalid who had but lately recovered from the fever,
      strode forward.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The book is mine,&rdquo; he said, deliberately taking it from the gaoler and
      boldly thrusting it into his pocket. This, as he had foreseen, wholly
      diverted the furious Aaron from the lawyer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis yours, is it?&rdquo; he cried, tearing off Gabriel&rsquo;s doublet, and
      with one vigorous pull splitting in half his ragged shirt. &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve tried
      the hangman&rsquo;s whip, you Roundhead rogue, and we will see now if a sound
      drubbing from my rod will tame you. Ho! Sandy! give me your broad back for
      a whipping post, and if you don&rsquo;t hold this vile traitor&rsquo;s wrists fast,
      I&rsquo;ll flog you to a jelly yourself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Sandy slouched forward whimpering and reluctant, yet not daring to disobey
      his tyrant. A sob rose in his throat as he felt the prisoner leaning on
      his shoulders, and gripped the thin wrists fast about his neck as Aaron
      had bidden him.
    </p>
    <p>
      Meanwhile Humphrey Neal had stood by intently watching all that passed.
      The sight of Gabriel&rsquo;s back, however, scarred for life by the flogging he
      had received that autumn, sent such a storm of rage through him that for a
      moment he was not calm enough for action. Aaron&rsquo;s rod was raised once, and
      a violent blow fell on the scarred shoulders. The rod was raised a second
      time, but Humphrey, knowing now how to intervene, sprang forward, seized
      it in his strong grasp, and flinging his left arm about the gaoler&rsquo;s
      throat suddenly tripped him up by an unexpected lunge at the back of his
      knee. Springing aside he let the half-tipsy fellow fall heavily on to the
      ground, and a thrill of relief passed through every man in the place when
      they heard the resounding crash with which this brutal tyrant&rsquo;s head met
      the floor.
    </p>
    <p>
      Humphrey Neal bent over him for a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The fellow is not dead, but I&rsquo;ll warrant him not to stir for the next
      three hours&mdash;he&rsquo;s not the first villain I have tripped up in that
      fashion.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! Lord! Oh! Lord! whatever will become of me?&rdquo; whimpered Sandy. &ldquo;He&rsquo;ll
      beat me to a jelly when he comes to himself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Look you here, Sandy,&rdquo; said Gabriel, hastily putting on his doublet and
      cloak. &ldquo;No one shall harm you if you will but help us to escape. We will
      take you with us, and you shall never clap eyes on Aaron again. Come, let
      us down the steps, there&rsquo;s a good fellow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He put his hand on the lad&rsquo;s shoulder kindly, and Sandy, like a dog that
      has been caressed by his master, was ready to dare anything in his
      service.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They will be feasting and gaming by now, will they not? and the guard
      will be but slight,&rdquo; suggested Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, sir, but there be a sentry at both the gates,&rdquo; said Sandy, scratching
      his head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Help us, then, on to the Castle wall, the key of the entrance will surely
      be on this bunch. I know well there is a way from this tower on to the
      outer wall. Do you seize the keys, and lock Aaron safely into this room
      while we steal quietly down.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Sandy began to look more hopeful. &ldquo;You&rsquo;ll be needing ropes,&rdquo; he suggested.
      &ldquo;And where be I to find them?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I saw a big coil of rope at the top of the tower the day my Lord Falkland
      came here,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;I will come with you to search for it, and we
      will leave the rest to follow, bringing the keys with them.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Sandy obeyed blindly, and before long the two had returned with the coil
      of rope. Never had the old walls of St. George&rsquo;s Tower seen a more
      extraordinary sight than the escape of the forty prisoners of war in the
      dusk of that wintry afternoon. The white, haggard faces of the
      half-starved men bore an indescribable air of grim resolution. Silently as
      ghosts, they made their way down the tower, and with marvellous
      self-control crept one by one on to the outer wall.
    </p>
    <p>
      This was the most dangerous moment, for it seemed only too possible that
      the guard at the main entrance might see them. From the Osney Gate they
      were partially screened by St. George&rsquo;s Tower itself, and, crouching as
      low as was possible, they devoutly hoped that the Christmas feasting would
      have made the guard more or less drowsy.
    </p>
    <p>
      Humphrey Neal and Rawlyns of Marlborough were the first to emerge, and
      they busied themselves with making the rope fast to the battlements; then
      one ghost-like figure after another glided forth, until, last of all,
      Sandy and Gabriel appeared, locking the entrance after them and pocketing
      the bunch of keys.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was agreed that Humphrey Neal should be the first to test the rope. If
      it would bear his weight it would certainly bear the lean and fever-worn
      prisoners.
    </p>
    <p>
      Breathlessly they watched him slide down and alight safely on the snowy
      slope beside the millstream.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let us not wait for each other,&rdquo; said Gabriel, &ldquo;but each cross the ice
      and seek safety beyond in whatever quarter seems to him best.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      To this they all agreed, and without risking another word to each other
      they one by one let themselves over the wall, and crossing the frozen
      millstream escaped in various directions, mostly going in groups of three
      or four.
    </p>
    <p>
      Now and then Gabriel, as he awaited his turn, heard sounds of merriment
      from within the Castle walls, and as Sandy slid down the rope a distant
      echo of &ldquo;The Boar&rsquo;s Head&rdquo; chorus floated up to him. His hearing seemed to
      have become preternaturally acute, and he shivered a little when through
      the frosty air he heard the guard at the main entrance whistling the
      refrain.
    </p>
    <p>
      And now at length Sandy stood on the bank below and Gabriel&rsquo;s turn had
      come. With a heart beating high with hope and excitement he let himself
      over the wall, and grasping the rope swung in mid air, descending hand
      over hand, while the distant sound of the singers within floated back to
      him:
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The Boar&rsquo;s head, as I understand,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Is the bravest dish in all the land.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      He alighted safely in the snow, and found his arm gripped by Humphrey
      Neal, then as the chorus of the carol was shouted out they cautiously made
      their way over the frozen millstream, and were just scrambling up the
      opposite bank when the sharp barking of a dog startled them into anxious
      listening once more.
    </p>
    <p>
      Crouching among the bushes, they heard a discussion being held by the
      guard, and trembled lest a sentry should pass along to the spot on the
      walls where their rope was made fast. It was now that Sandy came to their
      aid, for he knew the dog and coaxed it to his side, fondling it into quiet
      and good humour.
    </p>
    <p>
      By this time the other prisoners had safely disappeared in the gathering
      twilight of the short December day. They resolved to linger no more, but,
      bidding Sandy follow, began to walk rapidly to the other side of the city,
      choosing, as far as might be, the back streets and alleys.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some wandering minstrels on a round of carol-singing before long attracted
      their notice, and they observed that one of the company lingered far
      behind the others, rolling about unsteadily as he walked, and tipsily
      twanging his lute. When by-and-by his companions trooped into an alehouse,
      he wandered aimlessly along by himself, swearing profusely, yet
      occasionally chanting a boisterous refrain of &ldquo;Noel&mdash;Noel,&rdquo; in a
      fashion that made Humphrey laugh heartily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In ten minutes the fellow must fall into the kennel,&rdquo; he said, gaily,
      &ldquo;and, if so, he may prove of use to us. Ay, to be sure! I knew he couldn&rsquo;t
      stagger on much longer.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t belabour me like that,&rdquo; groaned the minstrel, apostrophising the
      stones, &ldquo;I was keeping the best of time. &lsquo;Noel! Noel! Noel! Noel!&rsquo; my
      throat&rsquo;s on fire. We&rsquo;ll have a stoup at the &lsquo;Pig and Whistle.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;As many as you please,&rdquo; said Humphrey, cheerfully. &ldquo;But, in the meantime,
      we will do your carolling for you. I&rsquo;ll trouble you for the lute, and&mdash;yes,
      you may as well spare your hat, too!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Laughing at the placid way in which the minstrel fell asleep on his stony
      bed, Humphrey tucked the lute under his arm, clapped the felt hat on to
      Gabriel&rsquo;s bare head and hurried down the street.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We will pass the guard on Magdalen Bridge as minstrels on our way to
      perform at Cowley. Do you by chance know any carols?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know one,&rdquo; said Gabriel, beginning to hum the air of the Bosbury Carol.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That will do. I know the tune, and will catch up the words of the chorus,
      and, with the lute to twang an accompaniment, we shall make a brave show.
      Sandy, you will pick up any money that the good Christians throw to us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But sir, I see the watchman coming,&rdquo; said Sandy, apprehensively; &ldquo;for
      Heaven&rsquo;s sake, let us hide in yon archway.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay; no skulking,&rdquo; said Humphrey, &ldquo;let us put a bold face on it, and say
      we have come to sing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      So saying, he turned in at the gateway of Merton, cheerfully twanging his
      lute.
    </p>
    <p>
      The porter encountered them with a face of astonishment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now then, you fellows, what are you about? Don&rsquo;t you know that His
      Majesty the King visits the Queen&rsquo;s apartments?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, to be sure, master,&rdquo; said Humphrey, assuming the dialect of a
      countryman. &ldquo;And we have orders to sing in the quad. You&rsquo;ll not be denying
      us poor folk our chance of earning a groat in these cruel hard times.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, well,&rdquo; said the porter, good-humouredly, &ldquo;Christmas is Christmas,
      and as you say, the times are hard. But see there&rsquo;s no brawling or
      drinking or unseemly noise.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Master we be the most mannerley minstrels in the shire,&rdquo; said Humphrey,
      touching his hat obsequiously as he passed on. &ldquo;And that be true as the
      Gospel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This will stand us in good stead when we get to the Bridge by-and-by,&rdquo; he
      added, in a low voice. &ldquo;Let us cross to yonder window above the archway,
      the lights are brightest there, and doubtless the Queen holds her
      Christmas festivities within.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel, feeling after his long imprisonment in the Castle like one in a
      dream, fearing every minute lest he should wake and find this strange
      adventure unreal, crossed the snowy quad, and at a nod from his companion
      began to sing the Bosbury Carol, Humphrey cleverly putting in an effective
      accompaniment on the lute. Out into the still frosty air rang the quaint
      old words, and feverish excitement gave strength to the voice of the
      half-starved prisoner.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      When we were all, through Adam&rsquo;s fall,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Once judged for to die;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And from all mirth brought to the earth,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      To dwell in misery;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      God pitied then His creature man,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      In Scripture as you may see,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And promised that a woman&rsquo;s seed
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Should come for to make us free.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Oh! praise the Lord with one accord,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      All you that present be;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      For Christ, God&rsquo;s Son, has brought pardon,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      All for to make us free.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      As he sang he noticed the shadows of those within the room moving
      fantastically on the ceiling, and when Sandy in a startlingly sweet treble
      caught up the air of the refrain, the figure of a lady approached the
      window and looked forth. The light gleamed on her bare white shoulders,
      and on the pearl necklace about her slender throat. Gabriel instantly
      recognised the Queen, and for a minute scarcely wondered at the thraldom
      in which she contrived to hold her husband, so radiantly beautiful was her
      face, so full of charm and vivacity her whole bearing. She turned her head
      now and imperiously beckoned to some one within.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel, still with the strangest sense of unreality, sang another verse,
      half-fancying himself once more in the snowy garden at Hereford, half
      expecting to catch sight of brave Sir John Eliot&rsquo;s snow effigy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      He thought no scorn for to be born
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Of a birth both low and small;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Betwixt ox and ass in a crib He was
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Laid poorly in a stall;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      To the shepherds in fold the thing was told,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      In Luke as you may see,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Who sang glory to the Lord on high
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      That did come for to make us free.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      As once again the chorus rang out, he saw the King join his consort at the
      window, and, watching the two, could not but reflect how amiable a
      gentleman His Majesty might have been had he not been fated to fill a
      position wholly unfitted for him. But then his face grew stern, for back
      into his mind there came a memory of the long, long list of grievous acts
      of tyranny and injustice for which the King was responsible; and he
      thought of Eliot done to death in prison, of Hampden laying down his life
      in the struggle to free the country, and of Falkland, contemned and
      misjudged by all, striving in vain to make peace, and dying broken-hearted
      in the saddest isolation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Haunted most of all by this memory of Falkland, he stumbled somehow into
      the final verse of the carol.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And thus in death yielded up His breath,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Saying, consecrated, just,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      All this was done by Christ, God&rsquo;s Son,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      To bring men&rsquo;s souls to rest.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Therefore you all, both great and small,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      That here now present be,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Serve him always, with diligent praise,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      The Lord God that made us free.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      In the chorus one of the courtiers at a sign from the Queen opened the
      window and threw down a few coins to the minstrels, after which their
      Majesties withdrew. Sandy groped in the snow for the money, Humphrey Neal
      courteously raised his hat, but Gabriel stood motionless, gazing intently
      up at the brightly-lighted windows.
    </p>
    <p>
      The weird shadows moving to and fro on the ceiling looked to his fancy
      like the nodding plumes on a funeral-car, and he shivered as he heard the
      laughter and merriment of those within, for it sounded to him as hollow
      and mirthless as the wintry wind which sighed and moaned through the
      archway below.
    </p>
    <p>
      Just in that fashion had the wind raged and moaned when His Majesty had
      entered Westminster Hall nearly two years before on his rash attempt to
      arrest the five members.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What are you staring at?&rdquo; said Humphrey Neal, astonished at the
      expression on his companion&rsquo;s face. &ldquo;We had better hasten on.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel made no reply, but with one lingering look at those strange
      funereal shadows on the ceiling, he turned away, following his companions
      across the quiet quad and out into the street.
    </p>
    <p>
      He had looked his last on the King.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0025" id="link2HCH0025"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXV.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent20">
      &ldquo;Whatever harmonies of law
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The growing world assume,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Thy work is Thine. The single note
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      From that deep chord which Hampden smote
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Will vibrate to the doom.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Tennyson.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">B</span>y the time they
      approached Magdalene Bridge the twilight had faded into darkness, but the
      stars shone brightly in the frosty atmosphere, and the snowy ground
      glimmered white through the pervading gloom. Some temporary
      fortifications, not of a very effective order, had lately been made to
      protect the bridge, and a strict guard was kept. It was the endeavour to
      pass through at this late hour of the afternoon which was like to prove
      their greatest peril.
    </p>
    <p>
      More than once Humphrey Neal looked with anxiety at his two companions.
      From Sandy nothing but a dog-like obedience could be expected; and it
      seemed to him that Gabriel&rsquo;s overbright eyes and feverishly flushed face
      told their own tale. The lieutenant, whose fortitude and intrepid courage
      had carried him in a masterly fashion through the escape from the Castle,
      stood now on the verge of utter collapse. Clearly it rested with him to
      take the initiative and to pioneer the others through this dangerous
      attempt to pass the sentries.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sing a snatch of some carol as we walk,&rdquo; he suggested.
    </p>
    <p>
      And Gabriel obeyed, chanting, to a tune he had known all his life, the
      words:
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;The God of love doth give His Son,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The Prince of Peace, to quell
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      The sin and strife that mar man&rsquo;s life;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      With us He deigns to dwell.
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      On earth be peace,
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      Bid strife to cease,
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      To all men show goodwill.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      By this time they had reached the first sentry.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Halt, there!&rdquo; said the man. &ldquo;None leaves the city after sunset.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good master sentry, let us pass; the sun hath set but an hour, and we be
      bound to reach Cowley by supper-time,&rdquo; said Humphrey in his countryman&rsquo;s
      drawl.
    </p>
    <p>
      The sentry summoned one of the guard.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Leave the city!&rdquo; said the burly fellow, with a laugh. &ldquo;You&rsquo;re too late,
      my man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We should ha&rsquo; been here sooner, sir,&rdquo; said Humphrey, &ldquo;but we had to sing
      in the quad at Merton to Her Majesty. You&rsquo;ll never be denying us when we
      tell you that we&rsquo;ve been carol-singing to the King and Queen.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, well, you seem a harmless fellow, but I don&rsquo;t remember your coming
      into the city.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I came in yesterday, sir; and for the love o&rsquo; heaven let us pass through
      now to the Cowley road, for it be cruel cold here, and we have but this
      night to earn a few coins by our minstrelsy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, go through with you, then,&rdquo; said the guard, carelessly, &ldquo;and you
      may thank your stars that it be Christmas night, or I&rsquo;d not have let you
      by.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;God bless you, sir, for a good Christian,&rdquo; said Humphrey, touching his
      hat. &ldquo;Come, mates, we&rsquo;ll e&rsquo;en give them a tune as we go.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then raising the lute he sounded the refrain of the Bosbury carol, and
      they passed out of Oxford singing the old familiar words which for one of
      them had so many memories. Once Gabriel glanced back to the bridge, and
      the dim outline of the towers and spires of the beautiful city, with its
      lights shining out here and there like glowworms; and most fervently did
      he hope never again to enter the place where he had suffered such
      torments.
    </p>
    <p>
      For some minutes they walked rapidly on, but when at length they were out
      of earshot the sense of their good fortune in escaping thus far
      successfully made them forget everything in a rapturous sense of relief.
      They laughed and shouted like schoolboys released from work, and it was as
      much as Sandy could do to keep pace with them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No more gruesome thoughts of racks and halters!&rdquo; said Humphrey. &ldquo;And for
      you no more months of slow starvation in that fever den. Farewell, a long
      farewell to Aaron and his rod!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder if by now he has recovered his senses,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis
      more like that our rope has been discovered by the guard and the escape
      found out in that fashion&mdash;I wish we could have brought it off with
      us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We will press on as fast as may be for fear of pursuit,&rdquo; said Humphrey.
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a house I know at Cowley where we can get food. &rsquo;Tis owned
      by an old retainer of ours who can be trusted.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They toiled on as fast as might be over the rough road, with its
      treacherous ruts frozen hard, and all were thankful enough when they saw
      the outline of St. Bartholomew&rsquo;s leper-house looming into sight, for the
      frosty air and the exercise had sharpened their appetites.
    </p>
    <p>
      Old Nicholas, the farmer, gladly gave them food, and they were sitting in
      his chimney-corner feasting on cakes and hot ale, when to their dismay the
      tramp of horses and the voices of men without made them fear that already
      they were pursued.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never heed, Master Humphrey,&rdquo; said old Nicholas. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll put them on the
      wrong track, and do you all step up the stairs behind yon door, for maybe
      they&rsquo;ll be thrusting their heads into the house place.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They obeyed their host, and Humphrey, knowing well that he was a shrewd
      old man, had faith in his discretion. The others heard in no small
      trepidation the tramp of feet on the flagged path leading to the door;
      then came a peremptory knock.
    </p>
    <p>
      Nicholas opened promptly enough, anxious to keep his questioners in a good
      temper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you seen aught of three carol singers here?&rdquo; asked a voice which
      clearly reached the fugitives on the staircase.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Bellringers did you say?&rdquo; asked Nicholas, feigning deafness. &ldquo;Up at the
      inn, sir, supping at the inn.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Three <i>carol singers</i>,&rdquo; shouted the man.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! to be sure,&rdquo; nodded Nicholas. &ldquo;Yes, sir, and one of them had a lute,
      oh! yes to be sure, I saw them a while ago, and they was singing like
      archangels.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Which way did they take?&rdquo; shouted the pursuer. &ldquo;Are they like to be at
      the inn?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, sir, not at the inn,&rdquo; said Nicholas, shaking his head vigorously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Which way did they go?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Nicholas stepped out into the garden and pointed and gesticulated with
      much energy.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where does that lead to?&rdquo; questioned the officer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where does it lead to?&rdquo; repeated Nicholas, as though not quite sure that
      he had heard aright. &ldquo;It leads to Thame, sir, you&rsquo;ll soon get there; Thame
      the market town.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, they have taken the road there, have they. The villains have escaped
      from Oxford Castle and one of them is a spy. Now then, my boys, set spurs
      to your horses, we shall soon run the quarry to earth, and the first that
      comes up with them shall have the hanging of the vile rebels. Keep to the
      left and press on.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The sound of the horses&rsquo; hoofs died away in the distance; then Nicholas
      returned to the house place, and the three hunted men came out of hiding.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That was a close shave, Nicholas,&rdquo; said Humphrey Neal, shaking the old
      man&rsquo;s hand gratefully. &ldquo;Thanks to your ready wit we are safe, but we must
      press forward without delay or these wolves will be the death of us yet.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where do you escape to, sir?&rdquo; asked Nicholas.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To London,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;There will be a warm welcome for Mr. Neal at
      Notting Hill Manor, the home of my grand dame. &rsquo;Tis thanks to him I
      have escaped.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thanks to your own courage,&rdquo; said Humphrey. &ldquo;But we will hasten on,
      Nicholas, without delay, and at Watlington I will get old Parslow to speed
      us on our journey.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Nicholas with many good wishes bade them farewell, and, taking the
      precaution of leaving the road, they went across country, shortening the
      distance and running less risk of capture.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have hunted so often in this part of the country that I know every inch
      of the ground,&rdquo; said Humphrey, as he pioneered his two companions across
      the snowy fields and frozen brooks. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis not so pleasant a matter,
      though, to be hunted oneself, especially on foot. Perhaps at Watlington we
      can get a mount from Parslow, he is the landlord of the &lsquo;Hare and Hounds,&rsquo;
      and I&rsquo;ve known him all my life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The bitter wind blew in their faces as they toiled on; and, at length,
      Sandy began to whimper that he could go no farther. They tried their
      utmost to cheer the lad.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We shall soon be at Watlington,&rdquo; said Humphrey, &ldquo;and I&rsquo;ll get Parslow to
      give you a berth as stable boy; you shall be as happy as a King, and maybe
      happier, with plenty to eat and a motherly old cook who&rsquo;ll see you&rsquo;re not
      bullied. Oh! you&rsquo;ll think yourself in paradise after the life you&rsquo;ve led
      with Aaron.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Sandy grinned placidly, but soon remarked again that he was &ldquo;cruel
      footsore.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This is Chalgrove field, where Colonel Hampden got his death wound,&rdquo; said
      Humphrey, and Gabriel looked over the snowy ground, gleaming white in the
      starlight, and tried to think how it had looked on that fatal day when a
      deadly fight had been fought, and the waving corn had been trampled
      underfoot and dyed crimson with the blood of the noblest of Englishmen.
    </p>
    <p>
      By this time the excitement which had carried him on had subsided, and
      though he said nothing, it was evident to Humphrey that only dogged
      resolution and an indomitable will enabled him to drag one foot after the
      other. But he came of a stock that was not easily daunted, and it was not
      till they reached the &ldquo;Hare and Hounds&rdquo; at Watlington that he would admit
      that he was dead beat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come round to the back entrance,&rdquo; said Humphrey. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll get a word with
      old Mogg the cook.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Softly lifting the latch, he took them into the kitchen of the inn, where
      an old crone, with a most good-natured face, sat alone by the fire.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mogg,&rdquo; said Humphrey, stealing across the room, &ldquo;a happy Christmas to
      you, and of your charity take us into hiding, for we stand in peril of our
      lives.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Larka mercy, Master Humphrey, how you do startle a body,&rdquo; exclaimed the
      old woman, beaming with pleasure at the sight of one she had known from
      babyhood. &ldquo;What&rsquo;s amiss with yonder gentleman? Methinks he is but
      ill-fitted for travelling. &rsquo;Tis in bed you should be, sir, with a
      good sack posset and warm blankets.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In truth, &rsquo;tis where I would fain be,&rdquo; said Gabriel, dropping on
      to the nearest bench. &ldquo;Yet I would crave leave to have a wash first.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Sandy stared at him, that anyone should actually wish to be clean on this
      cold winter&rsquo;s night seemed to him the most extraordinary thing he had ever
      heard.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, Mogg, the brutes have treated my friend most scurvily,&rdquo; said
      Humphrey; &ldquo;do you furnish him with one of your master&rsquo;s shirts and a pair
      of hose, and look well to him, for he&rsquo;s worn out and half-starved. But
      first take me to the master&rsquo;s room and let me have speech of him in
      private, for we will keep our coming quiet if possible.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Parslow, the landlord, who had known Squire Neal, of Chinnor, for many
      years, gladly undertook to help Humphrey, and Sandy was promised work in
      the stableyard on the understanding that the two gentlemen he had helped
      so greatly should start him in life with money for his outfit. By nine
      o&rsquo;clock, thanks to Mogg&rsquo;s kindly offices, Gabriel found himself in a state
      of drowsy cleanliness and comfort in a great four-post bed, and when
      Parslow ushered his friend into the room and stayed for awhile chatting he
      was too blissfully sleepy to open his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then, should there be any signs of pursuit, you will let us know,&rdquo; said
      Humphrey, setting down his candle and pulling off his boots. &ldquo;Meanwhile
      we&rsquo;ll sleep.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis the bed on which Colonel Hampden lay the night before
      Chalgrove fight,&rdquo; said Parslow. &ldquo;Well do I remember it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And I&rsquo;ve good cause to remember it, too, Robin, for &rsquo;twas the very
      night Prince Rupert&rsquo;s men set our house ablaze and brought us to ruin.
      Well, good-night to you, and many thanks for your aid. We will be up by
      four, and, as you suggest, go with Jock the carrier to Henley. Once out of
      Oxfordshire we shall be safe. My friend sleeps already I see. Poor fellow,
      after lying for months on bare boards, I&rsquo;ll warrant he thinks himself in
      clover.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They slept soundly for some three hours, then Humphrey was roused by
      hearing a peremptory knocking without. He started up in bed and listened;
      someone was going downstairs to the front entrance, and again a thundering
      knock descended on the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      Stealing across to the window, he looked cautiously down and descried the
      dark forms of four or five horsemen&mdash;there were sounds of unbolting
      the door, and then the question he had expected: &ldquo;Have you seen a party of
      minstrels from Oxford pass through here?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, sir,&rdquo; said the landlord, with truth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Curse the fellows! How can we have missed them? Do you and a couple of
      men ride on, sergeant, you may yet overtake them on the London-road.
      Everton, you and I will get some food and a few hours&rsquo; sleep here.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can give you food, gentlemen, but being Christmas night we are fuller
      than usual,&rdquo; said Parslow.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, anything will do,&rdquo; said the officer, dismounting. &ldquo;Everton, see the
      horses fed and stabled while the landlord makes ready for us, it will be
      the quickest way in the end.&rdquo; Humphrey whistled softly to himself,
      dismayed to think of the risk they now ran of being trapped. The notion of
      being taken in bed and being dragged back to Oxford to be hung was not to
      be borne. He groped in the dark for his clothes and hastily dressed. His
      companion still slept, though uneasily, now and again talking and moaning
      in a way which alarmed Humphrey, who thought it highly probable that the
      new fever had already attacked him.
    </p>
    <p>
      Presently there was a soft knock at the door and the latch was lifted by
      the landlord, who stole in cautiously, candle in hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; said Parslow, &ldquo;you are not safe here. I&rsquo;ve left the King&rsquo;s officers
      down below supping, and have promised to make a room ready for them. I
      will put them in here if we can safely manage to take the two of you down
      to the stableyard. Once there I can hide you among the sacks in the
      carrier&rsquo;s cart, and will rouse Jock when the officers are abed and bid him
      drive you with all speed to Henley.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis our only hope,&rdquo; said Humphrey; &ldquo;yet I don&rsquo;t know but my
      friend is too ill to travel. Look at him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      In truth the sleeper&rsquo;s flushed face and burning hands were not reassuring,
      but they were obliged to rouse him and try to explain matters.
    </p>
    <p>
      He started up, staring at them in a dazed, bewildered way.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We are within an ace of being caught,&rdquo; whispered Humphrey. &ldquo;Don your
      clothes with all speed and the landlord will help us to escape.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With an effort Gabriel forced himself to attend, though it seemed to him
      that a couple of sledge-hammers were pounding remorselessly on his brain.
      He began to dress without a word, but staggered and all but fell when he
      attempted to cross the room. Humphrey took him by the arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What of Sandy?&rdquo; he asked. &ldquo;Let us leave the money for him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To be sure,&rdquo; said Humphrey, placing some gold pieces in the landlord&rsquo;s
      hand. &ldquo;I know you&rsquo;ll have the poor fellow provided for, Robin, and for
      your help to us you shall be well recompensed. We&rsquo;ll follow you on tiptoe
      without more delay.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The landlord had hurriedly re-arranged the bed, and now, candle in hand,
      crept down the stairs, pausing once or twice to make sure that the
      officers from Oxford were still chatting over their supper. Humphrey was
      relieved to see that the sense of danger had for the time restored
      Gabriel. With admirable selfcontrol he rallied his failing powers, stole
      softly after the landlord, and left the inn by the back door at which they
      had made their entrance a few hours earlier. In the stableyard stood a
      carrier&rsquo;s cart piled up with sacks of corn. Into this the two fugitives
      climbed, the landlord arranging the sacks round them and covering the
      whole with a bit of sail-cloth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You lie there, gentlemen, and you&rsquo;ll be safe enough,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;and when
      the officers are abed I&rsquo;ll rouse Jock and bid him put in the horses and
      drive to Henley.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The waiting seemed endless, but at last they heard cautious steps
      approaching and whispered remarks between Parslow and Jock, and finally
      there came the grinding of the wheels and a shaking and jarring of the
      cart which made Gabriel feel as if his last hour was come. He gasped for
      breath; to move was impossible, for the corn sacks were piled on every
      side, and on the top of them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can never endure twelve miles of this&mdash;we shall be here for
      hours,&rdquo; he reflected, desperately.
    </p>
    <p>
      But just then, as the cart rumbled out of the yard and passed into the
      street, there were sounds of a window being thrust open, and a man&rsquo;s voice
      shouted out.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ho! there! Which way are you going?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The fugitives held their breath to listen; clearly their pursuers had
      heard the sounds of departure&mdash;were they even at this last moment to
      fall into the hands of their captors?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, what a fool I was,&rdquo; reflected Gabriel. &ldquo;I could endure for days in
      this carrier&rsquo;s cart if needful. Anything&mdash;anything rather than to be
      again a prisoner in Oxford Castle!&rdquo; Meanwhile Jock was conveniently deaf,
      and drove placidly along the snowy street.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Stop, you fellow,&rdquo; roared the officer. &ldquo;Which way do you go, and what&rsquo;s
      your errand?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Jock drew up, swearing vehemently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where be I a-goin?&rdquo; he shouted, in a surly voice. &ldquo;To Henley with a load
      of corn.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And to the horror of the fugitives he got down from his place and began in
      a leisurely way to alter something in the harness, lugubriously singing
      meanwhile a snatch of a tune which Gabriel thought would ring in his ears
      for ever.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The cramp is in my purse full sore,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      No money will bide therein&mdash;a,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      And if I had some salve therefore,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      O lightly then would I sing&mdash;a.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      The officer at the window above burst into a laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In truth a shrewd fellow!&mdash;here&rsquo;s a groat to mend the purse, and if
      on the road you come upon three soldiers bid them wait on me here as they
      return, and fail not to tell them if you have clapped eyes on any of these
      cursed wandering minstrels.-&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The window was closed, and with a cheery word to the horses Jock climbed
      back to his place. They heard him chuckle to himself as he resumed the
      reins, and soon the cart had rumbled out of Watlington and was rolling and
      swaying and grinding its way among the frozen ruts.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How do you fare?&rdquo; said Humphrey, anxiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall last out,&rdquo; said Gabriel, philosophically. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis better
      than a halter anyway. Is the driver trustworthy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, an honest old man, he&rsquo;ll stand by us, I know him well. But I thought
      that fellow at the window smelt a rat and would stop us at the last
      moment. Heavens! How this road doth churn one up! we shall be knocked
      black and blue by the time we have got to the end of the journey.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel was past speaking. He could only lie there in torment, half
      fancying that he had been sentenced to be pressed to death, so
      increasingly intolerable grew the weight of the corn-sacks above him. The
      only relief was from a chink between the sacks which chanced to come just
      where a rent in the sail-cloth let through a breath of air, and now and
      then as the cart swayed brought into view a starry patch of the dark blue
      vault above. He wondered what Hilary would have thought could she know of
      his dilemma; and then with a rush of hope and a renewed sense of life and
      strength, he remembered that freedom meant at least the possibility of
      seeing her again. And spite of his present misery he smiled to himself,
      and even perceived the humour of Jock&rsquo;s song about the cramp in his purse,
      with the monotonous chorus of
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Ay ho, the cramp&mdash;a! ay ho, the cramp&mdash;a!
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      They must have travelled some eight or nine miles when the sound of
      horsemen in the distance roused him to fresh anxiety. Doubtless the
      soldiers, finding their errand at Henley hopeless, were riding back. Now
      was the time when Jock&rsquo;s fidelity and ready wit would be put to the test.
      There was a breathless pause; the groaning of the wheels slowly ceased and
      a harsh voice rang out into the night.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Stand, in the King&rsquo;s name!&rdquo; shouted the sergeant, while his men seized
      the horses. Instinctively Humphrey gripped the hand of his sick comrade.
      The two lay listening in an agony of suspense to hear what questions would
      be put.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
