      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXVIII.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent20">
      &ldquo;True love&rsquo;s the gift which God has given
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      To man alone beneath the heaven;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      It is not fantasy&rsquo;s hot fire,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Whose wishes, soon as granted, fly.
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      It liveth not in fierce desire,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      With dead desire it doth not die;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      It is the secret sympathy,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The silver link, the silken tie,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Which heart to heart, and mind to mind,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      In body and in soul can bind.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;<i>Lay of the Last Minstrel</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">M</span>eanwhile, in the
      withdrawing-room, Humphrey Neal was asking Madam Harford to promote his
      suit with Helena.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will do what little I can for you, sir,&rdquo; said the old lady, who liked
      him and desired to see him wedded to her goddaughter. &ldquo;But first, I would
      bid you make sure of the maid&rsquo;s own feeling in the matter. Then, if she
      approves, you had best seek out her guardian, Dr. Twisse, the Rector of
      Newbury.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! is her guardian a parson?&rdquo; said Humphrey with a groan. &ldquo;I shall never
      find favour in his eyes; he&rsquo;ll be asking what view I take of the Divine
      right of kings to break the law.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No; you will find him a liberal man, and a kind-hearted kinsman to my
      god-daughter. Once assured that the marriage is for his niece&rsquo;s happiness,
      he will not, I think, trouble you with arguings. Why should you not speak
      to Helena now, and ride to Newbury to-morrow with my son. He could then
      say a word on your behalf.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Humphrey caught at this idea, and asked where he should be likely to find
      Helena.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I left her but now in the south parlour,&rdquo; said Madam Harford. And with a
      smile she watched the hasty way in which Humphrey at once quitted the
      room, eager to bring his wooing to a happy close.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is a tolerably well-assured lover,&rdquo; thought the old lady. &ldquo;I do trust
      Nell will not prove uncertain of her own mind at the last minute.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Humphrey found the south parlour lighted only by the glow from the fire;
      there was no sound but the soft whirr of the spinning-wheel, and in the
      dim room the flax on the distaff and little Nell&rsquo;s yellow curls shone out
      brightly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You should keep blindman&rsquo;s holiday,&rdquo; he said, drawing up a stool and
      seating himself beside her. &ldquo;Pray idle for a few minutes, and talk with
      me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, sir, can I not talk and spin at the same time?&rdquo; said Helena, gaily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, not when the talk is of a serious matter.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is anything wrong? Is Mr. Harford worse?&rdquo; asked Helena, in alarm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, no; he is much better, and already planning when to rejoin Sir
      William Waller. You think of him, but never trouble your head about me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His sigh was too theatrical to deceive her. She laughed merrily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That reproach comes with an ill grace from your lips,&rdquo; she retorted. &ldquo;Did
      I not walk with you, and talk with you, sir, this very afternoon for an
      hour by the clock?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It will be our last walk,&rdquo; said Humphrey, gloomily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo; she asked, and somehow she dropped her thread and let
      the wheel stand idle.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am going away to-morrow, with Dr. Harford,&rdquo; said Humphrey, intently
      watching the little girlish face, and hailing with great delight the look
      of trouble that dawned in it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But why?&rdquo; she faltered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is because I love you that I go,&rdquo; he said, eagerly. &ldquo;Because I must
      move heaven and earth to get into favour with your guardian. Helena, tell
      me, could you ever wed one who, till this war ends, is like to be a
      half-ruined man? I am ashamed to propose such a marriage, but I love you
      with my whole heart. We are alike homeless and forlorn. Give me the right
      to shield and protect you, and I will spend my life in making you happy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She sat quite silent, with drooped head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Can you not trust one that so loves you?&rdquo; pleaded Humphrey, realising now
      that this little gentle maid was not, after all, to prove an easy
      conquest.
    </p>
    <p>
      She lifted her head for a minute, and looked shyly, yet searchingly into
      his eyes. There was none of the fierce passion that had terrified her in
      Norton&rsquo;s gaze, nor was there the quiet friendliness she had often seen in
      Gabriel&rsquo;s hazel eyes; surely this was the love that would satisfy her! And
      yet&mdash;yet&mdash;the pity of it!&mdash;could she honestly say she loved
      him? All at once she hid her face and burst into tears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Helena!&rdquo; he cried, in dismay, kneeling beside her, &ldquo;what have I done?
      What have I said to grieve you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I don&rsquo;t know what to do!&rdquo; she sobbed. &ldquo;If my father were but here!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He drew down one of her hands, and held it in his tenderly. &ldquo;Tell me about
      him,&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      And Helena poured out all her pent-up grief, and did not draw away her
      hand when now and again he kissed it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Tell me,&rdquo; said Humphrey, &ldquo;had your father still been here, do you think
      he would have trusted you to me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; said little Nell, with a sob. &ldquo;Anyone would trust you. It was not
      you that I doubted.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What, then, my beloved?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was whether I loved you&mdash;enough.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Suppose,&rdquo; said Humphrey, &ldquo;I join Sir William Waller&rsquo;s force when Gabriel
      Harford returns, and then come back in a year and ask you again. By that
      time you may know your own mind.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      But at this suggestion Nell had fresh light thrown on her innermost heart.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, no,&rdquo; she cried, clinging to his hand. &ldquo;I could not bear that you
      should go away for a year. They would kill you, as they killed my father.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you would care a little?&rdquo; said Humphrey, smiling. &ldquo;Perhaps, after
      all, you do begin even now to love me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She did not reply, but she did not resist him when he clasped his arms
      around her, and drawing the fair little head on to his shoulder covered it
      with kisses.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To-morrow,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I will ride to Newbury, and if Dr. Twisse gives his
      consent, who knows but he may be willing to return with me, and himself
      tie the knot? For in days like these I am sure Madam Harford will agree
      with the proverb, &lsquo;Happy is the wooing that&rsquo;s not long a-doing.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Yet after all it was not till Humphrey Neal and Dr. Harford had made their
      farewells the next morning, and had left the Manor House to a most dreary
      quiet&mdash;a stillness which might be felt&mdash;that Helena became quite
      sure of herself. The light of her life seemed to have gone out, and she
      wondered how she had ever endured existence at Notting Hill all through
      the previous autumn. The next day her spirits sank still lower. What if
      Dr. Twisse would not consent to the marriage? It was quite possible that
      he might consider Humphrey Neal&rsquo;s prospects too much injured by the war to
      make him a desirable husband from the financial point of view.
    </p>
    <p>
      And, indeed, this consideration was what chiefly filled the wooer himself
      with anxiety as he journeyed down to Newbury, and Dr. Harford had no
      little difficulty in cheering him in his depression. So downhearted had he
      become when they actually reached their destination, that the physician
      good-naturedly undertook to break the ice for him, and leaving Humphrey at
      the inn, took the letter from Madam Harford himself to the Rectory. He
      made a most excellent ambassador, for very few could resist his charm of
      manner, and his frank, clear way of stating a case. The Rector knew at
      once that he was a man whose sound judgment could be trusted, and he
      promised to call on them at the inn in an hour&rsquo;s time to discuss the
      matter with Mr. Neal.
    </p>
    <p>
      Fortified by a good supper and by a cheery talk with Dr. Harford, Humphrey
      underwent the ordeal with composure, and made a good impression on
      Helena&rsquo;s guardian. He found also, to his amusement, that the mere fact
      that Dr. Twisse was a parson told after all in his favour. For as the good
      man informed them, he had only that morning been pondering over the church
      register, and had found that it furnished sad food for reflection. The
      burials were many, but the marriages had been few indeed since the war
      broke out.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In truth, if the miserable strife goes on much longer, there will be no
      men left in the country,&rdquo; he said, with a sigh. &ldquo;There is nothing like a
      deadly war for the utter destruction of home life and happiness.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Little Mistress Helena hath already suffered cruelly through the war,&rdquo;
       said Dr. Harford. &ldquo;And to see her happily wedded to one able to protect
      her and to safeguard her property would greatly please my mother.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then the opinion of Sir Robert Neal was quoted as to the prospect of
      recovering the Oxfordshire property, and before long Dr. Twisse had
      consented to the marriage, and had agreed to return to London with
      Humphrey Neal that he might discuss arrangements with Helena and her
      godmother.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
