    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXIV.
    </h2>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Just in so far as we have love which shall survive, though that to
      which it clings be taken away from us,... in so far as our sorrow has
      brought us into the wide fellowship of human suffering and anguish, and
      given us a tenderness that shall endure though years of placid comfort
      should flow over us&mdash;in so far as we have reached a life not subject
      to change or the workings of Time&mdash;so far we have some sense of the
      eternal realities, so far we may feel that we see God, and may, though
      with awe-struck humility, ask whether, haply, in some measure, we are
      seeing as God sees. Infinitesimal as our attainment may be, we shall,
      nevertheless, know what it is to enjoy, and shall not only strive after,
      but shall, in some measure, have the life eternal</i>.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <h3>
      &mdash;P. H. WICKSTEED.
    </h3>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">I</span>t was on the
      Saturday preceding Norton&rsquo;s walk with Hilary that Gabriel Harford rode
      once more from Gloucester to the scene of his rescue of Major Locke&rsquo;s
      daughter. His recovery from his severe illness had long ago been complete,
      and the open-air life had fortunately proved the best cure for the
      mischief done to his constitution by the long months in Oxford Castle.
      Though thin and a trifle gaunt-looking after the severe campaign and the
      insufficient food, the indomitable pluck and manliness which had carried
      him through so much had stood him in good stead through all the quarrels
      and discussions and difficulties which had prevailed of late among the
      Parliamentary generals, to the great discomfort of the whole party.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sir William Waller had, some time before, perceived, with the sagacity
      which made him the greatest tactician possessed by either Royalists or
      Parliamentarians, that an entire reorganisation of the army was needed and
      that, with the Earl of Essex at the head, nothing but disaster lay before
      them. The new model army was at length being formed, and, by the
      self-denying ordinance, Waller retired to his work in the House of Commons
      and his soldiers were dispersed, some being sent to serve in the new army,
      others despatched to various garrisons in the South of England.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was with no little amusement that Gabriel recognised again the scenes
      of his moonlight adventure two years before, and old Amos, the gatekeeper,
      gave him a warm greeting.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Eh, sir!&rdquo; he exclaimed. &ldquo;These be better times for the Manor, and &rsquo;tis
      you we have to thank for it all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, man! you did quite as much to save your mistress,&rdquo; said Gabriel,
      heartily. &ldquo;We could never have found our way to her without you for guide.
      Well! All&rsquo;s well that ends well! Are Mr. and Mrs. Neal within?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, and main glad they&rsquo;ll be to see you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The trim bowling-green, over which Joscelyn Heyworth had helped him to
      escort Helena in such unceremonious haste, was now in a blaze of sunshine,
      and on the steps where they had nearly betrayed themselves by laughing, as
      they drew off their riding-boots, a large tortoiseshell cat lay basking.
      From within the house came a cheerful sound of voices, and when the
      servant ushered him into the hall, he found Humphrey Neal and his pretty
      little wife so absorbed in playing with their baby son and heir on the
      hearthrug, that they had not noticed the rare arrival of a visitor.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Captain Harford!&rdquo; announced the servant, and both host and hostess came
      eagerly to meet the newcomer with a warmth of welcome which was
      unmistakable.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I thought Sir William Waller was in the New Forest!&rdquo; exclaimed Humphrey.
      &ldquo;What good fortune brings you here?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We were at Ringwood about Easter, pretty well worn out with long marches
      and the worst weather of the whole winter, in our journey for the relief
      of Taunton,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;But now Sir William Waller&rsquo;s army is
      disbanded, and I was sent for a time to Gloucester with a contingent of
      the men to serve under Massey in Herefordshire.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They certainly work you hard and don&rsquo;t overfeed you. Why, you are
      well-nigh as lean and hollow-cheeked as when I first saw you in that
      pestilent gaol at Oxford.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We have in truth been half-starved these many months,&rdquo; said Gabriel.
      &ldquo;What else can one expect when the country has been laid waste and
      plundered for nigh upon three years? And even if provisions were to be had
      for money, we had naught to pay with, thanks to the mismanagement of the
      authorities.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Helena, determined that he should at least have all that the Manor would
      provide in the way of a banquet, hastened off to interview her
      housekeeper, while Gabriel, with a secret pang, watched the fatherly pride
      with which Humphrey showed off the perfections of the blue-eyed,
      curly-locked son and heir, who rolled and kicked in perfect bliss on the
      hearthrug, quite indifferent to the fact that he was in a most distracted
      country.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is the image of Helena,&rdquo; said Humphrey. &ldquo;All save his hands; did you
      ever see such a fist in a brat of his age? You should feel how hard he can
      grip. Soon we shall have him at work with the dumb bells!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have been reading Mr. John Milton&rsquo;s letter on Education,&rdquo; said
      Gabriel, with a laugh, &ldquo;and mean to have him as well skilled in athletics
      as an ancient Greek. I found my friend, Captain Heyworth, deep in the
      treatise the other day.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! you mean the gentleman that married my pretty cousin Clemency. I have
      heard naught of them since old Sir Robert Neal&rsquo;s death. How do they fare?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sadly enough; you probably didn&rsquo;t hear that he lost his arm at the second
      battle of Newbury. It came about through sheer lack of surgeons, and
      through the scandalously inadequate aid for the wounded. Each regiment was
      supposed to have its surgeon and two mates, but at Newbury the supply had
      fallen into arrears, and Heyworth&rsquo;s wound gangrened, and many other men
      lost their lives just from neglect and from the severe privations we had
      to put up with.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you have seen the Heyworths in their home since then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I was at Katterham about two months ago. It is piteous to see that
      poor fellow suffering, and like to suffer all his life long, Sir Theodore
      Mayerne says. We are speaking of my friend, Captain Heyworth,&rdquo; he
      explained as Helena rejoined them.
    </p>
    <p>
      She listened to his account with eager sympathy in her gentle eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I remember him well,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;both here and at Gloucester; he was ever
      cheerful and light-hearted. Doth he keep up his spirits even now?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He makes a gallant effort to do so,&rdquo; said Gabriel, &ldquo;but you can guess
      what it would be for a man of his active habits to be a helpless invalid
      at three-and-twenty.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The crippled soldiers need to be the bravest of all, for the dead have at
      least due honour accorded to them, and rest in peace, and the victors have
      praise and glory and success to crown them, but most people forget those
      who have to drag on a maimed life year after year,&rdquo; said Helena. &ldquo;How doth
      his wife fare? She was very good to me when I was in trouble.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She hath a son of her own, but not such a healthy and fine child as
      yours, and the anxiety of her husband hath told upon her. Still, brighter
      times may dawn for them. When I saw him, poor fellow, he was clearly
      longing to be back again with Sir William Waller. Indeed, he hath been
      sorely missed, for in February, when the men broke into mutiny, he would
      have been better able to cope with them than any other officer.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What made them mutiny?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Partly the endlessness of the campaign and the privations, partly that
      Sir William Waller, though much liked by his officers, fails to tackle his
      men just in the right way. Then the pay was terribly in arrears, though
      that was no fault of his.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir Thomas Fairfax is to be Commander-in-Chief of the New Model Army, I
      hear,&rdquo; said Humphrey Neal.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, and Skippon Major-General. There is a strong desire that, spite of
      his remaining in Parliament, Cromwell should be appointed to the vacant
      post of Lieutenant-General, but I know not how that will be.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was so much to hear and to tell that the time sped quickly, and when
      Gabriel was obliged to return to Gloucester he carried with him a very
      happy picture of his friend and pretty Helena in their home, and felt that
      Major Locke would have been content to see the daughter whose future had
      filled his dying moments with anxiety, in the old Manor with husband and
      child to cheer her.
    </p>
    <p>
      Partly in the hope of winning over those recently engaged in the affair of
      the Clubmen, but mainly with the intention of diverting Prince Rupert from
      his journey northward, Massey set out from Gloucester at dawn on the 20th
      April, having been reinforced by the contingent from Waller&rsquo;s army, which
      brought up his strength to about five thousand foot and three hundred and
      fifty horse.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was with no little delight that Gabriel found himself marching back
      once more to his own well-loved county, and his spirits rose when, during
      the halt at Newent, he heard that his regiment was to remain there for the
      night, marching early the next day to Bromyard, where Massey had
      expectation of winning recruits from the dispersed Clubmen.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bromyard was, he believed, the benefice held by Dr. William Coke, and
      unless Hilary should happen to be at Whitbourne he might be able to see
      her. It chanced that, owing to his long and frequent absences from
      Hereford, he had never heard of the death of old Mr. Wall, at Bosbury, and
      had no notion that Dr. Coke had been promoted to the vacant living during
      his two years&rsquo; probation in London.
    </p>
    <p>
      His annoyance was therefore unspeakable when, at the last moment, Massey
      changed his plans, ordering his guards to undertake the expedition to
      Bromyard, and the rest of the troops to press on to Ledbury. With bitter
      regret Gabriel had to endure the sight of the blue regiment left behind
      for the work he so ardently longed to set about, and with the obedience of
      a soldier to tramp on precisely where he did not wish to go.
    </p>
    <p>
      The picturesque town of Ledbury was bathed in the glow of the spring
      sunset as the Parliamentary troops emerged from the narrow cross street
      into the spacious main thoroughfare with its beautiful black and white
      timbered houses and, at the further end, the quaint town hall raised on
      massive black posts, between which on market days the countrywomen set
      their stalls. Massey and his officers dismounted at the door of the chief
      inn, a well-managed hostelry known as &ldquo;The Feathers,&rdquo; and, hungry with
      their long march, they were chiefly intent on ordering supper when they
      were checked by a curious-looking man, who, in spite of his short stature,
      forced his way through them, elbowing a passage without so much as a &ldquo;by
      your leave,&rdquo; until he reached Colonel Massey.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel looked at him intently. Where had he before seen that strong
      square face with its air of gloomy austerity, its smouldering, resentful
      eyes?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; said the man, plucking at Massey&rsquo;s sleeve, &ldquo;by the mercy of a good
      Providence I chanced to be in Ledbury this evening; I am sent to remind
      you of your promised aid.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Eh!&rdquo; exclaimed Massey; &ldquo;who are you, and what aid did I promise?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am one Peter Waghorn, of Bosbury, and last autumn you bade me wait till
      you came hither again. You broke your word, sir, and never aided us when
      you were here in March, but this time I beg you to fulfil your promise and
      cast down the Popish cross which stands in our churchyard.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To be sure! I remember you now,&rdquo; said Massey, and Gabriel with a sudden
      flash of recollection instantly recalled both the man and his story. He
      had last seen him at Hereford, vehemently addressing the people outside
      the cathedral. He listened with some interest to Waghorn&rsquo;s words.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do not neglect this second call, sir,&rdquo; he said, solemnly; &ldquo;for as I
      prayed at noonday, I heard a voice bidding me to rise and haste to
      Ledbury. Like Abraham, I set forth in faith, and now I well understand why
      I was sent. Come back with me, sir, I implore you, and cast down the
      cross.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was no insincerity about this man, he evidently spoke from his heart
      and with intense anxiety awaited the officer&rsquo;s answer. Massey, a
      good-natured soldier of fortune, caring more for the fighting than the
      cause, regarded him with no little amusement.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The people desire its destruction?&rdquo; he said, carelessly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It would be for their souls&rsquo; good,&rdquo; said Waghorn. &ldquo;Some do idolatrously
      bow to it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, well, that&rsquo;s a foolish practice. Moreover, Parliament hath ordered
      the crosses to be broken down,&rdquo; said Massey. &ldquo;I will send over some of the
      soldiers to-morrow morning.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The gloomy face of the fanatic brightened, and without actual thanks, but
      with the air of one who has gained his heart&rsquo;s desire, he touched his hat
      and withdrew.
    </p>
    <p>
      Massey turned to Gabriel Harford.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I want a word with you in private,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Come to my room while
      supper is making ready.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel, wondering what was to happen, followed the Colonel to a room
      overlooking the High Street, and, at Massey&rsquo;s invitation, took a place in
      the deep window-seat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think you know Cromwell, do you not?&rdquo; said the Governor of Gloucester.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, I was serving under Waller when he acted with him last autumn
      in the Newbury campaign, and again last month in the Western campaign,&rdquo;
       said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There is a very important and secret matter that I must make known to
      him,&rdquo; said Massey. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t entrust the despatch to an ordinary man, but
      if you will undertake to carry it to him you will be doing him a greater
      service than I can explain to you. Would you be willing to resign your
      temporary post in my force and undertake this, even though I can give you
      no explanation of the signal importance of the work?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, I will gladly undertake it,&rdquo; said Gabriel. &ldquo;Am I to ride at
      once?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, not yet,&rdquo; said Massey, smiling at his ardour. &ldquo;For I will at the
      same time send a despatch to the Commander-in-Chief, who, I understand, is
      still at Windsor organising the New Model with Cromwell&rsquo;s aid. I can&rsquo;t
      complete that till I have learnt what Prince Rupert is about, and if
      possible turned him back. But I wanted to know if you were willing to turn
      despatch-bearer for the nonce.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There is nothing I should like better than to do a service for Cromwell,&rdquo;
       said Gabriel, his eyes kindling. &ldquo;For in truth he seems to me the greatest
      man I ever met.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Humph!&rdquo; said Massey. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s little doubt that he is an able leader, but
      he&rsquo;s too religious by half. The man&rsquo;s a mystic, a seventeenth-century
      Enoch, with the soldierly zeal of a David to boot. By the bye, you may as
      well take over a detachment of the men from Waller&rsquo;s army to Bosbury
      to-morrow. I&rsquo;m as likely as not to forget that fellow&rsquo;s request, and I
      think you have done that sort of business before, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, we hewed down Abingdon Cross,&rdquo; said Gabriel. And when the next
      day he found that the rest of the forces were to witness the hanging of an
      unhappy scout of Prince Rupert&rsquo;s, who had shot a sentry in the early
      morning, he was glad to have had the Bosbury work entrusted to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I would rather hew down fifty crosses than stand by and see a poor wretch
      hanged,&rdquo; he reflected, as they marched along the rough country lanes. &ldquo;A
      fair fight is one thing&mdash;every man takes his chance, but hanging is a
      hateful business.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then he remembered with deep regret that this despatchbearing that Massey
      meant to entrust to him would probably rob him of the eagerly-desired
      glimpse of Hilary, and also of the visit to his home at Hereford. He
      wondered whether it would not be possible to let his father know of his
      near neighbourhood, longing sorely to see him and to learn from him more
      than the few and long-delayed letters he had received could tell. Even if
      he did not see Hilary he might learn through Dr. Harford how she fared.
      After all if he did see her, she might possibly refuse to speak to him, as
      she had done in very cruel fashion at Hereford two years ago. His heart
      ached even now at the memory of the scene in the Cathedral porch. How was
      it that although the pain of his wound at Edgehill could never be vividly
      recalled, the anguish of remembering that last interview remained always
      so keen? Was it because the body was a mere garment presently to be laid
      aside, while love, which belonged to the soul and spirit, was eternal and
      changeless?
    </p>
    <p>
      But to serve Cromwell in some real, though unknown fashion, was worth
      suffering for; moreover, he should see Sir Thomas Fairfax, the
      Commander-in-Chief, and he was naturally eager to learn more about this
      New Model Army, which was the main hope of his party.
    </p>
    <p>
      He fell to thinking of the three men who had most influenced his life; his
      father, Falkland and Cromwell. What was it that had specially attracted
      him to such opposite types? He tried to think what characteristics they
      shared, and came to the conclusion that it was a certain breadth of mind
      and a habit of looking at the inner realities, not the externals, of
      religion.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was curiously free from the usual habit of judging men by mere outward
      appearance, and the fact that both Falkland and Cromwell had been
      handicapped by nature, and were without form or comeliness had from the
      first been no hindrance to him. Their largeness of soul had irresistibly
      drawn him to them; for Falkland, with his wide charity, his philosophic
      Christianity, had been centuries in advance of his contemporaries; while
      Cromwell stood now revealed as the foremost of that band of Independents
      who most nearly reached the level of toleration for those of other
      religious views. He was ready to tolerate all sorts and conditions of men,
      save only the Papists and the rigid Episcopalians; the former because they
      would fain have handed England over once more to the Pope&rsquo;s jurisdiction,
      the latter because the recent tyranny of Laud and the servile adulation
      with which the bulk of the clergy justified the King&rsquo;s misrule had made
      them for the time a danger to the State.
    </p>
    <p>
      But his musings were cut short by a sudden glimpse of an orchard by the
      roadside, and the first sight they had yet had of apple-trees in blossom.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What an early spring!&rdquo; he thought to himself. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis but the 21 st
      of April and here&rsquo;s apple blossom! And there are the poplars at Bosbury
      already green, and the old tower which Hilary asked me about all those
      years ago. Well! &rsquo;tis a mercy we can&rsquo;t see in life what lies before
      us. And to point the moral of that reflection here comes Peter Waghorn,
      like a blot on the fair picture.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good-day, sir, good-day!&rdquo; said the wood-carver, his dark face lighted by
      a gleam of triumph. &ldquo;I thank the Lord you have come. My prayers have been
      heard, and we shall accomplish His work!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0035" id="link2HCH0035"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXV.
    </h2>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>The real test of a man is not what he knows but what he is in himself,
      and in his relation to others. For instance, can he battle against his own
      bad inherited instincts, or brave public opinion in the cause of truth?</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &mdash;Tennyson.
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">O</span>n this bright,
      mild Tuesday morning, Mrs. Durdle was bustling about in the sitting-room
      at the Vicarage, armed with a goose-wing and a duster, weapons wherewith
      she waged a daily battle with the dust. Spite of her unwieldy proportions,
      she was a most active person, but even the energetic are not sorry to
      pause a little in their work on a balmy spring day, and when Zachary
      crossed the little lawn and approached the open casement, she willingly
      went to the window, nominally to shake her duster, but in reality to enjoy
      a gossip.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mornin&rsquo;, Mrs. Durdle!&rdquo; said Zachary. &ldquo;A fine growin&rsquo; day this!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Zachary was somewhat bent and old, yet his face, though wrinkled, had
      still a youthful ruddiness, and bore that benevolent expression which
      comes when the grinders cease because they are few, and the lips take an
      infantine and gentle smile as a recompense.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, for me, I say, &rsquo;tis a day when workin&rsquo; is none so easy,&rdquo;
       said Durdle. &ldquo;Folk talk a deal about the peace and quiet of a country
      life, but I had a heap more quiet at Hereford before I came to keep house
      for the Vicar. Look you there!&rdquo; and she pointed with fine scorn to an
      untidy table, &ldquo;he&rsquo;s been and got out them nasty bones again! If they
      wasn&rsquo;t as dry as an empty cider-press I&rsquo;d give them all to the dog!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With laugh Zachary suddenly held up and brandished in the air a long bone
      which he had hitherto concealed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Dundle gave a horrified exclamation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My patience, man! Don&rsquo;t bring that here! Vicar would never take bones
      from the churchyard. &rsquo;Tis animals&rsquo; bones he&rsquo;s all agog for, and
      then only when they be as old as Noah&rsquo;s ark.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll put it back in the mould when parson&rsquo;s seen it; but I tell you, Mrs.
      Durdle, &rsquo;tis a marvel. <i>That&rsquo;s</i> a giant&rsquo;s shank bone, and he
      must ha&rsquo; stood nine feet high&mdash;poor chap, think o&rsquo; that! I&rsquo;m glad
      there&rsquo;s not so much o&rsquo; me. Think o&rsquo; nine feet o&rsquo; rheumatics!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, rheumatics or no rheumatics, I&rsquo;m sorry for his wife,&rdquo; said Durdle,
      laughing. &ldquo;She must have needed to be a rare good knitter to keep him in
      hose! If you must leave the thing for the Vicar, let me give it a good
      dustin&rsquo; out o&rsquo; window first. Ah! Zachary, after all, &rsquo;tis ill work
      jesting over bones when England&rsquo;s strewn with the bones o&rsquo; them as has
      been killed in this weary war.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;re right, Mrs. Durdle&mdash;you&rsquo;re right. &rsquo;Twill be three
      years come Lammastide since the King set up his standard at Nottingham,
      and ever since naught but battles and sieges, plunderings and
      threatenings. And now there&rsquo;s this plaguey garrison hard by at Canon
      Frome, with a Governor that sticks at nothing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What! Colonel Norton?&rdquo; said the housekeeper, raising her eyebrows. &ldquo;Why,
      he be always comin&rsquo; to see Vicar. But between you and me, Zachary, &rsquo;tis
      Mistress Hilary&rsquo;s pretty face, I take it, that draws him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then, Mrs. Durdle, for pity&rsquo;s sake have a care o&rsquo; your young lady, for I
      hear little enough to his credit. But I thought Mistress Hilary had been
      courted by a young spark at Hereford?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Eh, to be sure, so she was. She and young Mr. Gabriel Harford were like
      lovers since they were no higher than this table. But the war put a stop
      to that, and from being fast friends they became foes, the more&rsquo;s the
      pity.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, like master, like man, as the proverb hath it,&rdquo; said the sexton,
      stooping to root up a plantain from the turf. &ldquo;Vicar he says, he&rsquo;ll have
      nought to do with wars and fightings, for he be a man o&rsquo; peace. And so be
      I, Mrs. Durdle, so be I. But beware of yon Governor o&rsquo; Canon Frome, for
      there&rsquo;s many a wench will have cause to rue the day when he came to
      Herefordshire.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;For my part, I like the gentleman well enough. He&rsquo;s a fine, handsome
      officer, and the Vicar always enjoys his visits,&rdquo; said Durdle, pouncing
      like a bird of prey on the laboriously-woven spider&rsquo;s web which she just
      then saw in a corner of the window.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, you women! you women! &rsquo;Tis always the same. A handsome spark
      will ever find you ready to give him a good word,&rdquo; said Zachary, shaking
      his head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And are you so sure, Zachary, that a pretty wench can&rsquo;t turn you round
      her fingers?&rdquo; retorted the housekeeper, with a smile.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Handsome is as handsome does,&rdquo; quoted the sexton, shrewdly. &ldquo;Give me the
      woman who knows how to brew good cider; grave-diggin&rsquo; all among bones and
      dust is terribly dry work, Mrs. Durdle.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, well, come round to the kitchen, man, though &rsquo;tis over early
      for your noonings,&rdquo; said Durdle, with a laugh, &ldquo;but, by-the-bye, what was
      the tale I heard in the village last night about the doings at Drybrook?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis o&rsquo;er true,&rdquo; said Zachary, &ldquo;though &rsquo;twas not the Canon
      Frome men that plundered there, but a troop of Colonel Lunsford&rsquo;s horse
      that were serving in Prince Rupert&rsquo;s forces. At Drybrook, when a poor
      fellow refused to give up a flitch o&rsquo; bacon to the foraging party, they
      struck him down and knocked out his eyes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good gracious, Zachary; now don&rsquo;t you be telling that gruesome tale to
      Mistress Hilary, for she can&rsquo;t abide hearing tell o&rsquo; such doings, though
      she do pretend to be so fond o&rsquo; war and fighting and glory and the rest.
      There&rsquo;s not much glory in havin&rsquo; your eyes put out, I&rsquo;ll warrant!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Zachary lounged off towards the back premises, and Durdle was about to
      retire to the kitchen, and resume her gossip there, when she heard a knock
      at the front door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now I do believe that&rsquo;s Colonel Norton&rsquo;s knock,&rdquo; she muttered, bustling
      out in reply to the summons.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her surmise was right enough; there he stood, booted and spurred, in all
      the glory of his gay attire, and with a sparkle in his dark eyes, which
      instantly banished from Durdle&rsquo;s mind all Zachary&rsquo;s warnings. She ushered
      him into the room she had just quitted, and though he had only asked for
      the Vicar his glance had so plainly bade her tell her mistress as well of
      his arrival, that she promptly sought Hilary, who had just finished making
      apple pasties in the kitchen.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll clap those in the oven, dearie,&rdquo; said the housekeeper, &ldquo;and do you
      doff your apron and tell the Vicar Colonel Norton is waiting to see him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary departed on the errand, unable to determine whether she wished to
      see her admirer or not.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will leave you to have your chat with the colonel,&rdquo; she said when she
      had with some difficulty roused the Vicar from a treatise on ancient coins
      which Mr. Silas Taylor had lent him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, nay, child,&rdquo; said the Vicar, retaining her hand in his. &ldquo;I have
      scarce clapped eyes on you this morning; come in too, and hear the news.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And to Norton&rsquo;s satisfaction the uncle and niece entered the room
      together. The Vicar&rsquo;s greeting was always cordial, yet this morning Norton
      fancied that there was a certain depression about his host which he could
      not fathom.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you bring us any news, sir?&rdquo; asked the antiquary wistfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No news, sir, and no treasures for the collection, unluckily,&rdquo; said
      Norton. &ldquo;I called mainly on business. You have not been disturbed here, I
      hope, by Governor Massey? I hear he is hovering about again near Ledbury.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, we have heard naught of him here,&rdquo; said the Vicar. &ldquo;I have been up
      this morning seeing the owner of the Hill Farm. There is sore trouble
      there, sir, and I wish you would consider the people more than you do.
      These foraging parties are growing unbearable.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Believe me, I do what I can, sir,&rdquo; said Norton in his most winning tone.
      &ldquo;I dislike the work of plundering as much as you would, but how else are
      we to keep the army alive?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar sighed heavily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;May God send us the blessing of peace!&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I tell you, sir, it
      fairly breaks my heart to go about among the people of Bosbury. There is
      scarce a family but has lost a man in this cruel war, or else hath been
      well-nigh ruined by marauders.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, Vicar, we must all take the fortune of war. Of course, the rustics
      grumble when hungry soldiers seize their goods&mdash;but how are the
      officers to check starving men? That is what I was last night urging on
      old Sir Richard Hopton, who does naught but complain of the Canon Frame
      garrison. &lsquo;Good Sir,&rsquo; I said to him, &lsquo;What would you have me do? If the
      King gave me money I would pay for what we consume. But we are fighting
      for the divine right of Kings, and have surely a divine right to feed on
      something more satisfying than air.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis not alone the taking of gear that I complain of,&rdquo; said the
      Vicar gravely, &ldquo;but of cruelties perpetrated by the soldiers&mdash;abominable
      cruelties which did not spare even women and children.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Such things will happen in time of war, sir,&rdquo; replied
    </p>
    <p>
      Norton. &ldquo;What can you expect? Soldiers are but human. &rsquo;Tis only the
      Roundheads that set up for being saints. However, we must not scare
      Mistress Hilary with talk of cruelties. Believe me,&rdquo; he said, turning to
      her, &ldquo;these tales of the village folk never lose in the telling, and we
      are not so black as we&rsquo;re painted. Prince Rupert&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Prince Rupert is one of a thousand!&rdquo; said Hilary, enthusiastically. &ldquo;How
      I should like to see him! Do you think there is a chance that he may come
      this way?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are of a more martial spirit than the Vicar. That is generally the
      way. We poor soldiers mostly find favour with the fair sex&mdash;&rsquo;tis
      one of our few compensations,&rdquo; said Norton, venturing nearer to her and
      lowering his voice as he noticed that Dr. Coke had moved over to the table
      and taken up the bone brought in by the sexton. &ldquo;Yet do not make me
      jealous of the Prince by dwelling overmuch on his merits. Am I to have my
      answer to-day?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She shook her head, and blushed deliciously. Norton had every intention of
      furtively kissing her hand, when the Vicar suddenly turned round and
      showed them his latest treasure.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Most curious! Most interesting! Why, the fellow must have been a giant.
      Hilary, look here! In life this man must have stood at least eight feet
      high. Where did it come from?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know, Uncle,&rdquo; said Hilary, shuddering. &ldquo;Ugh! how gruesome it
      looks! I can&rsquo;t bear skulls and bones!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton with a smile watched the two. &ldquo;What a contrast,&rdquo; he reflected.
      &ldquo;That old bone collector and a maid whose cheeks are like a wild rose! I
      wonder if the parson will get in the way of my designs?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was roused from his reverie by the entrance of Mrs. Durdle and the
      customary tray of cakes and cider.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar re-crossed the room with an eager question on his lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where did this come from, Mrs. Durdle? To whom am I indebted for this
      very rare bone?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, sir, &rsquo;twas Zachary brought it, and do now let me take it back
      to him. It gives me the creeps to see churchyard bones lying round loose.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I suppose if Zachary dug it up we ought to give it Christian
      burial,&rdquo; said the Vicar regretfully, &ldquo;but it does seem a pity. A most rare
      and interesting bone.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, yes,&rdquo; said the housekeeper, receiving it carefully in her
      apron, &ldquo;very interesting, but do now let it be buried decentlike. &rsquo;Tis
      impossible to keep the place tidy&mdash;let alone clean&mdash;when your
      antics are littering all over the house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a general laugh as she left the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No more <i>antics</i> for you, Uncle dear, if Mrs. Durdle has her way,&rdquo;
       said Hilary blithely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She is a most orderly person,&rdquo; said the Vicar, with a good-humoured
      smile, &ldquo;and to have as master an untidy old antiquary must be a sore trial
      to her. But pardon me, Colonel, all this time I have been rambling on
      about my own affairs, and I understand that you had some special matter to
      talk over with me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To tell the truth, sir, I walked over from Canon Frome this morning to
      ask you to sign your name to the Protestation framed by Prince Rupert. He
      commands the signatures of the people of this neighbourhood, and I shall
      be glad to have yours.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He handed a paper to the Vicar, who, with some reluctance, took it, and
      began to read it to himself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hey! What!&rdquo; he exclaimed, presently, &ldquo;the Prince commands? Why, Colonel,
      he has no right to extort oaths from free Englishmen. He fancies himself
      back in Germany. Listen to this! <i>&lsquo;I do strictly enjoin, without
      exception, all commanders and soldiers, gentry, citizens, freeholders, and
      others within the county and city of Hereford to take this Protestation.&lsquo;</i>
      I&rsquo;faith, he goes too far, Colonel, too far! Look at this! I must swear
      that all the Parliamentarians ought to be brought to condign punishment&mdash;I
      must swear that I will help His Majesty to the utmost of my skill and
      power and with the hazard of my life and fortune; I must swear not to hold
      any correspondency or intelligence with Parliamentarians, and to discover
      all their plans that I may chance to know; and all these particulars I
      must vow and protest sincerely to observe without equivocation or mental
      reservation.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, but, Vicar, we all know that you honour the King,&rdquo; said Norton,
      reassuringly. &ldquo;No man could dare to call your loyalty in question&mdash;why,
      you are the son of one of the twelve bishops who signed the Remonstrance.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very true,&rdquo; said the Vicar &ldquo;but the signing of that ill-judged and
      illegal document was, to my mind, my father&rsquo;s great mistake. No, no,
      Colonel; I try to do my best to honour the King and to love and honour all
      men; therefore I loathe this unlawful Protestation, and will not say, &lsquo;I
      willingly vow and protest,&rsquo; as here enjoined.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton watched him intently; this was a side of the antiquary&rsquo;s character
      which had not before been revealed to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But, sir, you scarce realise, I think, what a serious matter this may
      be,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;The Prince has expressly ordered that all who refuse to
      sign shall be seized without delay and kept in custody. It was enacted, as
      you see, on the second of this month.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar again examined the paper, then looked up with an astute
      expression. &ldquo;So it seems, sir, but you will also note that this
      Protestation is ordered to be tendered to all by the High Sheriff and
      Commissioners of the county, assisted by a Divine.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton veiled his annoyance by a laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of course if you want to keep to the letter of the law, we must bring
      over the whole posse from Hereford, but I thought as we were friends&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar smiled genially, and held out his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We are friends, certainly&mdash;very good friends. But as to keeping to
      the letter of the law&mdash;I don&rsquo;t acknowledge this document to be law at
      all, &rsquo;tis grossly illegal. You see, sir,&rdquo; he added reverently, &ldquo;I
      must try to remember that at Ordination I vowed to maintain and set
      forwards <i>quietness, peace and love</i> among Christian people.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As though the words had cost him something to utter in what he knew would
      be a hostile atmosphere, he turned away and stood for a minute by the
      window, looking out at the church he loved so well, and the strong tower
      of refuge and the quiet graveyard.
    </p>
    <p>
      Norton stroked his moustache to conceal a scornful smile, then bent low
      over Hilary&rsquo;s hand and kissed it, conveying to her by look and touch much
      more than the customary salute.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am not without hope, Mistress Hilary, that where I have failed you will
      succeed,&rdquo; he said gently. &ldquo;Try if you can to persuade your uncle, for his
      refusal places him in some danger. I know well how much influence your
      sweet words have over men, and trust you will permit me to wait on you
      before long to learn of your success.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With one of his sweeping bows he turned to take leave of the Vicar, who
      accompanied him to the door and bade him farewell very cordially, but
      being pre-occupied with the thought of the Protestation, forgot to give
      him the usual invitation to stay to dinner.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary, with a restlessness which she had never before felt, paced up and
      down the room unhappily. Did this man indeed love her as he professed to
      do? And did she in truth care for him? That he was handsome, clever and
      fascinating was beyond dispute&mdash;she thought she did care for him&mdash;certainly
      she was far from being indifferent to him&mdash;and yet? Yet it was not
      like that day years ago when Gabriel had spoken to her in the wood, and a
      whole new world had opened to them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing can be like first love, of course,&rdquo; she said to herself dreamily,
      and then bitterness overwhelming her, &ldquo;but my first love was all a
      miserable mistake! Gabriel cared more for this phantom of parliamentary
      government&mdash;loved that better than he loved me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She impatiently dashed from her eyes the tears that had started at this
      thought, and with sudden energy caught up her lute and began vigorously to
      tune it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I <i>won&rsquo;t</i> be a fool!&rdquo; she thought, resolutely forcing back the old
      memories that tried to rise. &ldquo;I will wed this loyal Colonel Norton. He
      said my words had power over men, and I see they have over him. They had
      none over Gabriel!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      At that moment the Vicar returned to the sitting-room.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, my child,&rdquo; he said, stroking her hair, &ldquo;yonder is a pleasant-spoken
      man, but I can never sign that paper he brought. We will talk no more of
      it, the very thought of it chafes me. Sing me one of your songs, dear, let
      us have &lsquo;Come, sweet love, let sorrow cease!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary winced, for the plaintive sweetness of &ldquo;Bara Fostus Dream&rdquo; was for
      ever associated with the summer days when Gabriel had wooed her; but she
      could not refuse her uncle&rsquo;s request, and sang the song in a more subdued
      frame of mind.
    </p>
    <p>
      She had just begun the last verse&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then, sweet love, disperse this cloud&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      when sounds of confusion in the village street and an uproar of voices
      brought her to a sudden pause. Running to the window, she called eagerly
      to the Vicar.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;See, Uncle, the people are thronging this way. What can have happened?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And as the Vicar joined her and looked forth, Durdle and Zachary rushed
      without ceremony into the room, breathless with haste, but each eager to
      give the news.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, sir, come out and stop it, for pity&rsquo;s sake,&rdquo; panted Durdle.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, do&rsquo;ee now. Mayhap they&rsquo;ll hearken to you,&rdquo; said Zachary.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is wrong?&rdquo; asked the Vicar, looking from one to the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The soldiers, sir&mdash;they&rsquo;ve marched from Ledbury!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Parliament soldiers, sir,&rdquo; panted Zachary. &ldquo;Fetched by Waghorn a-purpose
      to pull down the cross.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And they&rsquo;re a-goin&rsquo; to do it, too,&rdquo; put in Durdle, determined to have the
      last word.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar&rsquo;s indignant amaze almost choked him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What!&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;Pull down Bosbury Cross! Why, Hilary, &rsquo;tis one
      of the oldest in all England&mdash;one of our most valued antiquities. God
      grant I may be able to save it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He hastily crossed the room towards the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, sir,&rdquo; said Zachary, &ldquo;you speak to the captain, he be a
      pleasant-looking young officer. But as for Waghorn, I do think he be gone
      stark mad.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t come into the crowd, Hilary,&rdquo; said the Vicar, excitedly, as he
      hurried from the house. &ldquo;Wait in the garden and leave me to plead for this
      treasure of the past.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
