    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXVIII.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      We wait beneath the furnace-blast
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The pangs of transformation,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Not painlessly doth God re-cast
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      And mould anew the nation.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Hot burns the fire
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Where wrongs expire;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Nor spares the hand
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      That from the land
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Uproots the ancient evil.
    </p>
    <p>
      &mdash;Whittier.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">O</span>n returning to
      Ledbury, Gabriel seized the opportunity of writing to his father, begging
      that, if possible, he might see him before he left the neighbourhood; and
      by the time he had found a messenger to despatch to Hereford, Massey had
      returned from reconnoitring the surrounding country. The Governor of
      Gloucester was in excellent spirits, for he had reason to believe that
      Prince Rupert, having learnt of his arrival at Ledbury, had halted in his
      march to join the King, and would probably return and give him battle.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I only wish it were possible to fortify this town,&rdquo; he remarked as he and
      his officers supped at the &lsquo;Feathers,&rsquo; &ldquo;but it is out of the question.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you think we shall have a night attack, sir?&rdquo; asked Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis possible, for Prince Rupert ever loves that device. Yet he
      could scarce be here to-night. Some of the men had best, however, bivouac
      in the High Street: your detachment has had light work to-day, Captain
      Harford, and shall be told off for this under Captain Bayly; I may need
      you anon for the work of which we spoke.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In truth the men have had lighter work than we thought for, sir,&rdquo; said
      Gabriel, &ldquo;for the desire to pull down Bosbury Cross seemed to be only on
      the part of that fanatic Waghorn, and the Vicar pleaded for it with such
      excellent good arguments that, under certain conditions, I gave leave that
      it should be spared. I think, had you been there you would have done the
      same, sir, and I trust you don&rsquo;t disapprove of what I did.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Massey laughed good-humouredly. &ldquo;If you choose to incur the wrath of that
      mad fellow &rsquo;tis no affair of mine,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;And now I think of
      it, the Vicar of Bosbury was a sensible and kindly man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, and hospitable,&rdquo; said Captain Bayly. &ldquo;He gave us a good supper when
      we halted last winter at Bosbury. There was a pretty niece, too, I
      remember.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      This remark brought upon Gabriel much laughter and raillery, which he took
      in good part.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Were you not there with one of the Hoptons?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, to be sure, the younger one, that tried to defend Castle, Ditch near
      Eastnor. He was worsted, and thrown into gaol at Hereford, but managed to
      escape by leaping a wall, and rejoined us at Gloucester. I don&rsquo;t know
      where he is serving now.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Supper being ended Massey retired to finish his despatches, and Gabriel
      had orders to supervise the barricading of the streets with carts, which
      kept the men hard at work throughout the evening.
    </p>
    <p>
      The moon had risen, and the picturesque High Street with its gabled black
      and white houses would have looked like a place in fairyland had it not
      been for the grim preparations for defence and for the busy soldiers
      moving to and fro, some carrying torches which threw a fitful glare over
      the scene and made the bright helmets and gorgets glitter. Everyone was
      far too hard at work to notice the silent spectator who, wrapped in a long
      cloak and a hood of the sort much worn by aged men, noiselessly shadowed
      Captain Harford wherever he went.
    </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn&rsquo;s hatred only increased when he saw how remarkably active in the
      cause Gabriel could be, how swiftly the orders he shouted were carried
      out, and what an excellent officer he made. It was impossible to conceive
      one more in touch with his men, and the fanatic gnashed his teeth when he
      reflected that one authoritative word from this young fellow of two or
      three and twenty would have been sufficient to level the cross with the
      ground.
    </p>
    <p>
      By the time all was in readiness it was growing late, and Gabriel and his
      successor, Captain Bayly, walked down the High Street to the &ldquo;Feathers,&rdquo;
       at the door of which Massey lounged smoking his pipe.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Bid them sound the bugle for the evening psalm,&rdquo; he said, as the two
      officers joined him. &ldquo;The men had best sleep while they may.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As the bugle rang through the little town and the men assembled in front
      of the market-house, Waghorn, stepping forward like a bent and aged man,
      stealthily approached Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now will this sparer of crosses join in a psalm with the godly,&rdquo; he
      reflected, wrathfully. &ldquo;Let his days be few! Even in the midst of his sin
      shall he be stricken!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Little dreaming that one of his worst foes stood close behind him, Gabriel
      joined with rather a heavy heart in the psalm which seemed to haunt him at
      every crisis in his life. Standing now in the street at Ledbury with the
      manly voices of the soldiers ringing out into the night, he remembered how
      the same words
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      In trouble and adversity
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The Lord God hear thee still
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      had strengthened him as he stood waiting for the first attack at Edgehill;
      how in the Cathedral long ago with his eyes on Hilary&rsquo;s pale face, the
      same words had fallen on his ears, and how in the porch at Bosbury the
      psalm had on this very day been to them a bond of union. No thought of
      personal danger came to him now, though Waghorn&rsquo;s cloak brushed his
      sleeve. It was of Hilary he thought, and of the peril that threatened her.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the close of the psalm the bugle sounded the &ldquo;Last post,&rdquo; and such of
      the men as had quarters marched off; those who were to bivouac in the
      street scattering into groups about the market-house, and a detachment
      moving torch in hand to the upper end of the town where four ways met.
    </p>
    <p>
      Massey invited Gabriel and Captain Bayly to have a cup of mulled claret
      with him at the &ldquo;Feathers.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, sir, if you will pardon me,&rdquo; said Gabriel, who longed to be alone,
      &ldquo;I will ask to be excused. Truth to tell, I am dog-tired, and would fain
      sleep.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Massey slapped him on the shoulder with a laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Art sick, or in love? Eh? Beshrew me, but I believe you did leave your
      heart at Bosbury to-day. I&rsquo;ll be with you anon, Bayly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then, drawing Gabriel aside, he moved with him to the further end of the
      market-house just at the corner of the narrow alley which led steeply up
      to the church. Against the pale moonlit sky they could see the dark
      outline of the spire betwixt the gables of the houses.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have written both despatches,&rdquo; he said, in a low voice, &ldquo;and as we
      can&rsquo;t tell what the next four-and-twenty hours will bring forth I will
      give them now into your keeping, yet do not start until you can bear
      tidings of Prince Rupert&rsquo;s doings.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I may take part in the battle, sir?&rdquo; asked Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, if you are minded to volunteer. I will give you word when you had
      best go. And remember this: a despatch-bearer needs something more than
      mere courage. He needs dexterity, diplomacy and caution. If I cannot get
      speech with you, and the fighting goes against us, lose no time in
      escaping and make whatever circuit you deem best to reach Windsor in
      safety. I&rsquo; faith, I think we have no eyes upon us now in the dark alley,
      and at the &lsquo;Feathers&rsquo; we are over-tightly packed for privacy. Stow these
      safely away, and give the Commander-in-Chief all the details I am unable
      to set down. But at all costs see that both despatches are delivered. More
      hangs on it than you wot of.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Under the shelter of their military cloaks the transfer of the despatches
      was easily effected, and Gabriel thrust them into the inner pocket of his
      coat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will guard them with my life, sir,&rdquo; he said, in a low voice. &ldquo;And I
      thank you for trusting me with the work.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Massey laughed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Small matter for thanks! &rsquo;Tis ever a risky and troublesome
      business. Well, good-night to you, Captain. May your affair of love
      prosper!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good-night, sir,&rdquo; said Gabriel, forcing a laugh, as he paced slowly up
      the narrow alley.
    </p>
    <p>
      Alas! was it not a very one-sided affair of love? he thought to himself,
      with a sigh. If for a moment he ventured to hope that Hilary still cared
      for him, the next he remembered with a pang the way in which she had
      permitted Norton to dangle about her. He wondered, uneasily, what the
      Vicar could be dreaming of to allow it. Dr. Coke had seemed a shrewd as
      well as a generous man, yet had evidently no notion that the Governor of
      Canon Frome was playing the mischief in his very household. And then he
      remembered how plausible and fascinating Norton could be, recollected,
      too, that strange glimpse of a noble nature which he had now and then seen
      in him, and realised that very probably the Vicar and Hilary only knew the
      Colonel at his very best.
    </p>
    <p>
      A storm of despair swept over him as more and more plainly he saw the
      great danger which threatened her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis enough to madden a man!&rdquo; he said to himself, writhing at the
      sense of his powerlessness to help. &ldquo;It may be months or years ere I see
      her again, while all the time Norton can prowl round in his devilish
      fashion! Yet, if I rave like this, I shall lose all control over myself.
      After all, she gave me her promise to speak&mdash;I know she will keep her
      promise.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The thought calmed him, and, pausing at the head of the alley, he stood
      for a minute praying silently in his usual brief, formless, but thoroughly
      heartfelt way, &ldquo;God of Justice! grant her Thy help and guidance, and keep
      us from all evil this night.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The wind blew softly down the narrow alley, the dark spire pointed
      silently towards heaven, and in the stillness the soul of the Puritan grew
      once more strong and undaunted.
    </p>
    <p>
      As he paced back again to the High street he did not notice the dark
      figure standing in the shade of a doorway, but in the manner of one well
      used to bivouacking for the night he laid his sword on the ground, put his
      helmet and gorget in place of a pillow, and, with his military cloak
      wrapped about him, was soon sleeping soundly in one of the shallow
      recesses betwixt the wooden posts on which the market-house was raised.
    </p>
    <p>
      At some little distance a sentry paced to and fro; Waghorn, watching his
      movements with a keen and wary eye, waited patiently in his sheltered nook
      until he was assured that all the soldiers slept. Then seizing his
      opportunity as the sentry marched back to the farthest point of his beat,
      he glided noiselessly out of the shadow, heartening himself with fierce
      inward ejaculations.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let destruction come upon him at unawares! I dread that sentinel. But
      courage! I will remember Jael, the wife of Heber, the Kenite, and my part
      is not to slay, merely to filch!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Crouching down beside Gabriel he saw that he slept profoundly. In the cold
      clear moonlight it was easy to trace marks of care and suffering in the
      face, and, as the fanatic stealthily unbuttoned the coat, he reflected
      with grim satisfaction that worse would be in store for the sleeper when
      he woke.
    </p>
    <p>
      Just then, to his dismay, he heard the footsteps of the sentry drawing
      steadily nearer, and hastily stretching himself out beside his victim he
      lay motionless until the danger was past and the footsteps were once more
      retreating.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then in trembling haste he partly raised himself, thrust his hand with the
      control and caution that he had acquired in his wood-carving within the
      pocket of the buff coat, and had actually got hold of the despatches when
      the barking of a dog in a neighbouring house roused Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hullo!&rdquo; he cried, sitting up and gripping Waghorn by the arm. &ldquo;What are
      you about, fellow?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn in vain tried to escape; he was held as in a vice. Fortunately for
      him his face was in shadow, and he was completely disguised by his cloak
      and hood. With ready tact he began to whimper and moan like one
      half-witted.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis naught but daft Lubin, sir; naught but daft Lubin,&rdquo; he
      pleaded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Daft Lubin, indeed!&rdquo; said Gabriel, impatiently. &ldquo;I should think you <i>were</i>
      daft to wake up a tired man in the dead of night. Ho! sentry! call the
      guard and let this crazy fellow be taken up, or he&rsquo;ll be disturbing the
      men again.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn whimpering, struggling and protesting all the way up the street
      that he was &ldquo;naught but daft Lubin,&rdquo; was remorselessly hurried away by the
      guard.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yawning and shivering with the discomfort of one roused in his first
      sleep, Gabriel stretched his stiff limbs.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What was the row?&rdquo; muttered Captain Bayly, drowsily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Naught but an old half-witted beggar,&rdquo; said Gabriel. Then suddenly
      noticing that his coat was unbuttoned, he felt in consternation for the
      packet, and gave an ejaculation of relief on finding the despatches safe.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The night grows cold,&rdquo; said the other, wrapping his cloak more closely
      about him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis naught to some of the nights we had in Waller&rsquo;s time,&rdquo; said
      Gabriel. &ldquo;He took no heed of frost or damp, though now and again he was
      sorry for the horses.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With another prolonged yawn he stretched himself out face downwards, and
      was soon once more wrapped in profound sleep.
    </p>
    <p>
      Towards morning he had a curiously vivid dream. He thought he was swimming
      across a blood-red lake, and he knew that he bore despatches which should
      warn Cromwell of a dastardly attempt about to be made on his life. He had
      nearly gained the shore when the dark hull of a boat loomed into sight,
      and Norton leaned over the bows with a mocking smile on his lips and dealt
      him a blow which sent him down&mdash;gaspingly down&mdash;through the red
      depths. Yet he rose again to the surface, and flung the despatches with a
      last dying effort to the shore; and when for the second time he rose, the
      packet was being lifted from the ground by his father. Then he finally
      sank and was vainly fighting for breath when a bugle sounded &ldquo;To arms!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He sprang up instantly on the alert; the red light heralding the sunrise
      suffused Ledbury, drums beat the alarm, the guard shouted, &ldquo;To arms! to
      arms!&rdquo; and Massey&rsquo;s soldiers came pouring out of their night quarters in
      every direction. In two minutes Gabriel was in the stable saddling
      Harkaway with his own hands, and learning with a thrill of excitement that
      Prince Rupert, by a forced march through the night, was now close to the
      town, and was resolved to give them battle.
    </p>
    <p>
      Colonel Massey, in excellent spirits, came riding out of the courtyard of
      the &ldquo;Feathers,&rdquo; and rapidly gave directions to his officers. To Captain
      Bayly fell the work of defending the market-house and the entrance to
      Church-alley, and soon from the upper end of the town came sounds of
      incessant firing, and the hoarse cry of the contending watchwords, &ldquo;St.
      George!&rdquo; and &ldquo;Queen Mary!&rdquo; from the Royalists, and &ldquo;God with us!&rdquo; from the
      Parliament soldiers. The chief barricade higher up the street kept the
      Prince&rsquo;s troops at bay for some time, but in the meanwhile an attempt was
      made by a detachment of the Royalists to enter the town by Church-alley at
      right angles with the High Street, and some sharp skirmishing took place
      there, in which Gabriel bore a part.
    </p>
    <p>
      Scarcely had they beaten back the attack from this quarter when shouts and
      uproar warned them that the main barricade had been broken down after a
      resistance of about half-an-hour. This opened the High Street for the
      Prince&rsquo;s horse to charge, and though Massey made a gallant counter-charge
      and his men fought bravely, they were borne down. Rallying for a time by
      the market-house, he endeavoured to protect the retreat of his foot, and
      signing to Gabriel to approach, spoke a few hurried words to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Seize your chance now,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;and ride off. With a circuit you should
      be able to bear them safely. We shall charge again and fall back in good
      order on Gloucester.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Without further delay he urged his men forward against the approaching
      Royalists. And Gabriel obediently, but with not unnatural reluctance,
      turned Harkaway&rsquo;s head in the opposite direction, and was about to ride
      from the town when a loud outcry made him glance to the right.
    </p>
    <p>
      Down Church-alley rode once more a detachment of Prince Rupert&rsquo;s men, and
      he saw the figure of &ldquo;daft Lubin&rdquo; wildly accosting the leader, and heard
      him shout the words: &ldquo;Fire on yon officer! He bears despatches! Fire in
      the King&rsquo;s name!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Urging on Harkaway, Gabriel rode like the wind. A sudden crash and a
      numbness which made the reins fall from his left hand and his arm drop
      powerless at his side warned him that a ball had struck him; for a moment
      his eyesight threatened to fail him, but with an effort he recovered
      himself, gathered up the reins in his right hand and set spurs to his
      horse.
    </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn at the corner of the alley stood staring after him in blank
      astonishment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Curse him! how can he ride after that?&rdquo; he exclaimed. &ldquo;Ha! he reels in
      the saddle! Fire again, men! fire again! Now he clings to the horse&rsquo;s neck&mdash;he
      must fall&mdash;he is ours! he is ours! Evil shall hunt the wicked person
      to overthrow him!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      At that instant one of the Prince&rsquo;s troopers, finding his way blocked by
      the fanatic, pushed roughly past.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Out of the way, you prating Puritan!&rdquo; he cried, &ldquo;or I&rsquo;ll dash your brains
      out!&rdquo; And with that he dealt Waghorn a blow on the head which left him
      groaning on the ground.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0039" id="link2HCH0039"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXIX.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent30">
      One loving howre
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      For many years of sorrow can dispence;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      A dram of sweete is worth a pound of sowre.
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      . . . true is, that true love hath no powre,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      To looken backe; his eyes be fixt before.
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Spenser.
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">M</span>eanwhile Massey,
      with great coolness and ability, retreated in good order with the
      remainder of his men to Gloucester, but many had been made prisoners, and
      about a hundred and twenty had been killed in the street and in the hot
      pursuit.
    </p>
    <p>
      Had it not been for Waghorn&rsquo;s words to the Royalists, Gabriel might have
      made his escape as easily as the Governor of Gloucester had anticipated.
      But, learning that important despatches were so nearly within their reach,
      some four or five troopers gave chase to him with a heat and determination
      that only increased with each mile traversed. Bullets whistled about his
      ears, but on he sped, every nerve strained in the wild excitement of the
      ride, all pain for the time overcome by the intense desire to carry out
      his task.
    </p>
    <p>
      A second ball struck the already injured arm, making a ghastly flesh
      wound. Still he galloped on, but, alas! with the horrible consciousness
      that his pursuers were gaining on him.
    </p>
    <p>
      His strength was fast failing when the sound of church bells fell on his
      ear; surely they were the bells of Bosbury? Hardly conscious of the
      direction he had taken, only galloping madly across country to baffle his
      pursuers, he had indeed approached within a short distance of the village,
      which lay in the valley below embosomed in trees.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the time being he was out of sight of the Royalist troopers, and, with
      a word to Harkaway, he put the horse at a hedge which seemed a little off
      the course he had ridden.
    </p>
    <p>
      The horse did his part gallantly, and alighted in a field which sloped
      steeply down to a tiny brook, but the agony of the leap was too much for
      the rider. With a stifled groan he fell to the ground, and Harkaway, not
      understanding his grievous plight, but thankful to find the desperate
      gallop at an end, unconsciously served his master by going quietly down to
      drink at the brook.
    </p>
    <p>
      The pursuers were puzzled at suddenly losing all trace of the
      despatch-bearer. They paused to listen, but no sound of distant
      horse-hoofs fell upon their ear, only somewhat further on they could hear
      children&rsquo;s voices. Riding forward, they came into sight of an orchard in
      which two little girls with their skipping-ropes were playing on the
      daisy-flecked grass. As they skipped they sang an old May-pole song, their
      childish voices rising high and clear in the country quiet:
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Come, ye young men, come along,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      With your music, dance and song;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Bring your lasses in your hands,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      For &rsquo;tis that which love commands.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Then to the May-pole haste away,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      For &rsquo;tis now a holiday.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      It is the choice time of the year,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      For the violets now appear;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Now the rose receives its birth,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      And pretty primrose decks the earth.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Then to the May-pole haste away,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      For &rsquo;tis now a holiday.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly they broke off, and the elder child cried out: &ldquo;Look! Look, Meg.
      There be soldiers yonder.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Three, four, five of them!&rdquo; said the little one, counting with keen
      interest.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And two of them have left their horses and be coming this way,&rdquo; said Nan.
      &ldquo;See their red ribbons; they be King&rsquo;s soldiers.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Nan, I&rsquo;m frightened! They said they would hang the boys and drown the
      girls!&rdquo; cried Meg, clinging to her sister.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That was because the children of Broxash sang
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      If you offer to plunder, or take our cattle,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Be assured we will bid you battle.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      said Nan, reassuringly. &ldquo;We were only singing the May-pole song.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Nevertheless her eyes grew large with fright as the soldier approached.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Here, you brats!&rdquo; he shouted. &ldquo;Have you seen a Puritan officer gallop by
      this way?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, we have been skipping,&rdquo; she replied, sturdily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A wounded man on a bay horse.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We have not seen him&mdash;he hath not been here,&rdquo; said Nan.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Curse him! What a dance he hath led us! How a man that&rsquo;s been twice hit
      can ride across country that fashion, beats me. The devil must be in him.
      Come, mate, we must to horse again, and push on&mdash;the plaguey fellow
      shan&rsquo;t give us the slip.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They hastened back to rejoin their comrades, and Nan looked wistfully
      after them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I hope they won&rsquo;t find him,&rdquo; she said, shivering. &ldquo;If they do they&rsquo;ll
      kill him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;m glad we&rsquo;re not men,&rdquo; said Meg, picking up her skipping-rope. &ldquo;We
      shall never have to kill folk.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      By this time Gabriel had recovered his senses, and the sight of the
      Malvern Hills roused him to the remembrance that he was near Bosbury; with
      a vague idea of getting Hilary to bind up his wounds for him, and then of
      somehow reaching his father, he staggered to his feet, hoping to find
      Harkaway at no great distance. The horse, however, was nowhere to be seen,
      and, with faltering steps, he made his way with great difficulty across
      the field to a gap which he saw in the hedge. The children&rsquo;s voices
      reached him, and helped him to persevere.
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      &ldquo;Here each bachelor may choose
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      One that will not faith abuse,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Nor repay with coy disdain
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Love that should be loved again.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      It was the same maypole song that he had listened to years ago at Bosbury
      just after their betrothal.
    </p>
    <p>
      Utterly spent with pain and loss of blood, the effort of making his way
      through the gap in the hedge proved more than flesh could bear.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis no use&mdash;no use!&rdquo; he thought, despairingly as he entered
      the orchard. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t go another step! My God! Must I be so near to
      Hilary, and yet die like a dog in a ditch?&rdquo; He reeled back, and, with a
      groan, fell senseless to the ground, to the horror and dismay of the
      children, who dropped their skipping-ropes and fled in terror.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The Puritan!&rdquo; they screamed; &ldquo;he has fallen down dead!&rdquo; But before very
      long curiosity conquered terror; they stole back hand-in-hand, and gazed
      at him with awe-struck faces.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He looks as if he were asleep,&rdquo; said little Meg.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s how folks do look,&rdquo; explained Nan, &ldquo;just asleep, you know. But all
      the time they&rsquo;re really awake up in the sky.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wondering, perhaps, why we don&rsquo;t understand,&rdquo; said Meg, dreamily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, see!&rdquo; cried Nan, in great excitement, &ldquo;he&rsquo;s down here still, he&rsquo;s not
      dead. His hand is moving!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel tried to get up, but fell back again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! what hellish pain!&rdquo; he moaned.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What can we do for you, sir?&rdquo; said Nan.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who is it?&rdquo; he asked, looking up in a dazed way. &ldquo;Where?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We be Farmer Chadd&rsquo;s children, sir, and this is our orchard nigh to
      Bosbury,&rdquo; replied the little girl.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How far from Bosbury?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis but a little way across the hop-yards, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If I could see Hilary before I die!&rdquo; he muttered. &ldquo;I <i>will</i> see her!
      I <i>will</i> see her! What became of Harkaway? Children, do you see a
      riderless horse near?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They ran off and soon returned with beaming faces.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There be a strange horse down by the brook,&rdquo; said Nan. &ldquo;A bay with two
      white feet.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is gentle enough; could you bring him here for me? I am sorely hurt.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They gladly promised and ran down the sloping field, leaving Gabriel in a
      curious borderland of semi-consciousness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall remember it all if I try,&rdquo; he reflected. &ldquo;My head is getting
      clearer. There was something I had to do! What on earth was it? Massey
      trusted me with something. If the Prince overpowered him I was to go&mdash;where?
      This agony makes all else a blank! I shall be no better than that daft
      vagabond who woke me last night. Ha! the despatches! I remember all now!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With intense anxiety he felt for them. They were bloodstained but safe,
      and exhausted with the effort of concealing them once more, he sank back
      in a dead faint.
    </p>
    <p>
      Now it chanced that on this Wednesday morning the Litany being ended, Dr.
      Coke and Hilary left the church and went to see Farmer Chadd, who was in
      great distress because his horses had been seized by the Canon Frome
      garrison. They were talking to him in the farmyard when his two little
      daughters came running up to beg his help.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a horse, father, down by the brook,&rdquo; they explained breathlessly,
      &ldquo;and the wounded Puritan officer in the orchard asked us to fetch it, but
      it won&rsquo;t let us come near.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A Puritan officer? One of the fugitives from Ledbury, I reckon,&rdquo; said
      Farmer Chadd.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is wounded, do you say, child?&rdquo; asked the Vicar.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, sir,&rdquo; said Nan, dropping a curtsey. &ldquo;Wounded and well-nigh dead.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish you would stable the horse and say naught about it in the village,
      Chadd, as likely as not the poor fellow will be haled to prison if the
      Canon Frome folk hear of this,&rdquo; said Dr. Coke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;d do aught that would go against <i>them</i>&rdquo; said the farmer, thinking
      wrathfully of the looting and plundering he had had to endure.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will give help to the officer, then, and you will put up the horse,&rdquo;
       said the Vicar. &ldquo;Come, children, show us where this poor Puritan lies.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary, with a horrible presentiment of coming sorrow, hastened across the
      orchard, and, with a low cry, knelt down on the grass beside the wounded
      man.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Uncle,&rdquo; she said, looking up with wild eyes, &ldquo;see who it is!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Poor boy! poor boy!&rdquo; said the Vicar, with deep concern. &ldquo;What a change
      since yesterday, when he stood bold and strong at the head of his
      soldiers. He has swooned. Help me, dear, to remove his armour.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary obeyed, and, giving the helmet to Nan and Meg, asked them to fetch
      water from the brook. The Vicar, who had some little knowledge of surgery,
      managed, for the time, to staunch the wounds, and, presently, feeling a
      woman&rsquo;s soft fingers at his throat unfastening his gorget, Gabriel
      regained consciousness, and lay watching the sweet, grave face which bent
      over him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hilary!&rdquo; he said, faintly. &ldquo;Thank God! Now I can die in peace!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, no,&rdquo; she said, smoothing back the hair from his forehead. &ldquo;You must
      live, Gabriel, I&mdash;we&mdash;cannot spare you. Uncle Coke is half a
      leech, he will bind up your wounds.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar gave a rueful smile. &ldquo;I may be half a leech, but I&rsquo;m not a whole
      conjuror, and can&rsquo;t make a couple of handkerchiefs into bandages that will
      serve. No, Hilary, you must get me some linen from Mrs. Chadd. Here come
      the children with the water; take them with you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar went to rescue the helmet full of water which Nan in her haste
      was spilling by the way, and Hilary bent over her lover.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will be back again very soon, Gabriel; promise not to move rashly. I
      wish I need not leave you&mdash;I can&rsquo;t bear to go.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He raised her hand to his lips. &ldquo;What a nightmare these years of war have
      been! If we could but wake and forget them!&rdquo; he said, with a tired sigh.
    </p>
    <p>
      But before anything further could be said the Vicar interposed,
      cheerfully, &ldquo;Come, my dear, the children will help to carry the things,
      and not even Prince Rupert&rsquo;s Protestation forbids me to obey the
      commandment and give a thirsty enemy a cup of water to drink.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      While Hilary and the children ran to the farm he held the helmet to the
      wounded man&rsquo;s lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel drank thirstily. &ldquo;If you have signed the Protestation, sir, the
      less you have to do with me the better,&rdquo; he said, reviving a little.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have not signed it,&rdquo; said the Vicar, sturdily, &ldquo;and I have every
      intention of taking you to my house that you may be properly tended.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, indeed I dare not let you run such a risk; if aught should befall
      you what would become of Hilary?&rdquo; said Gabriel, his eyes full of anxiety.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are right to think of her; you two were old friends at Hereford.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;More than friends&mdash;we were betrothed before this war divided us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yet, did we not agree yesterday when you spared Bosbury Cross that, spite
      of the war, there was one bond which still united us?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You would not object to my suit?&rdquo; said Gabriel, eagerly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;On the contrary, I should welcome it. The friendship betwixt the Harfords
      and the Unetts is a two generation friendship, and truth to tell, I have
      just learnt that my niece is in some danger from the attentions of Colonel
      Norton&mdash;a man in whom I have been much deceived.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel lay musing for a minute, then asked abruptly&mdash;&ldquo;How soon could
      I be fit to ride, sir?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It will be a matter of a month at least,&rdquo; said the Vicar.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Surely, I could ride as far as Hereford&mdash;to my father?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, &rsquo;tis out of the question. Oh, we will hide you safely
      somehow. Hilary hath a ready wit and will doubtless hit on some device.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If I could but have speech with my father,&rdquo; said Gabriel, restlessly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I could myself ride over for him, and he could dress your wounds,&rdquo;
       suggested the Vicar.
    </p>
    <p>
      With an effort Gabriel rallied his failing powers.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will be true with you,&rdquo; he said, firmly. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis not for that I
      would see him, but I bear despatches to Fairfax and Cromwell, and am in
      honour bound to see them in safe hands.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Despatches!&rdquo; exclaimed the Vicar with a troubled look. &ldquo;This is a grave
      matter. Yet &rsquo;twas honest of you to tell me. I think I might at
      least bring your father to-night to see you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And should I die ere he comes&mdash;promise to give them to him,&rdquo; said
      Gabriel, pleadingly. &ldquo;Dying folk must often have asked your aid, Vicar. I
      ask that&mdash;nothing but that?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now, may God forgive me if I do amiss,&rdquo; muttered the Vicar. Then, turning
      to meet the eager hazel eyes which watched him so intently, &ldquo;I promise
      you, my poor boy. Be at rest.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      After this Gabriel lay with closed eyes until he heard Hilary&rsquo;s voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I fear we have seemed long,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;and you are suffering so much.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He smiled. &ldquo;Not now,&rdquo; he replied, reviving for a while from sheer
      happiness in the change that had come over her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You little folk run over and play under the apple trees,&rdquo; said the Vicar
      to Nan and Meg, &ldquo;while I tend my patient.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And with Hilary&rsquo;s help he rapidly bound up the wounds in a somewhat rough
      and ready fashion, and put the arm in a sling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Captain Harford has told me much, my dear, while you have been gone,&rdquo; he
      remarked. &ldquo;Do you feel disposed to take on you the duties of nurse?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary blushed and glanced shyly at her lover. &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; she replied. &ldquo;Where
      can we best shelter Gabriel?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He thinks that his presence at the Vicarage could not be hid from the
      villagers. We must not risk awakening Colonel Norton&rsquo;s suspicions.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Uncle! Why should we not use the room in the Church tower? The
      bell-ringers never go up the steps. No one but Zachary ever goes, and
      Zachary must be taken into the secret.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis well thought of, child; Captain Harford would be safe enough
      there if we can once carry him up unseen.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why should you not give out that you mean to use the tower room for your
      antiquities?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You can truthfully say that you are making a study of bones,&rdquo; said
      Gabriel, smiling in the midst of his pain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The notion is not amiss, but yet it will be hard to take him there in
      broad daylight,&rdquo; said the Vicar, securing the last bandage.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary&rsquo;s face lighted up. &ldquo;Why,&rdquo; she cried, eagerly, &ldquo;you and Zachary
      might carry him in a hop-pocket? If you go by way of the hop-yards you
      would scarce be likely to meet a soul, and if you did, &rsquo;tis easily
      explained that you are carrying something you have just discovered. The
      villagers will only think &rsquo;tis what Mrs. Durdle calls one of
      Parson&rsquo;s &lsquo;antics.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar turned with a smile to Gabriel. &ldquo;Did I not tell you she would
      hit on some device? But before I go I will help you to move to the other
      side of the hedge, for there is a right of way through this orchard to
      Ledbury, and you had best not risk being seen.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The pursuit was hot, but I think it must be over by now,&rdquo; said Gabriel,
      allowing himself to be helped to a place where he was sheltered from the
      orchard by an elm tree and a low hedge.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There! now don&rsquo;t stir till I return,&rdquo; said the Vicar. &ldquo;I will go home and
      bid Mrs. Durdle prepare the room, and bring Zachary back with me, as soon
      as may be. And you little people, let Mistress Hilary know if anyone comes
      in sight.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, sir,&rdquo; said the children, curtseying.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are like two good little watchmen,&rdquo; he added, smiling and patting
      their heads. &ldquo;See that you don&rsquo;t fall asleep at your posts, for the sun is
      hot. Now,&rdquo;&mdash;he thought to himself with a humorous gleam in his eyes&mdash;&ldquo;if
      Hilary and her lover do not patch up their ancient quarrel I shall wish I
      had sent her on this errand instead of going myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0040" id="link2HCH0040"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XL.
    </h2>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Duelling, in this country at least, is no longer legal, and we believe
      that war, which has been aptly styled international duelling, is alike
      doomed.. . . It is certain that the time must assuredly come (for is not
      this the darkness before the dawn?), and it will be probably sooner than
      we can conceive, when there will be a tremendous upheaval and revulsion of
      feeling with regard to it.</i>&rdquo; &mdash;J. J. Green.
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">F</span>or some little
      time Gabriel lay back in perfect silence against the grassy bank, and,
      spite of the acute pain he was in, he nevertheless felt ready to echo the
      children&rsquo;s chorus which floated to them from beneath the apple trees&mdash;<i>For
      it is now a holiday</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary sat on the grass beside him, and from time to time he opened his
      eyes to watch the tender womanly hand as it ministered to his needs, or to
      look into the sweet face, as it bent over him. He realised, too, with a
      happy sense of homecoming, that he was indeed in his native county every
      time he caught sight of the lovely Malvern Hills which, in the morning
      light, seemed to take all the hues to be seen on a pigeon&rsquo;s neck, and
      formed a fitting background for Hilary&rsquo;s rare beauty.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ought I to let you do all this for a &lsquo;friendly foe&rsquo;?&rdquo; he said, looking up
      at her with a hint of the old mirth in his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Forget what I said yesterday, Gabriel. I did not mean half of it,&rdquo; she
      said, blushing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I knew you meant to keep your promise&mdash;that was my sole comfort last
      night at Ledbury,&rdquo; he replied, with a sigh.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary continued nervously, but yet with no little force: &ldquo;I went that
      very afternoon to see Dame Elizabeth, and you were right, it was just as
      you said. Oh! I hope I may never again see the false face that deceived
      me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;God grant you never may!&rdquo; said Gabriel. And then a silence fell between
      them, and the merry talk of the children could be heard.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary mused sadly over her shortcomings, but presently, noticing a change
      in her lover&rsquo;s face, gave an exclamation of dismay.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Gabriel! how white your lips are growing! Is the pain so great?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis very bearable while you are near,&rdquo; he said, his eyes resting
      on her with indescribable tenderness. &ldquo;I was thinking how love can lift
      one out of all that is worst in the world.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She instantly responded to his thought as in the first days of their
      betrothal. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis stronger than war, or differing views,&rdquo; she said,
      gently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, or death,&rdquo; he replied.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t talk of death!&rdquo; she cried, shuddering. &ldquo;Oh! when we heard of the
      battle this morning, and I remembered the cruel words I had spoken to you,
      I thought my heart would break.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My <i>beloved</i>,&rdquo; he said. And in the strong emphasis of the word there
      seemed to lurk all the pent-up passion of the long years of separation.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the first time since that September morning when they had talked in
      the garden at Hereford, before hearing of Powick fight, their lips met in
      a kiss that was like a sacrament, and each knew that nothing could ever
      again part them.
    </p>
    <p>
      But their happiness was short-lived, for the children ran through the gap
      in the hedge, and Little Meg said, breathlessly, &ldquo;Mistress Hilary! there
      be someone coming into the orchard.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It looks like one of the officers from Canon Frome,&rdquo; said Nan, uneasily,
      her mind dwelling on cattle-lifting and plundering.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What if it should be Norton!&rdquo; said Gabriel, trying to get up.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You must not show yourself,&rdquo; said Hilary, earnestly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;All will be ruined if you are seen. Dear love, promise me, and then I
      shall have no fear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis true I should be worse than no defence,&rdquo; said Gabriel,
      reluctantly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary hastily placed her cloak so as to screen him a little better from
      view, and made the children sit in the gap to block the way.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nan and Meg, you will not betray him, I know,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sit there and weave daisy chains.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Glancing at the approaching figure, she saw that it was indeed Norton,
      and, anxious to prevent him from drawing too near to the hedge, she went
      forward to meet him. She wondered now how she could ever have been
      deceived by him, and hated herself for having allowed him for a moment to
      make her distrust Gabriel&rsquo;s love.
    </p>
    <p>
      Norton&rsquo;s greeting was eager and full of charm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This is clearly a red-letter day in my calendar, Mistress Hilary. First,
      I have news of Prince Rupert&rsquo;s success at Ledbury, and then I have the
      crowning happiness of meeting you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis indeed a fair morning,&rdquo; said Hilary. &ldquo;You are doubtless going
      by the field-path to Ledbury to gain further tidings. I will not detain
      you. Good day, sir,&rdquo; and she curtseyed, hoping to dismiss him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! I am in no haste; my horse has cast a shoe, and I have sent it on to
      Diggory, the smith. Prince Rupert is sure to pursue Massey most of the way
      to Gloucester, &rsquo;tis ever his failing to press the chase too far. I
      will rest awhile in this pleasant orchard.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Poor Hilary, only longing for him to go, felt that she was indeed being
      punished for having allowed him in former times to be too much with her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder whether you have thought over what I said to you the day before
      yesterday,&rdquo; observed Norton, eagerly watching her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The day before yesterday,&rdquo; she said, with a puzzled look. &ldquo;What happened
      then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are not complimentary,&rdquo; he replied, laughing. &ldquo;Perhaps you have
      forgotten all about it. But I remember very well that I had the happiness
      of walking with you from the Hill Farm to the Vicarage, and of offering
      you&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Was that only the day before yesterday? To me it seems half a lifetime
      ago,&rdquo; said Hilary.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You were not altogether kind to me; in fact, when we got to the Vicarage
      you followed Colonel Massey&rsquo;s example, and beat a hasty retreat.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She made a brave effort to divert him from the subject, observing with a
      smile: &ldquo;And I am going to beg you, sir, not to follow the example of
      Prince Rupert; pray do not push the pursuit any further.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pardon me,&rdquo; said Norton more gravely, &ldquo;but I have every intention of
      carrying it to a successful end. Don&rsquo;t you understand that I love you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, it is of no use,&rdquo; she replied. &ldquo;I cannot listen to your suit. Pray,
      pray leave me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will not leave you,&rdquo; he said, fiercely, &ldquo;till I clearly understand why
      you are thus cold and indifferent.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, I have no love to give you,&rdquo; she said, with quiet dignity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never mind that, my love is hot enough to serve for both.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do not <i>want</i> your love,&rdquo; she said, emphatically.
    </p>
    <p>
      His eyes gleamed with an anger that made him look devilish.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The meaning of which is, that you love another. Rumour spoke truly, and
      the young Parliamentary captain who spared Bosbury Cross&mdash;:&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary started, and a wave of colour suffused her face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You see I know all about it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She remained quite silent, with drooped head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you love this Captain Harford? Speak&mdash;for I <i>will</i> know the
      truth!&rdquo; he said, savagely.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary raised her head. There was such suffering and pathos in her face
      that any man not the thrall of passion would have been touched. &ldquo;Sir, all
      our lives we have loved each other. Oh! if you understood, you would be
      generous,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why did you not tell me the truth on Monday?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Our betrothal had ended at the beginning of the war. I vowed I would not
      love a rebel. But yesterday, when we met again, I found that war was
      weaker than love, that it could not really part us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So you became disloyal to your King?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, no; I shall always honour His Majesty; but in truth I can think of
      only one man in all the world, and that&rdquo;&mdash;her face lighted up&mdash;&ldquo;that
      is Gabriel Harford, for he <i>is</i> all the world to me. I have told you
      the whole truth, sir, and now, by your honour as a gentleman, I ask you to
      leave me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Shall I tell you what you have done?&rdquo; said Norton, speaking low and
      rapidly. &ldquo;You have made me all the more in love with you&mdash;all the
      more determined to win you. What is this Captain Harford? A mere boy, your
      old playmate, perchance a pleasant comrade, but wholly unfit to be your
      lord and master.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; she said, with a new dignity in her manner, &ldquo;he is the man I love.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton muttered an impatient oath.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Had he been of our party I might have left you to him with a good grace.
      But nothing shall make me yield to a miserable Roundhead, a strait-laced
      Puritan, who glories in self-control, and keeps a conscience on his
      premises. Much good may his conscience do him! I have him like a rat in a
      trap!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The words almost paralysed her with terror. What did he know? What did he
      mean? Had he caught sight of Gabriel?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you!&rdquo; cried Norton, passionately. &ldquo;You are in my power. Do you
      understand that?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Beside himself with wrath, Gabriel dragged himself up on to his knees and
      drew his sword from the scabbard. Meg and Nan glanced round at him
      uneasily; and Hilary, conscious of the movement though her back was turned
      to the hedge, grew desperate in her anxiety.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, no!&rdquo; she panted. &ldquo;You are too brave a man to take so base an
      advantage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pshaw!&rdquo; said Norton, sneeringly. &ldquo;The man&rsquo;s a fool who neglects to use
      his advantages. You think only of the dear Puritan. You only fear what I
      may do to him. Well, I will confide in you. I have sent a trusty
      ambassador to Ledbury, and he is sure to make Captain Harford prisoner.
      Then, when he is in my power&mdash;well, there are many ways of
      exterminating rats&mdash;and rebels.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary choked back a sob, and moved a few steps from the hedge.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am told,&rdquo; said Norton with a cruel smile, &ldquo;that Sir Francis Doddington
      hung fourteen rebels at Andover t&rsquo;other day. And elsewhere twelve of them
      were strung up to one apple-tree. We might hang Captain Harford from one
      of those apple-trees yonder; it would be a fitting death for a
      Herefordshire man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With a wild hope of getting him out of the orchard she moved as though to
      go, trusting that he might follow&rsquo;. But Norton was too quick for her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come! cheer up and don&rsquo;t be so silent,&rdquo; he said, throwing his arm round
      her waist. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll talk no more of the Puritan. Let us kiss and be
      friends.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t touch me!&rdquo; she cried, indignantly, wrenching herself from his
      embrace. &ldquo;You are worse than a murderer.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton laughed mockingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now that was a foolish speech, for as I warned you, the game is in my
      hands.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank God! there is someone coming,&rdquo; cried Hilary, catching sight of a
      man slowly approaching by the path from Ledbury, and running swiftly
      towards him. &ldquo;Why, Waghorn! is it you?&rdquo; she exclaimed, recognising the
      well-known face of the wood-carver beneath a bandage tied about his
      forehead. &ldquo;You have little liking for us, but I know you will help me
      now.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mistress!&rdquo; said Waghorn grimly, &ldquo;I have a word to speak with yonder
      Governor of Canon Frome, and I cannot serve you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton strode angrily towards him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A word to speak, indeed! What have you been about? Where is your
      prisoner?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary in great astonishment stood by, glancing from one to the other.
      Waghorn, then, had been the Colonel&rsquo;s ambassador! Had he suddenly turned
      Royalist, or was it merely to revenge himself on Gabriel that he had
      become a spy?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; said Waghorn, &ldquo;I did all that you told me. Last night, having
      changed my outward man, I followed Captain Harford wherever he went in
      Ledbury. As the shadow followeth the wayfaring man when the sun shineth,
      so did I follow him. I saw Colonel Massey give him the despatches.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well! Well! did you take them?&rdquo; asked Norton, impatiently.
    </p>
    <p>
      Not heeding the interruption, Waghorn stolidly resumed his tale.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He hid them in his buff coat and lay down to sleep by the market-house. I
      well-nigh took the packet from him, but a cur barked and he roused up,
      gripped me by the arm and called the guard.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Idiot! I might have known that you would bungle the business. How was it
      you did not get him disabled in the skirmish instead of being knocked on
      the head yourself?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I adjured Prince Rupert&rsquo;s men to fire on him,&rdquo; said Waghorn, with solemn
      vindictiveness, &ldquo;and the ball of the avenger entered into his arm; but he
      still galloped on, clinging to the neck of his steed. Then one of the
      ungodly clouted me on the head and I saw him no more.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His slow speech, and the failure of the enterprise irritated Norton past
      endurance.
    </p>
    <p>
      Seizing him by the coat-collar, he gave him a sound shaking.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You prating, pig-headed, sour-faced lunatic! I wish I had managed the
      matter myself. Did you not ask which way he rode? Was there no pursuit by
      the Prince&rsquo;s troopers?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn groaned. &ldquo;Mercy! Mercy! Oh, my head! My head! Remember I&rsquo;ve a sore
      head.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve no head at all, you gaping fool, or you wouldn&rsquo;t have made such a
      cursed mess of this matter. Did you not ask, I say? Could no man give you
      news of him?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Freeing himself and groaning as he adjusted his bandages, the wood-carver
      replied, sullenly, &ldquo;I have news of him. When you will leave me time to
      speak, I will tell you all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Speak then,&rdquo; said Norton, impatiently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am a righteous avenger,&rdquo; said Waghorn, with an air of offended dignity,
      &ldquo;and, though thrice baulked, I will yet lay hands on the ungodly man that
      dallies with malignants, and doth not destroy graven images. &lsquo;Let his days
      be few, and let another take his office!&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go to! You are not preaching on a tub, you fool, but speaking to a King&rsquo;s
      officer,&rdquo; said Norton, with an angry frown.
    </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn continued deliberately. &ldquo;When I could think of aught but my
      clouted head, I sought to pursue Captain Harford, asking from one and
      another if they had seen a wounded Parliament officer on a bay horse. At
      length I fell in with some troopers who vowed they had pursued him in this
      direction, but had lost all trace of him and were returning to Prince
      Rupert.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They had seen him this way?&rdquo; said Norton, musingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn turned his piercing eyes on Hilary and looked at her fixedly. She
      tried bravely to keep an unmoved face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Doubtless he had his reasons for riding towards Bosbury,&rdquo; said the spy,
      with scornful emphasis.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A good notion,&rdquo; cried Norton. &ldquo;After all, you have a head on your
      shoulders, Waghorn. Methinks the lady&rsquo;s face hath an anxious look.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; said Hilary, drawing herself up, &ldquo;no maiden could listen to such
      words as you have forced me to hear to-day without showing some sign of
      anxiety.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn watched her with the eyes of a hawk, and his solemn voice broke
      the brief silence which had fallen upon them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I adjure you, Mistress, by all you hold most sacred, to speak the truth.
      Have you seen Captain Gabriel Harford?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl breathed hard, but kept silence, gazing like one transfixed into
      Waghorn&rsquo;s keen eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Speak, Mistress,&rdquo; he repeated. &ldquo;Have you seen Captain Gabriel Harford?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I saw him&mdash;yesterday,&rdquo; gasped Hilary.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We know that. Have you seen him this morning?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a minute&rsquo;s pause, while in agony she tried to see some way out
      of the dilemma. But way there was none.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have seen him?&rdquo; urged Waghorn, merciless as any Inquisitor.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; she replied, a sob rising in her throat.
    </p>
    <p>
      Norton, with fury in his eyes, stepped nearer to her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You dare to protect this rebel, and yet you knew that he carried
      despatches to the rebel army?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary bowed her head in assent, then turned away.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When did you see him?&rdquo; urged Norton, wrathfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      She looked up, and her terrible distress was evident.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I saw him&mdash;anon,&rdquo; she said, in a broken voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How long ago?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A little while before you came,&rdquo; she faltered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Which way did he ride?&rdquo; cried Norton, maddened at the thought that this
      girl was thwarting them and making them lose precious time. &ldquo;Tell me at
      once.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Utter despair seized her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh!&rdquo; she sobbed, &ldquo;have pity on me!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pity!&rdquo; said Norton, savagely. &ldquo;Have you pitied me? Tell me which way he
      went, or I&rsquo;ll&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      At this, Gabriel, driven desperate, struggled to his feet, but, turning
      faint, was forced for a while to lean against one of the hedge-row elms.
      The children, terrified by his movement and by the dispute in the orchard,
      dropped their daisy-chains and ran at full speed down the field, while the
      Colonel, becoming aware of a stir behind him, glanced round.
    </p>
    <p>
      That was too much for Hilary. She sprang forward and diverted Norton&rsquo;s
      attention by pointing to the hills. Her voice was the voice of one goaded
      beyond all endurance.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He rode yonder!&rdquo; she cried, &ldquo;to Malvern!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton turned to the wood-carver. &ldquo;Haste, Waghorn! Take word to my servant
      at the blacksmith&rsquo;s, and do you ride with him in pursuit. I have a word to
      say to this lady.&rdquo; Waghorn was only too ready to undertake such congenial
      work, and the moment he was gone Norton seized Hilary roughly by the
      wrists.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By your tears and your pretences,&rdquo; he said, with fierce scorn, &ldquo;you have
      done your best to hinder me; but I would have you know, Mistress, that I
      am not one to be baffled. You are wholly at my mercy now.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      In wild terror, she felt the pitiless brute force of the man.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let me go!&rdquo; she panted, struggling to free herself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, by Heaven! you shall not,&rdquo; said Norton, passionately. &ldquo;Waghorn can
      settle matters with your lover, and I will make sure of you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      In the agony of her resistance she forgot everything else, and was as much
      startled as Norton when suddenly an indignant voice rang out close to
      them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Coward!</i>&rdquo; cried Gabriel, and his tone made the Colonel wince as he
      released Hilary, and stood staring at the wounded man, who, apparently
      almost at his last gasp, nevertheless confronted him with drawn sword.
    </p>
    <p>
      His left arm was bandaged and in a sling, the sleeve of his buff coat had
      been ripped from wrist to shoulder, and hung down soaked in blood; his
      face was ghastly pale, with eyes like a flaming fire. Norton felt that he
      could not fight one in such extremity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What, the Puritan here, after all!&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;I&rsquo;faith, this is
      excellent. I arrest you, sir, in the King&rsquo;s name.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel&rsquo;s breath came in gasps, but with a gesture he urged Hilary to
      stand back under the trees, and, with flashing eyes, turned upon her
      assailant.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Defend yourself!&rdquo; he cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, an&rsquo; you will fight,&rdquo; said Norton, drawing his sword. &ldquo;Your blood be
      on your own head.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary, with hands clasped on her breast, stood by frozen with horror,
      every shade of colour gone from her lovely face. In awful contrast to the
      peaceful orchard with its grass and daisies, its pink-and-white apple
      blossom, its glimpses of the Malvern hills, was the unequal fight in the
      foreground, the deadly thrust of the flashing swords, the clash of the
      steel, the gasping, sobbing breath of her lover.
    </p>
    <p>
      Everything seemed against Gabriel; not only was he exhausted by pain and
      loss of blood, but he was a shorter, slighter man than the Colonel, and a
      less practised swordsman. He had nothing in his favour but a good cause,
      and a dauntless courage, and these will not ensure success.
    </p>
    <p>
      Although he made a brave fight it was before long only too evident that he
      was failing; twice he staggered and almost fell, and though each time
      recovering himself, Norton was convinced that in another minute he must
      succumb. And now the better side of the Colonel&rsquo;s nature once more
      asserted itself; he felt a certain admiration for his foe, an uneasy
      consciousness that there had been truth in that indignant cry of &ldquo;<i>Coward!</i>&rdquo;
       The thought disturbed him, so did the panting, agonising gasps of the
      Puritan, and an uncomfortable chill went to his heart when, in the heat of
      the combat, he felt a ring which he specially valued slip from his left
      hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly he was taken off his guard; with a desperate thrust Gabriel ran
      him through the body, and in the same instant both duellists fell to the
      ground, the one severely wounded, the other wholly exhausted by the rescue
      of the woman whom he loved, and in the defence of whose honour he had
      spent the last remnants of his failing strength.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0041" id="link2HCH0041"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XLI.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent20">
      &ldquo;Yet since that loving Lord
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Commanded us to love them for His sake,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Even for His sake, and for his sacred Word,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Which in His last bequest He to us spake,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      We should them love, and with their needs partake;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Knowing that, whatsoe&rsquo;er to them we give,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      We give to Him by Whom we all doe live.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Spenser.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>here was no more
      skipping that day for Nan and Meg; frightened out of their senses, they
      made their way home, and were just crossing the stable-yard when their
      father caught sight of them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have stabled that bay horse as Vicar said,&rdquo; he remarked, &ldquo;and do you
      two little maids keep a still tongue in your heads or we may get into
      trouble. Why, what&rsquo;s amiss with you both?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, father,&rdquo; said Nan, sobbing, &ldquo;our wounded Puritan is going to fight
      the officer from Canon Frome, who is in the orchard threatening Mistress
      Hilary.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll teach un to mind his manners in my orchard!&rdquo; said Farmer Chadd,
      hastily picking up a stout cudgel. &ldquo;Threatening did you say? and the lady
      there with no better protection than a wounded soldier! Good Lord! but
      these evil living Cavaliers will be the ruin o&rsquo; the land! Run in to your
      mother, my maids, and say I&rsquo;ll be back soon for dinner.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Just as he reached the orchard by one entrance the Vicar and Zachary
      entered at the opposite side, and all three men gazed in horror at the
      sight before them. The Governor of Canon Frome was stretched out on the
      grass, bleeding and unconscious, and Gabriel Harford, to all appearance
      lifeless, lay with his head on Hilary&rsquo;s lap.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar bent over him and felt his heart.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He still lives! but how can he possibly have fought Colonel Norton when
      in such a plight?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was to save me, sir,&rdquo; said Hilary. &ldquo;Oh! let us take him quickly to
      shelter before it is too late.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s life in this plaguey Governor o&rsquo; Canon Frome, sir,&rdquo; said Farmer
      Chadd, &ldquo;What be we to do with un?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you and your wife could bind up his wound; the best way would be to
      take word to his men, and get them to bear him hence on a litter. Could
      you do that, Chadd, and say naught as to Captain Harford? He is the son of
      Dr. Bridstock Harford, of Hereford.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then I&rsquo;ll do anything in the world for un, for Dr. Harford saved my good
      woman&rsquo;s life,&rdquo; said Farmer Chadd. &ldquo;You shelter the young gentleman, sir,
      and me and the missus will see to this here plaguey Colonel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With Zachary&rsquo;s help the Vicar lifted Gabriel on to the bier which they had
      brought from the church, and carefully covering him with sacking they bore
      him down through the hopyards to Bosbury. Fortunately, it was the
      dinner-hour, and they did not encounter a single person, but were able to
      cress the churchyard and to carry their burden up the step-ladder to the
      first floor of the tower. Here they found Mrs. Durdle hard at work; she
      had already laid a mattress on the floor, and was bustling about with a
      broom in despair at the dust and the cobwebs which had accumulated.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do wish I had time to scrub the place down, sir,&rdquo; she lamented. &ldquo;It
      bean&rsquo;t fit for a dog to lay in, let alone a Christian.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never mind,&rdquo; said the Vicar, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll warrant &rsquo;tis cleaner than
      Oxford Castle, and the main thing is to hide him and save his life.
      Zachary, can you fix boards in three of the windows, or at night the
      villagers may see our light?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Leaving the wounded man to the kindly offices of Mrs. Durdle and Hilary,
      both of them well skilled in sick-nursing, the Vicar hastened back to his
      house, returning before long with a box full of pre-historic bones under
      one arm and a flagon of Hollands under the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If anyone chances to ask you why we come to and fro to this tower,
      Zachary,&rdquo; he remarked, toiling up the ladder and setting down his burden,
      &ldquo;you can tell them I am keeping my antiquities here, and can say you&rsquo;ve
      seen them. What! hath Captain Harford not yet regained his senses? Try to
      get a little of this down his throat, Hilary. That&rsquo;s better; he will soon
      revive, and I will then set off for Hereford.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The last word seemed to reach Gabriel. He opened his eyes for a moment and
      caught a misty glimpse of Dr. Coke and Hilary with a rough stone tower
      wall and a deeply splayed narrow window in the background. Was he once
      more a prisoner in St. George&rsquo;s Tower at Oxford? The horror of the thought
      roused him. Then he noticed that he was lying in a bed on the floor, and
      that they had removed his buff coat, a perception which vaguely troubled
      him. ..
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My coat?&rdquo; he said, anxiously, yet still not knowing why he wanted it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you cold,&rdquo; said Hilary, spreading another blanket over him. But the
      Vicar understood, and fetched the buff coat from the corner where Durdle
      had thrown it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The inner pocket is here,&rdquo; he said, placing it within reach of Gabriel&rsquo;s
      right hand. And then, with a look of relief, the wounded man drew out the
      despatches.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you give them to my father?&rdquo; he said, pleadingly,
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; replied the Vicar; &ldquo;but I shall beg him to come here first and
      dress your wounds. Will you give them to him yourself?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He may not come in time,&rdquo; said Gabriel, faintly.
    </p>
    <p>
      And the Vicar, seeing that he longed to have the anxiety off his mind
      thrust the despatches into his black doublet, and bidding them keep the
      tower door locked, set off with Zachary to the stable, where the old
      servant saddled the cob for him, and, promising to be about the premises
      ready to give Mrs. Durdle help should she need him, watched his master
      ride off in the direction of Hereford.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Coke was not a man to shirk anything which he had promised, but he
      could not help feeling that in this despatchbearing he had undertaken work
      which he would have preferred to leave alone. To stand quite aloof from
      the strife and never to forget that he was before all things pledged to
      the service of the Prince of Peace had been his aim throughout the Civil
      War; but to refuse the request of one who lay apparently at the point of
      death, seemed to him impossible, while Gabriel&rsquo;s gallant rescue of Hilary
      increased the desire he felt to give him whatever ease of mind was
      possible.
    </p>
    <p>
      On reaching Hereford he rode straight to the physician&rsquo;s house and, learnt
      from the servant that her master was about to ride out into the country.
      However, he was shown into the study.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will not detain you many minutes, sir,&rdquo; he said, after the greetings
      had passed. &ldquo;I know how precious time is to such a busy man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, &rsquo;tis not on an urgent matter of life and death that I am
      riding out this afternoon,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford. &ldquo;I had last night a letter
      from my son, who, it seems, is at Ledbury, and I hope to meet him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Alas!&rdquo; said the Vicar, &ldquo;I bring you bad news of him. There was a sharp
      fight this morning at Ledbury, and your son is sorely wounded. We have
      hidden him from his pursuers in the tower at Bosbury, and he begged me to
      give you these despatches which he was bearing from Massey to Fairfax and
      Cromwell.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Harford took the blood-stained packet, but for a minute could not
      speak. At length he asked further particulars as to Gabriel&rsquo;s wounds, and
      when he, heard of the desperate ride across country and the duel with
      Colonel Norton, hope died out of his face. But, as usual, he was full of
      consideration for his visitor.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am inclined to think, sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;that you have been hurrying to
      and fro in aid of my son and have not yet dined. I will bid them prepare a
      meal, and then, when your horse is rested and my arrangements for leaving
      home made, we might, an&rsquo; you will, ride together to Bosbury.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar, being in truth extremely hungry after his arduous work, did not
      decline the offer of food, and was soon discussing a fat capon in the
      dining-room, while the doctor saw his wife and his assistant, made hasty
      arrangements for a week&rsquo;s absence, and put into his bag such things as he
      thought likely to prove needful for Gabriel&rsquo;s case.
    </p>
    <p>
      His wife, only longing to go herself to Bosbury, watched the preparations
      with tearful eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I cannot bear to feel that the headstrong girl who is to blame for it all
      should have the nursing of him,&rdquo; she sighed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, my dear, had you seen his face at Notting Hill when he was at
      death&rsquo;s door, and I merely gave him her message, you would understand that
      Hilary Unett is the only woman in the world who has a chance of nursing
      him back to life. &rsquo;Tis hard, dear wife, but there comes a time when
      a man is bound to leave even his father and mother and cling to his&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; said the poor mother, wiping her eyes, &ldquo;she is not his wife yet,
      and if he dies, I for one shall account her his murderess.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The physician stooped and kissed her tenderly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Keep up your heart,&rdquo; he said, with assumed cheerfulness. &ldquo;And I know that
      the kindly Vicar will bring you word how he fares, and if need arises
      fetch you to him. But if possible we must avoid that, since he cannot be
      safe when once his hiding-place hath been discovered. The Canon Frome
      garrison will know that he is not far off, and we may be sure will seek to
      lay hands on him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They were interrupted by little Bridstock, who came running into the room
      to show them a toy sword which the groom had made for him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At any rate, you shall never be a soldier,&rdquo; said the mother, catching him
      up in her arms and kissing him. &ldquo;And you can&rsquo;t marry that headstrong
      maid!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall marry little Betty Brydges,&rdquo; said the child, with decision, &ldquo;and
      be Member of Parliament like Sir Robert Harley.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The sublime confidence of his tone made the parents laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis a great thing to know one&rsquo;s own mind,&rdquo; said the doctor,
      patting the child&rsquo;s curly head. &ldquo;We have had our troubles, but at any rate
      our two sons will not vex our souls by weak and unstable characters. There
      is grit in both of them.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I would we had the choosing of their wives,&rdquo; said Mrs. Harford, ruefully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yet you didn&rsquo;t think that the best plan years ago,&rdquo; replied Dr. Harford,
      with a mirthful glance.
    </p>
    <p>
      And recalling their own extremely early and rash marriage, his wife could
      but smile and own that he was right.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her heart relented a little towards Hilary, and when Dr. Coke told her
      from what peril Gabriel had that day rescued her, and spoke words of warm
      gratitude and praise as to her son&rsquo;s courage and sterling character, her
      face brightened, and she watched the two riders mount their horses with a
      more hopeful spirit than might have been expected.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yet could Dr. Harford have looked at that moment into the tower room where
      his son lay, he would certainly have taken his wife with him.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
