    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0042" id="link2HCH0042"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XLII.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;Ruined love, when it is built anew,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Grows fairer than at first, more strong, far greater.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      &mdash;Romeo and Juliet, Act I., Scene I.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">A</span>s Hilary kept
      guard over her lover through those long hours of waiting, seeing the pain
      which she could do nothing to relieve, fearing, as she watched his failing
      strength, that the end was indeed drawing near, it seemed to her that the
      punishment of all her pride and perversity was falling on her with
      overwhelming force.
    </p>
    <p>
      When conscious, he lay absolutely still, too much exhausted to speak, and
      when drifting back into a semi-conscious state his moans tore her heart,
      and filled her, moreover, with terror lest some villager crossing the
      churchyard should possibly hear the sound.
    </p>
    <p>
      At last, when it was growing dusk, she heard horsemen on the road, and,
      after an interval, when doubtless the travellers were leaving their horses
      with Zachary in the stable-yard, came the welcome summons from below which
      had been agreed upon. Durdle clambered down the step-ladder and unbolted
      the door, and in another minute the Vicar and Dr. Harford made their way
      into the dim tower room.
    </p>
    <p>
      Looking up into the physician&rsquo;s strong, calm face, Hilary felt as if a
      load of care had been suddenly lifted from her shoulders. He greeted her
      with more than his usual cordiality, understanding well enough how sore
      her heart must be. Then he knelt down beside the mattress and looked with
      keen anxiety at his son.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will there be any risk in having a light?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar thought not, and, producing a tinder-box, began to strike a
      flint and steel and to kindle the lantern that had been brought from the
      house.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then when the light fell on the white face drawn with pain, the doctor
      regretted that he had not brought Gabriel&rsquo;s mother, for not even at
      Notting Hill had he seemed so near death.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary saw the change in his manner and her heart sank. Yet it comforted
      her a little when Dr. Harford proceeded to examine the shattered arm, for
      surely, she argued to herself, had there been no hope he would have left
      his son&rsquo;s last moments undisturbed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I did the best I could for him in the orchard,&rdquo; said the Vicar; &ldquo;but fear
      it was but rough-and-ready treatment.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The duel would have been enough to defeat the most skilful surgery,&rdquo; said
      the Doctor; &ldquo;and clearly the bone must have been broken as he fell. But he
      hath great rallying power, and I don&rsquo;t despair of him yet.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      On those words Hilary stayed her failing heart all through that terrible
      night, while Gabriel passed from one fainting fit to another, and it
      seemed as if the angel of death hovered above him ready at any moment to
      bear him away from her.
    </p>
    <p>
      At length towards daybreak he slept for a time, and woke with a look of
      renewed life in his face which cheered them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The despatches?&rdquo; he asked, looking from his father to the Vicar.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dr. Coke has given them to me,&rdquo; said the physician.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you will bear them without delay?&rdquo; said Gabriel, anxiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Harford&rsquo;s face clouded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To leave you now may mean your death,&rdquo; he replied. &ldquo;I do not think I can
      leave you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But I promised to guard them with my life, and they are urgent,&rdquo; pleaded
      Gabriel. &ldquo;Let me still serve.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary&rsquo;s eyes grew dim, but she spoke in a low, steady voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will do all that you bid me, sir,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Surely good nursing may
      save him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, my dear,&rdquo; said the physician, &ldquo;if anyone can keep him in life, I
      verily believe &rsquo;tis you; and if he urges me to go, I cannot say him
      nay.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will see them both yourself,&rdquo; said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, the despatches shall be placed in their own hands.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And tell General Cromwell,&rdquo; said Gabriel, &ldquo;that if I recover, I more than
      ever desire to serve the wounded.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With many last directions, the physician at length tore himself away, well
      knowing that it was doubtful whether he should ever again look on his son.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar went to see him mount, glad that he should leave Bosbury before
      the village was astir, and as they quitted the tower Gabriel turned to
      Hilary with a look that made her heart bound.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now do you repay a hundredfold all the suffering of these years,&rdquo; he
      said. &ldquo;Living or dying, I am content.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She bent down and kissed him tenderly. And long before the Vicar rejoined
      them he had sunk into a dreamless sleep.
    </p>
    <p>
      Cheering himself with the old family motto, Dr. Harford rode with all
      speed to Windsor, where he was able to deliver the despatches to Sir
      Thomas Fairfax and to give him an account of Prince Rupert&rsquo;s doings in
      Herefordshire. He found, however, that Cromwell had quitted Windsor, and,
      after taking Blechington House, was sweeping round Oxford, taking
      possession of all the draught horses in the neighbourhood, and thus
      disorganising the King&rsquo;s plan of campaign by preventing Prince Maurice
      from removing the heavy guns from Oxford. It was not until the night of
      the 28th April that the physician was able to overtake him near
      Farringdon, as he was on his way to rejoin Fairfax, after defeating Sir
      Henry Vaughan at Bampton.
    </p>
    <p>
      The troops had halted for a couple of hours beside the Lambourn, and the
      physician on asking to be taken to Cromwell, was conducted by a burly
      corporal to a pollard willow beside the stream. Here, with his armour
      removed, and a little gilt-edged volume in his hand, rested the tired
      leader, his back against the tree trunk, the expression of his face more
      that of a prophet than a soldier. Clearly what Massey would have termed
      the &ldquo;Enoch&rdquo; side of his character was now uppermost, and the &ldquo;David&rdquo; side
      no longer visible.
    </p>
    <p>
      As the corporal mentioned the name of the physician, he promptly slipped
      the little volume into his pocket, and with a brief and not particularly
      ceremonious greeting, received from Dr. Harford&rsquo;s hands the blood-stained
      despatches.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pray be seated, sir,&rdquo; he said, resuming his place under the tree, with
      the fatigued air of one who has for many days known scant rest. Then
      without comment he broke the seal and hastily read Massey&rsquo;s communication.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have done me a greater service than you know by bearing this,&rdquo; he
      said, glancing up from the closely-written sheet.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, I am but my son&rsquo;s ambassador,&rdquo; said the physician. &ldquo;He would have
      delivered the despatch himself, but was attacked and grievously wounded as
      he rode from Ledbury.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Cromwell glanced at the blood-stained letter, which told its own tale.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I remember Captain Harford well,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;He did excellent work at
      Newbury, and again, two months ago, when we were in Wiltshire.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Twas only through his great wish to serve you that I have
      consented to leave him in a risky hiding-place, and in grave peril of
      death from his wounds,&rdquo; said the physician.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Poor lad!&rdquo; said Cromwell, his stern face softened to such tenderness as
      amazed Dr. Harford. &ldquo;The moral courage of his nature is a thousandfold
      more needed in England than mere animal bravery. There is one of my
      troopers, Passey by name, who was his fellow prisoner in Oxford Castle,
      and he hath told me how no skilled physician could have shown a more
      tender care for the fever-stricken inmates.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Should he recover, he more than ever longs to serve the sick and
      wounded,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then in God&rsquo;s name bid him do it,&rdquo; cried Cromwell. &ldquo;I urged him at
      Newbury to wait for clearer guidance, bidding him beware of men and to
      look up to the Lord, letting Him be free to speak and command in his
      heart, and without consulting flesh and blood to do valiantly for God and
      His people. And here, doubtless, in this pain he hath passed through, his
      guidance hath come.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Should I find him living on my return, I will repeat your words to him,&rdquo;
       said Dr. Harford.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;God grant that he may be spared to you, sir,&rdquo; said Cromwell. &ldquo;I know too
      well what the loss of a first-born son means to the heart of a father.
      Look you, an&rsquo; it should chance that Parliament still desires to retain my
      services in the Army, let your son act as one of the mates to the surgeon
      of my troop, thus would he gain knowledge whilst still serving the Cause.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Harford welcomed the suggestion, and anxious to lose no time on his
      return journey, took leave of the great leader, understanding better than
      he had done before what it was that gave this man his extraordinary power.
      He had the insight to perceive what the greatest of modern historians has
      called Cromwell&rsquo;s &ldquo;all-embracing hospitality of soul,&rdquo; and to understand
      that this, combined with a rare sagacity in seeing what was practically
      possible and a matchless faith and courage, marked him out as the true
      steersman in those troubled times.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      During these days Peter Waghorn had in deep depression brooded over the
      utter defeat of his schemes. His fruitless search for Gabriel in Malvern
      had not improved his temper, and on going next day to Canon Frome Manor to
      interview Norton he learnt to his dismay that the Governor had been
      carried home from Bosbury desperately wounded and was raving in delirium.
      Nobody knew how he had met with his wound, but Farmer Chadd had found him
      lying unconscious in his orchard, and it was conjectured that the mishap
      must have occurred while he was seeking to arrest some of Massey&rsquo;s men in
      their flight.
    </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn kept his thoughts to himself and trudged back to Bosbury, guessing
      shrewdly that Captain Harford had all the time been within earshot, and,
      in spite of his wound, had managed to fight his rival. Had he encountered
      Hilary he would probably have asked her some direct question, but the
      villagers reported that she was ill and obliged to keep the house, a
      rumour which was confirmed by her non-appearance at church on the
      following Sunday.
    </p>
    <p>
      On the Thursday a soldier rode up to the wood-carver&rsquo;s house, and Waghorn,
      in some trepidation, went out to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The Governor bids you come with all speed to him at Canon Frome Manor to
      report on some work undertaken for him,&rdquo; said the messenger, looking with
      some curiosity at the austere Puritan.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good; I will come anon,&rdquo; said Waghorn. &ldquo;Doth the Colonel recover him of
      his wound?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, &rsquo;tis healing, and his head is clear, but I counsel you to come
      with all speed, for he&rsquo;s in a devilish ill-humour, and to be kept waiting
      is what he can&rsquo;t abide.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn laid aside his work, and in very low spirits tramped over to Canon
      Frome. To do him justice, he was ill at ease, and detested his alliance
      with an officer of Norton&rsquo;s type. It might be permissible to use the
      ungodly as tools, but as he recalled Hilary&rsquo;s appeal to him in the
      orchard, and reflected that he had left her wholly at the mercy of the
      Colonel, his conscience pricked him. He had, as a matter of fact,
      forgotten everything in the burning desire to prevent Gabriel Harford&rsquo;s
      escape.
    </p>
    <p>
      Evidently the soldier had drawn a truthful picture of Norton&rsquo;s state, for,
      as the wood-carver was ushered into his room, he peremptorily ordered his
      servant to quit him, and beckoning Waghorn to come near to the bed, looked
      up at him with an angry scowl.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, scarecrow! What news do you bring?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No news, sir,&rdquo; said Waghorn, gloomily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You great bungling idiot! Of course, I know you didn&rsquo;t find Captain
      Harford in Malvern; he was lying within a stone&rsquo;s throw of us behind the
      hedge.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And challenged you in order to save Mistress Hilary?&mdash;I guessed as
      much,&rdquo; said the wood-carver. &ldquo;I like your doings very ill, sir, and you
      well deserve what you got.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You vile hypocrite! Do you sit in judgment on me?&rdquo; said Norton. &ldquo;You! a
      turncoat&mdash;a spy! Why, you can&rsquo;t even carry out the dirty work you
      undertake. Prate no more, but tell me what they did with Captain Harford.
      We fell at the same moment, and he, as I well remember, had death in his
      face as he ran me through.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know not where they bore him, sir, and had there been a burial at
      Bosbury I must surely have known of it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Maybe, then, he still lives, and they have hidden him away somewhere.
      Doubtless the Vicar hath sheltered him; he is one of those soft-hearted
      fools who seek to overcome evil with good, and models his life after the
      Sermon on the Mount, not in your fashion, on the cursing Psalms.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was enough truth in this remark to cause Waghorn another twinge of
      conscience.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I may have been ill-advised to leave you in the orchard with Mistress
      Hilary,&rdquo; he admitted. &ldquo;But the flesh is weak, and I remembered only the
      duty of securing that half-hearted sparer of crosses. The lady told a most
      shameless lie, and if her lover was slain in the duel his blood will be on
      her head.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That may be a very soothing reflection for you,&rdquo; said Norton, with a grim
      smile, &ldquo;but it doth not better my case. Now, look you here, I will do
      anything in reason for you if you discover this man&rsquo;s whereabouts. You
      think, had he died, you would have heard of it. Well, by hook or by crook,
      you can surely find out where they have stowed him away. Have you seen
      aught of Mistress Hilary?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay; she keeps the house, I hear, and is ill.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A blind! A mere trick!&rdquo; cried Norton, angrily. &ldquo;Depend upon it, she keeps
      the house to nurse that accursed lover of hers. Oh! if I had but the
      strength to mount my horse, I would soon track him down.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I could keep watch on the house, sir,&rdquo; said Waghorn, &ldquo;and let you know
      who comes and goes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, do that, it may serve,&rdquo; said Norton; &ldquo;for I will not live to be
      thwarted by that Puritan Captain. And, look you, Waghorn, you might do me
      a service by worrying the Vicar. Go and seize the Prayer-book in the
      church, and bid him obey the Parliamentary order and use this blessed
      Directory they have concocted. &rsquo;S life! what wouldn&rsquo;t I give to see
      his face when you confront him with it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And he broke into a laugh, which was cut short by a paroxysm of pain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I could do that,&rdquo; said Waghorn, sternly, a gleam of satisfaction kindling
      in his eyes. &ldquo;I reckon he would take it even more to heart than the
      breaking of his painted window. Ay, I could do that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do it then,&rdquo; said Norton, mockingly, &ldquo;and serve the Cause that you are
      for ever prating about. I care not a jot, for it will serve me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With that he dismissed the wood-carver, and Waghorn walked straight to
      Ledbury, where he had the good fortune to find a trusty waggoner who was
      willing to carry a letter for him to Gloucester and bear back the reply.
      He then adjourned to a small alehouse, where he laboriously wrote an order
      to one of his Puritan friends for a copy of the Directory, which was
      already in use in Gloucester, but had not yet been enforced in
      Herefordshire.
    </p>
    <p>
      Having accomplished this work to his entire satisfaction, he tramped back
      in the dusk of the evening to Bosbury, but had only gone about half the
      distance when the sound of a horseman following him made him look round.
      He saw with a start of surprise that it was none other than Dr. Bridstock
      Harford.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good e&rsquo;en to you, sir,&rdquo; he said, touching his hat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good evening,&rdquo; said the doctor, as he galloped past.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now what should that bode?&rdquo; muttered Waghorn. &ldquo;Where hath he been? And
      whither doth he ride now? I&rsquo;ll light my lantern when I reach home, and see
      if the hoof-prints stop at the Vicarage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0043" id="link2HCH0043"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XLIII.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;But true religion, sprung from God above,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Is like her fountain, full of charity,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Embracing all things with a tender love!
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Full of goodwill and meek expectancy;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Full of true justice and sure verity,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      In heart and voice free, large, even infinite;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Not wedged in strict particularity,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      But grasping all in her vast active spright;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Bright lamp of God! that men would joy in thy
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      pure light.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Henry More, 1642.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>here was something
      indescribably desolate in the blank silence of the tiled house when
      Waghorn unlocked the door, and fumbled in the dusk for the tinder-box. No
      human being shared his dreary home, no animal kept him company or
      enlivened his solitary hours. It was undoubtedly owing to his loneliness
      that his tendency to gloomy fanaticism had, since his father&rsquo;s death, so
      greatly increased. The one joy left him appeared to be this morbid and
      exaggerated desire to root out all that he deemed wrong, and to punish all
      those who withstood his fiery zeal.
    </p>
    <p>
      Without pausing to eat or drink, he kindled his lantern and stole quickly
      out into the street. Early hours were kept in those days, and all seemed
      still in the village; stepping cautiously, he soon descried in the dust
      the prints of horse-hoofs, and was eagerly following them up to see
      whether they turned in at the Vicarage, when Zachary suddenly emerged from
      the gate.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good e&rsquo;en to you, Waghorn,&rdquo; said the clerk, in a more friendly tone than
      he usually employed towards the wood-carver. &ldquo;Ha&rsquo; ye lost summat, that ye
      go groping like the woman that dropped her tenth bit o&rsquo; silver?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay,&rdquo; said Waghorn, &ldquo;that&rsquo;s just what I have done, but I shall find what I
      seek yet, never fear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Zachary with apparent good nature swept his broad foot energetically to
      and fro among the dust, effectually wiping out all trace of the
      hoof-prints.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Better search by daylight,&rdquo; he suggested. &ldquo;And come now to the &lsquo;Bell&rsquo; and
      have a pint o&rsquo; home brewed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn deemed it prudent to accept the invitation, for he desired to get
      into Zachary&rsquo;s confidence, and hoped that some day he might gather from
      the garrulous old man the information he eagerly sought. But on this
      particular night the clerk was on his guard, and the fanatic gained
      nothing by his plot.
    </p>
    <p>
      Meanwhile, in the tower room, Dr. Harford, to his great joy, found his son
      in far better case than he had dared to expect. Hilary&rsquo;s good nursing and
      the patient&rsquo;s healthy life and sound constitution had triumphed over all
      the other drawbacks, and although some weeks must pass before he really
      recovered, all danger to his life was practically over.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar and Hilary listened with intense relief to the doctor&rsquo;s verdict.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The question now is, whether we shall try to remove him,&rdquo; said his
      father. &ldquo;It seems unfair to let you any longer run the risk of sheltering
      a rebel. Yet I scarce know where we could take him; we should never get
      him to Hereford without his being made prisoner.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, don&rsquo;t think of moving him. &rsquo;Tis hard, indeed, if the church
      tower may not afford him sanctuary,&rdquo; said the Vicar. &ldquo;If, indeed, there be
      any risk in the matter, I gladly take it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And how about his nurse? What hath she to say?&rdquo; asked the physician,
      looking into the girl&rsquo;s beautiful face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; said Hilary, blushing vividly, &ldquo;I am his betrothed wife, and only
      this very day we were saying that we wished the Vicar would wed us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel took her hand in his, and looked with eager hope at the kindly
      antiquary who had done so much for him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In the orchard as I lay in even worse plight, sir, you made no objection
      to my suit, and if, indeed, you will make us man and wife before I go, I
      should be for ever your debtor.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar and the physician glanced at each other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This comes, sir, an&rsquo; I mistake not,&rdquo; said Dr. Harford, &ldquo;from your words
      in the churchyard when Waghorn would have had the cross pulled down. I
      have heard that those who hearkened to you could never forget your plea
      for love, which is the bond of peace.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In truth, sir,&rdquo; said the Vicar with a twinkle in his eye, &ldquo;I trow it
      comes from the quiet days in this tower of refuge, when my niece had in
      your absence to nurse the wounded. Very gladly will I wed you, my
      children, and some fine morning we will steal across to the church before
      the villagers are astir. In the meanwhile I can read your banns in here
      each Sunday, with Durdle and Zachary for congregation.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then Dr. Harford told of his interview with Cromwell, and of the
      suggestion for Gabriel&rsquo;s future.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;An you could spare your niece, sir, it would perchance be no bad plan for
      our bride and bridegroom to journey to London, for possibly the Governor
      of Canon Frome may yet give some trouble. Hath anyone heard whether he
      recovers?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Farmer Chadd heard that, though still kept to his bed, he mends apace,&rdquo;
       said the Vicar. &ldquo;Your plan seems an excellent one, sir, and though I shall
      sorely miss Hilary, it would take a load off my mind to know that she was
      in safety.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then by the earliest opportunity I will write to my mother at Notting
      Hill Manor,&rdquo; said the physician. &ldquo;I well know that her house will be at
      your disposal, and that you, sir, would be an honoured guest there.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar gave a courteous little bow, then turned with a mischievous
      glance to the invalid.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing will please me more than to meet Madam Harford, yet don&rsquo;t make
      yourself uneasy, Gabriel, I shall not ride with you on the wedding
      journey, but shall visit you later on, when you are settled down into the
      prose of everyday life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a general laugh, and before long, the Vicar suggested that they
      had better return for the night to the Vicarage, leaving Dr. Harford to
      talk matters over with his son.
    </p>
    <p>
      Far into the small hours the two discussed future plans, and it was
      arranged that the Doctor should not again risk drawing attention to the
      hiding-place by a visit, unless actually sent for. Early in June, when the
      arm was likely to be quite sound again, he proposed to ride over at night,
      bringing Gabriel&rsquo;s mother with him, that she might be present at the
      private marriage, and see her son before he left the west. In the meantime
      he impressed on the wounded man the need of the greatest caution and
      secrecy, and then, stifling the anxiety he could not but feel, bade him
      farewell just as dawn was breaking, and saddling his horse, rode quietly
      back to Hereford before anyone else in Bosbury was stirring.
    </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn, with a grim smile on his sleeping face, dreamt of the bonfire he
      would make of the great Prayer-book in the church. The Vicar wandered in a
      happy valley where wonderful remains of pre-historic times delighted his
      astonished eyes. Hilary had visions of standing beside Gabriel in the
      porch, where in those days weddings were celebrated, and softly breathing
      the &ldquo;I will,&rdquo; which should make her indeed his wife. And Gabriel, in
      wakeful happiness, lay watching the light as it stole softly through the
      narrow window of his hiding-place, musing over the words the Vicar had
      daily used when he visited him:
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent10">
      O Lord, save Thy servant; which putteth his trust in Thee.
    </p>
    <p class="indent10">
      Send him help from Thy holy place: and evermore mightily defend
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      him.
    </p>
    <p class="indent10">
      Let the enemy have no advantage of him; nor the wicked approach to
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      hurt him.
    </p>
    <p class="indent10">
      Be unto him, O Lord, a strong tower; from the face of his enemy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Such a strong tower, such a helper and defender, must be, in his degree,
      prove to his promised wife; and he looked the future in the face far more
      soberly than in the first days of their betrothal long ago, but with a
      calm manliness which augured well for their new life.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar&rsquo;s anxieties, though lessened by Dr. Harford&rsquo;s reassuring report
      as to Gabriel&rsquo;s health, were by no means over. He went about continually
      with the uneasy consciousness that Waghorn was not only a dangerous
      fanatic, but actually a spy, and, as Hilary had discovered in the orchard,
      a spy who had not scrupled to aid such a man as Colonel Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      One evening, when as usual he had repaired to the tower at dusk, taking
      with him the food Gabriel would need during the night, he found himself a
      prey to the most unwonted nervousness. He unlocked the door and summoned
      Hilary from her day&rsquo;s watching in the tower room, waiting with restless
      impatience while she bade her lover good-night and crept down the ladder.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the sight of the girl&rsquo;s happy face cheered him, and he greeted her
      with a smile.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I believe you revel in these ghostly crossings of the churchyard,&rdquo; he
      said, wrapping her long cloak more closely about her. &ldquo;I will be with you
      anon when I have had a word with Gabriel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He watched her till she had disappeared in the Vicarage garden, then paid
      a visit to the invalid, who was far from sharing Hilary&rsquo;s enjoyment of her
      risky journeys to and fro, and always liked to hear that she had gained
      the Vicarage in safety.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When I think of all that you are doing for me, and of the danger of
      discovery, it makes me eager to be gone,&rdquo; he said, watching his kindly
      host as he placed within reach all that he could need.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, I&rsquo;m in no haste to get rid of you,&rdquo; said the Vicar, with a smile.
      &ldquo;You forget that I shall be left a lonely old bachelor when you and Hilary
      fare forth on your wedding journey.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It seems unfair, sir, that I should rob your home of its brightness,&rdquo;
       said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, and not only that, but rouse in me a certain dissatisfaction with my
      lot,&rdquo; said the Vicar, his eyes twinkling. &ldquo;I have serious thoughts of
      entering upon the holy estate of matrimony myself, an I can prevail on Sir
      Richard Hopton to accept my proposal for the hand of his daughter.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hilary&rsquo;s friend, Mistress Frances?&rdquo; said Gabriel, with keen interest.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, but say naught about it till I learn my fate,&rdquo; said the Vicar. &ldquo;The
      lady, for aught I know, may refuse me as decidedly as Hilary refused
      Squire Geers, of Garnons.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The recollection of this made them both laugh, and in much better spirits
      the Vicar quitted the tower, locking the door and putting the key in his
      pocket as he groped his way across the graveyard to the garden gate.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was now dark, save for the stars which just revealed here and there a
      white gravestone or the dim outline of bush or tree. Suddenly the Vicar
      became conscious of the presence of some living creature; though as yet he
      could see nothing he felt that he was not alone, and, pausing to listen
      intently, he distinctly heard the sound of breathing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who goes there?&rdquo; he said, in a hearty voice which belied his real
      anxiety.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis I, sir, Peter Waghorn,&rdquo; said the fanatic, gloomily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What, man! still longing to cast down the cross?&rdquo; said the Vicar. &ldquo;I had
      hoped you had come to see that we look on it with no superstition. But I
      know well &rsquo;tis a hard matter for all of us to see with each other&rsquo;s
      eyes. I should make a rare bungle did I try my hand at wood-carving, and
      you would make nothing at all of the pre-historic tooth which I am
      carrying from my museum room in the tower to show to Mistress Hilary.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It was too dark for him to see the expression on Waghorn&rsquo;s face, and he
      remained in ignorance of the man&rsquo;s intentions. Did he suspect that they
      used the tower to shelter Gabriel? Or did he merely keep a watchful eye on
      the Vicarage? Either surmise was disquieting. Dr. Coke fell back on his
      usual kindly sympathy, hoping to reach the heart of this strange and
      complex character.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come in and see me some night,&rdquo; he said, genially, &ldquo;for I have some rare
      old oak which you would be interested in. I&rsquo;ve a great mind to get you to
      carve me a corner cupboard for my study, an you think the wood will
      serve.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will come, sir,&rdquo; said Waghorn. &ldquo;But before you order the cupboard
      belike you had best be sure in your own mind that you&rsquo;ll be staying on at
      the Vicarage. Good-night to you, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With this vague and most discomforting speech the wood-carver quitted the
      churchyard, while the Vicar made his way home to ponder over the dark
      saying with growing uneasiness.
    </p>
    <p>
      On the following Saturday morning he was busy with his sermon when a knock
      at the door and the furious voice of the parish clerk recalled him from
      the study of St. Paul&rsquo;s words about charity to the difficulties of the
      present.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir!&rdquo; cried Zachary, crimson with anger, his face making the most strange
      contrast to Waghorn&rsquo;s grim pallor. &ldquo;Look what this pestilent fellow hath
      done now! &rsquo;Tis the Prayer-book, sir, from the church&mdash;he&rsquo;s slashed and
      torn it to bits!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar looked with indignation at the ruthlessly-torn pages, and
      hastily rising, paced the room, wrestling with a burning desire to kick
      the fanatic out of the house. When he had conquered himself, he returned
      once more to the writing-table.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By what right do you destroy the parish property?&rdquo; he said, gravely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am a parishioner, and do intend to see the law of the land obeyed,&rdquo;
       replied Waghorn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have yet to learn that the law of the land orders the tearing up of
      books,&rdquo; said the Vicar.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It orders the disuse of the Book of Common Prayer, and that&rsquo;s the same
      thing,&rdquo; retorted Waghorn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not at all,&rdquo; said the Vicar. &ldquo;If Parliament ordered you to cease from
      carving wood, it would not be lawful for me to come and burn your tools.
      Leave us, Zachary; I must discuss this matter alone with Waghorn.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With keen anxiety he recalled his encounter in the dark with the spy, and
      wondered how much he really knew.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I warned you, sir,&rdquo; said the wood-carver, &ldquo;that you might not be staying
      on at the Vicarage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hath Parliament, then, abolished me, as well as the Prayer-book?&rdquo;
       inquired the Vicar, with a humorous gleam in his grey eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It will turn you out unless you use the Directory as the law orders,&rdquo;
       said Waghorn, grimly, handing him a copy of the document. &ldquo;There be those
      at Gloucester that will see it is enforced; you must not look again to
      have a half-hearted officer, like Captain Harford, sent.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dr. Coke glanced with a sigh at the mangled prayer-book, wondering why it
      had become hateful to so many men.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It must be that they identify it with the harsh dealings of Archbishop
      Laud and Bishop Wren, and others who tried to enforce a system rather than
      to follow Christ,&rdquo; he thought to himself; and then he carefully read
      through the Directions which had been issued as to public worship. If he
      refused to obey he must leave his people as sheep without a shepherd just
      at a time when their distress was greatest, owing to the war and the
      constant harassing of the Canon Frome garrison. He must also imperil
      Gabriel&rsquo;s life by moving him from his present place of refuge.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dearly as he loved the liturgy he could not hesitate as to the right
      course of action. The thought of having to pray in public without a book
      was a nightmare to him, but with a moral courage that gave a curious new
      dignity to his manner and bearing, he said, quietly:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall give my father all the facts of the case, and for the present
      shall endeavour to follow the directions here given. Chapters shall be
      read from each Testament. Prayer, and especially the Lord&rsquo;s Prayer, shall
      be used. There shall be thanksgiving and singing of psalms. The Communion
      shall be frequently celebrated, and children shall be baptized only in
      church. Here are all the essentials of Christian worship, and though I
      sorely grieve to lose for a time the book that is far dearer to me than
      you guess, I see that for the present distress it is the only way.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And the surplice&mdash;that rag of popery&mdash;it must go also,&rdquo; said
      Waghorn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! Is it a rag of popery?&rdquo; said the Vicar with a smile. &ldquo;I had a notion
      that it was meant to represent the fine linen which is the righteousness
      of the saints. But though to my thinking &rsquo;tis a seemly garb, and I
      like things done as St. Paul advised, &lsquo;decently and in order,&rsquo; yet
      doubtless I can minister as well in my black doublet and hose.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Much better,&rdquo; said Waghorn, emphatically.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar sighed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Maybe &rsquo;tis a more appropriate garb,&rdquo; he reflected, &ldquo;for a man that
      well-nigh flew into a towering passion at sight of a torn Prayer-book.&rdquo;.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We will discuss the matter no more,&rdquo; he said, presently, &ldquo;but to-morrow
      in church let us try to meet in all sincerity as fellow-worshippers. Now I
      will show you the piece of oak we spoke of, and you shall take the
      measurements for the corner cupboard.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was no sleep that night for Dr. Coke, but, as Durdle often remarked,
      he was one of those whose looks did not pity them, and no one seeing the
      ruddy face and the long white hair had a notion what the man was
      undergoing when he took his place in the reading-desk on Sunday morning.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dearly beloved brethren,&rdquo; he began, &ldquo;owing to the present troubles in
      Church and State, it is not to-day in my power to use the Book of Common
      Prayer. I would remind you, however, that greatly as many of us love our
      liturgy, and helpful as we find it, God may be worshipped by us all in
      spirit and in truth, though our prayers be but halting and imperfect. I
      ask you, therefore, to kneel and to make after me, sentence by sentence,
      supplication to our Heavenly Father.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The startled people knelt, and very earnestly repeated the brief petitions
      for a more perfect faith, for a wider hope, for a more self-sacrificing
      love. They prayed for peace and for the needs of soul and body, and then
      with a gasp of relief the Vicar began the Lord&rsquo;s Prayer.
    </p>
    <p>
      The ordeal was over, and with a most thankful heart he gave out the
      Hundredth Psalm, which was valiantly played by flute and fiddle and
      heartily sung by all the congregation.
    </p>
    <p>
      After which, with the reading of che lessons, more psalm-singing and a
      sermon, the service came to an end.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; remarked Farmer Chadd, &ldquo;Vicar may not ha&rsquo; spoken with the tongue
      o&rsquo; angels as the text said, but he certainly did make folk see what
      charity means.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay,&rdquo; said Farmer Mutlow, &ldquo;and though I&rsquo;m with him in preferrin&rsquo; the
      Prayer-book, yet I will say it cheered my heart wonderful to pray for a
      good apple year, and above all to ask straight out for a blessin&rsquo; on the
      hops. Parson he knows well enough what plaguey uncertain things they be,
      and though the liturgy lumps &rsquo;em all in with &lsquo;fruits o&rsquo; the earth
      that in due time we may enjoy them,&rsquo; yet I always did hold with prayer for
      each child by name, and if for children why not for crops?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Quite right, neighbour, quite right,&rdquo; said Farmer Chadd. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll ask him
      to say a word for the hops every Sunday.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
