      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XLV.
    </h2>
    <p class="indent20">
      Revenge, at first though sweet,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Bitter ere long back on itself recoils.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      But mercy, first and last, shall brightest shine.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Milton.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">Z</span>achary was the
      only member of the household who slept that night. Hilary and Mrs. Durdle
      were too busy preparing what would be needed for the journey; the Vicar,
      full of anxiety, looked at his watch every quarter of an hour, and failed
      to find comfort even in ammonites or elephants&rsquo; teeth, while Gabriel, in
      the tower room, lay listening to the soft hooting of the white owl, and
      the unearthly stamping and knocking made down below by Harkaway. At the
      first glimmer of light he hastily put on the plum-coloured costume which
      had been laid by at Hereford since the early days of the war, and brought
      over by Dr. Coke for his journey. Then he filled his saddle-bags, and with
      a last look round the place which had made him so secure a refuge, stole
      down the ladder to feed and fondle his horse and saddle it in readiness
      for the journey. Zachary, with his head on the pillion, snored serenely,
      and Gabriel let him remain in peace till the first sparrow began to chirp,
      then cruelly roused him, unable to endure another minute&rsquo;s delay.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lord! Lord! I&rsquo;d but just closed my eyes,&rdquo; groaned the old man. &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t
      be married in the dark, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis morning, Zachary. Come, fix on the pillion; we shall have the
      Vicar here in a minute.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Yawning and stretching, the sexton struggled to his feet, and by the time
      the pillion had been strapped on, steps were indeed heard without, and on
      opening the door Gabriel was greeted by Mrs. Durdle in the choicest of
      white neckerchiefs, and her best Lincoln green hood.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good day to you and good luck to you, sir,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Vicar and Mistress
      Hilary be crossing the churchyard.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His face was aglow.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We have seen no more of Waghorn,&rdquo; he said, blithely, breathing the
      delicious morning air with rapture after his long imprisonment. &ldquo;But the
      owl hath hooted most dolefully. I have not slept a wink.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then catching sight of the Vicar in his college cap and black doublet and
      hose leading Hilary in the grey and pink gown he had specially begged her
      to wear, he hastened forward to greet them, and together they walked to
      the south porch, where, according to the old custom, the actual marriage
      was to take place.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly an ominous sound&mdash;the tramp of many feet close by made them
      pause and listen anxiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, sir, what is it?&rdquo; cried Durdle, in great terror.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Be still; let us hearken,&rdquo; said Dr. Coke, holding up his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary, with widening eyes, clung to Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t be afraid, dearest,&rdquo; he said, reassuringly; &ldquo;soldiers often pass
      through the village. They are not like to molest us here.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar went forward a few paces, and, catching sight of the uniform
      worn by the men of the Canon Frome garrison, realised the peril they were
      in.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Shelter in the church!&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis you they seek.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      But even as he spoke he saw that it was too late. Another file of soldiers
      rushed round from the west of the church, where they had lain in ambush
      till the rest of the men arrived, and Norton, with a contemptuous smile on
      his face, shouted his orders: &ldquo;Seize the Vicar! Arrest the rebel!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Amid a scene of wild confusion Hilary was torn from her lover, while, with
      unnecessary roughness, which turned her faint and sick, the soldiers bound
      Gabriel&rsquo;s arms. He saw that resistance was useless, and in the sudden
      revulsion from happiness to despair anguish overwhelmed him. Like one
      turned to stone, Hilary stood watching while the Vicar was also bound;
      and, roused by Durdle&rsquo;s screams and the unusual confusion of voices in the
      churchyard, men, women, and children came hurrying from the neighbouring
      houses to see what was amiss.
    </p>
    <p>
      As for Waghorn, in the excitement all his worst characteristics had
      started into view again, and like a maniac he stood shouting on the steps
      of the cross: &ldquo;Now am I avenged on mine enemy! They that dally with
      malignants shall rot in dungeons! No longer shall they hinder the work of
      the godly!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicar turned indignantly to the Governor of Canon Frome. &ldquo;What is the
      meaning of this outrage, Colonel Norton? You are interfering with me in
      the discharge of my duty!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your duty, sir, was to sign Prince Rupert&rsquo;s Protestation, and to refrain
      from aiding the King&rsquo;s enemies,&rdquo; said Norton, with a sneer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, you are wrong,&rdquo; replied the Vicar, firmly. &ldquo;I hold the King in all
      due reverence, but my first duty was to tend the wounded and shelter the
      homeless. And my next duty was to shield my niece from your wicked
      schemes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo; faith, you are a bold and outspoken man,&rdquo; said Norton, chuckling. &ldquo;But
      I can bide my time, Vicar.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He turned to watch Waghorn, who, in wild excitement, had sprung down from
      the cross and was shaking his fist derisively in Gabriel&rsquo;s face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ha! young bridegroom! I&rsquo;ll warrant you wish now that you&rsquo;d pulled down
      Bosbury Cross!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The taunt had the effect of restoring Gabriel to a quiet dignity of manner
      which impressed the soldiers. He made no reply whatever, but looked
      Waghorn in the face till, with an uneasy sense of guilt, the man withdrew
      a little. But the fanatic&rsquo;s place was quickly taken by Norton, and there
      was something in the malevolence of his smile which made the blood boil in
      Gabriel&rsquo;s veins. He remembered what this man had made him endure at
      Marlborough.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sorry, sir,&rdquo; said the Colonel, with a sneer, &ldquo;to spoil your highly
      virtuous device of holy matrimony, but as the proverb hath it, &lsquo;Marriages
      are made in heaven,&rsquo; and we intend to send you there. Sergeant! the
      halter!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A murmur of surprise and horror ran through the crowd. Gabriel felt as if
      a grisly hand had suddenly clutched his heart. He glanced anxiously at
      Hilary. Her face was marble white, she seemed scarcely conscious.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, sir, will you proceed so far?&rdquo; cried Waghorn, with a troubled look.
      &ldquo;This can be no hanging matter.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is it to you, fellow?&rdquo; said Norton, haughtily. And with satisfaction
      he saw the sergeant slip a rope about Gabriel&rsquo;s neck, and noted that a
      spasm of pain passed over the prisoner&rsquo;s face. He was too young and
      healthy to be without a most ardent love of life.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, sir,&rdquo; cried the Vicar, with passionate indignation, &ldquo;you cannot take
      so cruel a revenge! Captain Harford may lawfully be a prisoner of war, but&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is a rebel, and I know for a certainty that he bore about him
      traitorous despatches. Is it not so?&rdquo; said Norton, sharply turning towards
      the parliamentarian.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you know, why ask?&rdquo; said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Answer me!&rdquo; cried the Colonel, angrily. &ldquo;Did you not bear despatches?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your own spy hath already answered you. And for the despatches,&rdquo; said
      Gabriel, triumphantly, &ldquo;you&rsquo;ll not get them. They are long ere now
      delivered.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Away with him, sergeant! String him up to yonder tree,&rdquo; said Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      But with a wild cry of despair Hilary rushed forward &ldquo;Oh! no! no!&rdquo; and she
      threw her arms round Gabriel. &ldquo;You shall not take him! You shall not!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The soldiers were touched by her anguish, the villagers made indignant
      murmurings, some of the women began to sob. As for Waghorn, he turned
      away, muttering: &ldquo;Alack, poor lady! But nay, let me not falter! No
      weakness, Peter Waghorn! No weakness!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel kissed the weeping girl with passionate tenderness; then, unable
      to endure the sight of her grief, began to crave only for an end of this
      torture.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go, my dearest!&rdquo; he said, his voice faltering. &ldquo;I pray you&mdash;go!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      But the Vicar stepped towards Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I appeal to your better nature. As prisoner of war you
      have it in your power to send Captain Harford to gaol, but&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, that would be to make him your companion, dear sir,&rdquo; said Norton,
      lightly. &ldquo;No, no; I have quite other plans. <i>You</i> go to prison, <i>he</i>
      goes to Paradise. Come, you, as a parson, must own that I am giving him
      promotion.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn meanwhile paced to and fro wrestling with himself, and muttering
      like a madman through his teeth: &ldquo;Nay, nay; I will <i>not</i> relent. The
      enemies of truth must be punished. Let their habitation be desolate, and
      let none dwell in their tents! Add iniquity unto their iniquity.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was suddenly jostled aside by old Zachary, who, in deep distress,
      approached the Colonel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;For pity&rsquo;s sake, sir, hang me instead,&rdquo; he pleaded, &ldquo;&rsquo;twas my
      silly old tongue betrayed him&mdash;that and the fourth tankard of cider&mdash;hang
      me instead, for I deserve it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton laughed noisily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not at all&mdash;you have been a most useful tool. Come, get you gone!
      There will be work for you yet. You shall dig the grave, and Waghorn shall
      preach the funeral sermon. Why do you tarry, sergeant?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They tarried because it was no easy thing for Englishmen forcibly to part
      the sobbing girl from her lover.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dearest,&rdquo; said Gabriel, controlling his voice with an effort, &ldquo;you must
      go. Let some of the women take you to the Vicarage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      But as she raised her head and saw the rope about his throat, a new
      strength of resistance awoke within her. He should not die! She ran to
      Waghorn, and caught his hand in hers in eager entreaty.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Waghorn! you are not wicked like that man&mdash;you mean well&mdash;I
      know you mean well&mdash;help us now! Show mercy!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      For a moment the wood-carver wavered. Then a grim expression settled down
      upon his features.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nay, nay,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;Captain Harford hath but met with his deserts. What
      saith the Psalmist, &lsquo;Let there be none to extend mercy unto him! Let the
      iniquity of his fathers be remembered!&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, that was said by them of old time! But now we are bidden to be kind
      to one another&mdash;and tender-hearted,&rdquo; pleaded Hilary.
    </p>
    <p>
      But Waghorn, with a scornful look, exclaimed indignantly: &ldquo;Do not teach <i>me</i>,
      Mistress! I well know that you are of a carnal mind. Did you not deceive
      us in the orchard? You are a liar!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The villagers made angry protests at this plain speaking. Hilary, however,
      with a look that would have melted the hardest heart, continued her eager
      appeal.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes, I did speak falsely that day. But, oh&mdash;have <i>you</i>
      never sinned?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Puritan started back as if she had struck him. &ldquo;I?&rdquo; He hung his head,
      and in a flash it seemed as though his life with its bitter unforgiving
      lovelessness rose before him&mdash;a hideous vision. He crossed over to
      the Colonel, and put a hand on his sleeve.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How now, scarecrow? What is it?&rdquo; said Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You promised me that if I secured the despatches and Captain Harford, I
      might ask what I would of you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, what do you want?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I ask for the life of yonder Captain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton stared at him. &ldquo;Are you sure you don&rsquo;t mean his head in a charger?
      That, I think, is more in <i>your</i> line.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I ask you to spare his life,&rdquo; said Waghorn, sturdily, while all the
      people waited breathlessly for the reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      Norton gave a short scoffing laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, well, you may ask what you will, but I shall not grant such a
      request. You shall be reasonably paid for your services, and must content
      yourself with that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then the Puritan&rsquo;s wrath burst forth. &ldquo;Shame on thee for a
      promise-breaker! Dost think I served thee in this matter for filthy lucre?
      Nay, but to avenge the cause of truth, to save the land from the curse of
      those that break not down the high places, that destroy not the graven
      images!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He walked a few paces from the group and stood silently watching Hilary,
      who had again forced her way to her lover. Clinging to Gabriel, she
      sobbed, pitifully, while he whispered in her ear words of love and
      comfort.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hearken, Mistress Hilary,&rdquo; said Norton, striding across towards them,
      &ldquo;with one word you can save Captain Harford&rsquo;s life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What must I do?&rdquo; sobbed Hilary.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Only promise to be mine,&rdquo; he said, his eager eyes scanning her intently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I cannot!&rdquo; she replied, clinging closer to Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very well,&rdquo; said Norton, with a shrug of the shoulders. &ldquo;Sergeant,
      proceed!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary looked round at him in terrible agitation&mdash;then turned again
      to Gabriel, &ldquo;What am I to <i>do</i>?&rdquo; she cried, wildly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dear heart!&rdquo; he said, quietly, &ldquo;remember what we agreed. Cost what it may&mdash;be
      true!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But&mdash;your life&mdash;oh, my dearest!&mdash;your life!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It will not be ended by the hangman,&rdquo; he replied, with a strange
      vibration in his voice, &ldquo;it will go on elsewhere. We have but to wait.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton stamped his foot impatiently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, is your choice made?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go, my beloved!&rdquo; said Gabriel, tenderly, but with a firmness which
      steadied her failing powers. Then he gave her a long, lingering kiss, and
      she slowly took her arms from about his neck and staggered towards the
      Vicar, hiding her face on his shoulder.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gabriel watched her in heart-broken silence, understanding for the first
      time what the bitterness of death meant. An awful stillness reigned in the
      churchyard. He turned towards Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, I am ready,&rdquo; he said, in a low, firm voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      Norton watched him with mingled feelings. It was impossible not to admire
      his courage and dignity, yet never had he hated the man more.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Fool! You would die in your youth?&rdquo; he said, sneeringly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then into Gabriel&rsquo;s eyes there suddenly came a light that was Divine.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why,&rdquo; he cried, &ldquo;I would live in hellish torments to save her from such
      as you&mdash;and shall I fear <i>death?</i> You think that when I am hung
      and the Vicar cast into gaol, you will be free to carry out your vile
      schemes&mdash;but I tell you, <i>in spite of all</i>, evil will not
      triumph. There is a God who hates tyranny, who loves mercy and justice!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His whole face was transfigured. It was Norton whose cheek paled and who
      looked like the man about to die.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;String him up, sergeant. I loathe this cant,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Be quick, you fools&mdash;hang
      the rebel and have done with it!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The soldiers threw the end of the rope over a branch of the tree under
      which they stood; the sergeant adjusted the noose more carefully round the
      prisoner&rsquo;s neck, and Gabriel gave one last glance at the familiar scene&mdash;the
      tower of refuge clearly outlined against the roseate sky, the green
      churchyard, the old cross so curiously linked with his fate, the gabled
      houses in the village street, and the Vicar&rsquo;s white head bent down over
      Hilary&rsquo;s brown curls. Then the rope tightened about his throat, he closed
      his eyes and prayed, while through his brain there floated the old Psalm
      which he had last heard in Ledbury High Street
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      &ldquo;In trouble and adversity,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The Lord God hear thee still.
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      The Majesty of Jacob&rsquo;s God
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Defend thee from all ill.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly an exclamation and a sound of tramping feet made him open his
      eyes again. He saw that another detachment of Royalist soldiers was
      marching through the lych gate, but close at hand, having evidently
      approached quietly from another quarter, stood an officer whom he at once
      recognised as Lord Hopton.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hold, in the King&rsquo;s name!&rdquo; shouted the new-comer, and the sickening
      pressure about the prisoner&rsquo;s neck was relaxed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hilary rushed forward and threw herself at the General&rsquo;s feet.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, my lord,&rdquo; she pleaded, &ldquo;help us! Do not let them take his life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Madam,&rdquo; he said, raising her courteously, &ldquo;be of good cheer. I heard your
      lover&rsquo;s brave words. I also heard your words, Colonel Norton,&rdquo; and he
      glanced sternly at the Governor of Canon Frome.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sir, if you had heard the whole case against Captain Harford&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
       stammered Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What! &rsquo;tis Captain Harford?&rdquo; cried Lord Hopton. &ldquo;Ay, to be sure I
      recognise you now, sir, and remember that &rsquo;tis to your kindly
      offices when I lay wounded at Lansdown that I owe my life. Sergeant,
      remove that halter and unbind Captain Harford.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hilary, radiant with joy, ran to her lover, and&mdash;his bonds removed&mdash;he
      clasped her in his arms with a rapture which made them utterly oblivious
      of the thronged churchyard. They only felt that life laid down had been
      wonderfully renewed, and that every heartbeat was a wordless thanksgiving.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lord Hopton meanwhile had turned to the other prisoner.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What! you also bound, sir?&rdquo; he exclaimed, indignantly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is the meaning of this, Colonel Norton?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The Vicar of Bosbury,&rdquo; said Norton, sullenly, &ldquo;hath for weeks, sir,
      sheltered this rebel, and he is but a lukewarm supporter of His Majesty.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;His Majesty would fare better were all parsons such kindly peacemakers,&rdquo;
       said Lord Hopton, himself cutting the cords which bound the Vicar&rsquo;s arms.
      &ldquo;&rsquo;Tis men like you, Colonel, who are the ruin of the King&rsquo;s cause.
      Oh, I have heard of your cruelties, and I know how the whole country-side
      has cause to hate you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you give ear, sir, to the complaints of an aged gentlewoman like Dame
      Elizabeth Hopton, and the murmurs of a pack of peasants, you will hear
      strange tales.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lord Hopton frowned.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I intend to examine into matters later on, and you can then make your
      defence. Meanwhile I hold a letter from the King depriving you of your
      Governorship, and appointing Colonel Barnold. And I shall be obliged to
      you now, Colonel Barnold, if you and a detachment of the soldiers from the
      garrison will escort the ex-Governor to Canon Frome. I shall be with you
      anon.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You pardon a rebel despatch-bearer, sir, and overlook the persistent way
      in which Dr. Coke hath refused to sign Prince Rupert&rsquo;s Protestation,&rdquo; said
      Norton bitterly, &ldquo;but give me scant justice.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I hope to show you not only justice but clemency,&rdquo; said Lord Hopton.
      &ldquo;What of your despatches, Captain Harford?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Massey entrusted me with letters, my lord, to Fairfax and Cromwell,&rdquo; said
      Gabriel, &ldquo;but as I was sorely wounded they were borne to Windsor by
      another hand some weeks ago.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A shade of relief was visible about the General&rsquo;s lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That matter is ended, then,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;and with regard to what you say
      against Dr. Coke, I hold, sir, that he was bound to set the safety and
      honour of his niece before any matters of State, and that as a Christian
      he had a perfect right to shelter and tend a wounded man, whatever his
      political views.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norton was led away, and the Vicar eagerly thanked Lord Hopton for all
      that he had done for them. Then, seeing the expectation in the faces of
      the villagers, he added, &ldquo;Betwixt Hilary and Captain Harford, my lord,
      there was an attachment of long standing, and this very morning I was to
      have wedded them.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The women in the crowd smiled and nodded at each other, and Lord Hopton,
      catching sight of the radiant faces of the lovers, smiled too.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now what a happy thing it was,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;that I chose to make a night
      march, and reached Canon Frome at dawn! Finding the Governor absent, I was
      minded to see for myself what pranks he was after, and arrived in the nick
      of time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You were in time to save a life, my lord,&rdquo; said the Vicar, &ldquo;and now, an
      you will, may witness a wedding; we keep to the old custom here and wed at
      the church door.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll not only witness it, but will give away the bride if that is
      agreeable to you, sir,&rdquo; he said, glancing at Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My lord, the memory of your kindly dealing will long outlast the
      bitterness I have just passed through,&rdquo; said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      His face aglow with happiness, and still shining with that spiritual light
      which had arrested even Norton&rsquo;s notice, touched the Royalist general.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I very well know,&rdquo; he said, laying a kindly hand on his shoulder, &ldquo;that
      you were the first to show considerateness in the matter of Bosbury Cross,
      and till people of widely differing views act with the good sense and
      moderation shown by you and the Vicar, we shall never have true peace in
      England.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He turned to offer his arm to Hilary, when she suddenly perceived Waghorn
      gravely watching them from a little distance. Running towards him, she
      took his hand gratefully in hers.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall never forget, Waghorn, that you tried to save Captain Harford,&rdquo;
       she said, warmly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mistress,&rdquo; said Waghorn, earnestly, and with a quiet manliness wholly
      unlike his former manner, &ldquo;he was right. In spite of all, evil did not
      triumph.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And now the psalm which had rung in Gabriel&rsquo;s ears as he awaited death,
      sounded indeed through the churchyard as Hilary walked towards the porch
      between Lord Hopton and her lover.
    </p>
    <p>
      The villagers drew together in a group close by them, but little Nan and
      Meg being on the outskirts chanced to look back, and saw Waghorn standing
      afar off as though he had no part or lot in the service. With a kindly
      impulse they ran towards him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t stand there so all alone,&rdquo; said Nan, coaxingly, &ldquo;come nearer!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; echoed Meg, &ldquo;come nearer!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Waghorn&rsquo;s stern face relaxed. He sighed, but let them take him by the hand
      and draw him in with the rest.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2H_EPIL" id="link2H_EPIL"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      EPILOGUE.
    </h2>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>I pray God our zeal in these times may be so kindled with pure fire
      from God&rsquo;s altar that it may rather warm than burn, enliven rather than
      inflame, and that the spirits of good men may truly be qualified with
      Gospel principles, true fruits of the Divine Spirit. And truly I believe
      that the members of the Church, if not the leaders&mdash;notwithstanding
      all the perfections of times before us, so much pictured or applauded&mdash;have
      very much yet to learn. For I am persuaded that Christian love and
      affection is a point of such importance that it is not to be prejudiced by
      </i>supposals<i> of difference in points of religion in any ways
      disputable, though thought weighty as determined by the parties on either
      side; or by particular determinations beyond Scripture, which, as some
      have observed, have enlarged divinity, but have lessened charity and
      multiplied divisions. For the maintenance of truth is rather God&rsquo;s charge,
      and the continuance of charity ours.&rdquo;&mdash;Letters of Benjamin Whichcote,
      1651.</i>
    </p>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">A</span>nd were they
      married here in this very porch where we&rsquo;re sitting, grandfather?&rdquo; said
      little Bobbie Coke, looking up into the Vicar&rsquo;s kindly face, which the
      forty-five years had made only somewhat thinner and paler.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Here in this very porch, Bobbie,&rdquo; he replied, his arm about the lad,
      while on his knee sat little Mollie Harford, the orphan daughter of
      Gabriel&rsquo;s brother, Bridstock, who had died seven years before.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never was there such a happy wedding before or since, for it is not often
      that the bridegroom is rescued at the last moment from the jaws of death.
      The villagers were ready to cry for joy, and the soldiers&mdash;brave
      fellows!&mdash;why, they were only too glad to be let off the horrid piece
      of work their Colonel had set them to do.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And when did my grandfather come?&rdquo; asked Mollie.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He came that evening, and Mrs. Harford with him, and they all stayed at
      the Vicarage a couple of days, rejoicing. Then the bride and bridegroom
      went to say farewell to the Bishop at Whitbourne, and thence to London,
      where Madam Harford gave them a right loving welcome, and took good care
      of Hilary, while her husband joined Cromwell, and began his career as mate
      to the surgeon of his regiment. It was in that fashion that he again saw
      Colonel Norton. For after the great battle at Naseby, when he was going
      about the field succouring the wounded, he came upon the Colonel lying
      there half dead, and was able to bind up his wounds, and bring him the
      water he cried out for. When the Colonel had drunk it, he looked up with
      startled eyes at his helper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Why, God bless my soul! Is it you?&rsquo; he cried. &lsquo;What are you doing?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Helping the sick and wounded,&rsquo; said Gabriel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Confounded queer work for a gentleman,&rsquo; said Norton.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;It was good enough for Christ,&rsquo; said the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then up came the surgeon, said &rsquo;twas no use spending time over one
      that couldn&rsquo;t live an hour, and bade his mate come and rest. But Gabriel,
      saying that he knew the wounded officer, asked to remain with him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Why should I lie shivering here for an hour?&rsquo; said Norton, in his
      devil-may-care tone. &lsquo;It will be quicker work if I die on my feet, and
      I&rsquo;ll be bound you think I shall be hot enough in the next world.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Lie still,&rsquo; said Gabriel. &lsquo;Here&rsquo;s the cloak Lord Falkland gave me at
      Marlborough. We&rsquo;ll wrap it about you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now at the word Marlborough, the face of the dying man changed, and he
      fell a-thinking.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Say the words you said that night,&rsquo; he gasped.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Gabriel, unable to think what he meant, said the first words that came to
      his mind:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Forgive us our trespasses as we forgive them that trespass against us,
      and lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil, for thine is
      the kingdom, and the power and the glory, for ever.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And after that the dying man lay in his arms fighting hard for breath,
      but never speaking, only once he gripped Gabriel&rsquo;s hand and looked in his
      eyes, as though he would have thanked him. Then, as darkness fell on the
      blood-stained field, he passed away.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And what happened to my uncle Gabriel?&rdquo; asked Mollie.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The war ended not long after that, and he went to London, and studied for
      two years under Sir Theodore Mayerne, and then for two years more at
      Paris. In 1650 he settled finally in London, and there became a celebrated
      physician, and all went well with him. He had twenty years of happy wedded
      life, marred only by some trouble at the time of the Restoration for the
      part he had played in the Civil War. However, that was no very serious
      matter, and there were few happier homes in the country till the year of
      the Great Plague.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Knowing that his duty lay with the poor sick folk in London, he parted
      from his wife and four children, sending them, as he hoped, out of all
      risk to Katterham, a country place some eighteen miles off. But it fell
      about that, as they halted at Croydon to bait the horses, some that were
      also flying from the plague, sat with them at the common table in the inn,
      and even as they dined one of these fellow-travellers was seized with
      illness. Spite of all precautions, my dear niece herself sickened the next
      day, and ere twenty-four hours had passed she and her children were dead.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;An old comrade, Sir Joscelyn Hey worth, travelled to London to break the
      news to his friend, who seemed for the time wholly crushed. But as they
      sat together talking very sadly, there came in Sir William Denham, who for
      many years had known them both.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Doctor,&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;I scarce like to break in upon your sorrow, but my
      friend Judge Wharncliffe and his wife have just died of the plague, and
      their two sons are at death&rsquo;s door, with no one but an old man-servant to
      care for them, and the doctor who had attended them hath now died in the
      very house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At that Gabriel put aside his own trouble, and went forth to see what he
      could do. He found the elder lad, a fine fellow of one and twenty,
      beginning to rally, but the younger, a tiny, delicate child of but two or
      three years, lay at the point of death. He fought for its life, and never
      left it till it had passed the crisis, and by that time, as he afterwards
      told me, life had again become bearable to him, and he found what the joy
      of battle meant; it was not the brutal love of bloodshed, it was the
      God-like desire to overcome evil with good, disease with health, and death
      with life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And did the little boy get quite strong?&rdquo; asked Mollie, eagerly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay, to be sure, he&rsquo;s alive to this day, and has lived a right noble life.
      Few men have suffered with a better courage than Hugo Wharncliffe, and one
      day I&rsquo;ll tell you his story.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And now tell me the rest about Uncle Gabriel,&rdquo; said Mollie. &ldquo;Did he live
      much longer?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Only five years more, but they were five years full of good Work. It was
      in 1670, I remember, that he wrote to say he was advised to take a few
      weeks&rsquo; rest and hoped to pay us a visit at Bosbury on his way home to his
      father. Now Dr. Harford was attending some sick folk at the Grange, and
      chanced to be here the very day he arrived. As we all dined together
      Gabriel told us with much interest of certain people called Quakers that
      he had lately come to know. Their way of thought had great attraction for
      him, especially the effort they made to obey literally the teaching of
      Christ as to using no oath, and avoiding all war and violence.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;Seeing the quiet way in which they laid down their lives for their peace
      principles,&rsquo; he said, &lsquo;set me wondering whether Christ must not be grieved
      to find the war spirit so strong still among His followers, and that 1670
      years after his birth the bulk of us still demand an eye for an eye and a
      tooth for a tooth.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We found that in addition to all his usual work he had been visiting many
      of these Quakers, who, under the persecuting laws of those times, were
      imprisoned in Newgate, Bishopsgate Gaol and the New Prison. It was in this
      fashion that he had taken a fever, for gaol fever raged among these
      prisoners for conscience&rsquo; sake; but he said he grudged not having taken
      the infection from them, for he hoped that he had caught from them, also,
      some of their noble and true thoughts. He spoke, too, of Lord Falkland&rsquo;s
      craving for peace, and thought that, like him, the Quakers were in advance
      of the times, and were to lead the nation to truer and nobler ways of
      thought, particularly on this point about peace, which one day all men
      would see to be the only true Christ-following.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We were still talking of the Society of Friends when Dr Harford said he
      must go out again to visit two more patients. I remember we all three
      stood for a minute at the garden-gate, and can almost hear your uncle&rsquo;s
      voice still as he said, &lsquo;When they spoke of the duty of Christians to take
      no part in war, I used to feel as on the day when Waghorn would have
      pulled down the cross, and you spoke of love which is the bond of peace,
      and then coming hither we found Hilary standing beneath the yew tree
      holding open the gate for us.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;His eyes grew wistful, and I noticed that his hand rested for a minute on
      the gate, as though anything she had touched was sacred to him. Then, his
      cheerfulness returning, he said he must pay a visit to the Tower of
      Refuge, and so we parted, for I knew that the place was full of memories
      to him and that he would fain be alone.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In about an hour your grandfather returned, and we went across the
      churchyard to find your uncle, talking as we went of the way in which the
      fever and the overwork had changed him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&lsquo;He will need a long rest,&rsquo; said Dr. Harford. &lsquo;He hath worn himself out
      with the woes of others and with the noisome air of those pestilent
      gaols.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I said it was after all natural enough, for he had ever had a special
      feeling for prisoners since his time in Oxford Castle, and Herefordshire
      was the very best place he could have come to for a rest and change.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, by that we had drawn near to the porch, and saw that he was sitting
      on this western bench and must have fallen asleep, for he had taken off
      the long curled wig that all gentlemen wore then much as they do now, and
      with his short hair he looked curiously like the Captain Harford who had
      saved Bosbury Cross.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But something in his perfect stillness struck Dr. Harford with sudden
      anxiety. We bent close down to him&mdash;he had ceased to breathe, and
      from his face death had smoothed away all the lines of sorrow, so that he
      looked once more young. I wish I could describe to you the wonderful
      serene dignity of his expression&mdash;but that is not to be put into
      words. Here in this porch where five-and-twenty years before I had wedded
      him to my dear niece, God had once more united the husband and wife.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is such a pity people have to die,&rdquo; said Bobbie, kicking the
      flagstones with energy, because he saw tears in Mollie&rsquo;s eyes and wished
      to keep them from his own.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You think so?&rdquo; said his grandfather, with a smile. &ldquo;And quite right too
      at your age. But when like me you are an old man of four-score years and
      ten, there&rsquo;ll be so many waiting for you on the other side of the river
      that you&rsquo;ll be glad when you are told to cross over. I hear your
      grandfather&rsquo;s step on the path, Mollie, and when we two old friends chat
      over old times together, &rsquo;tis hard for you young ones to get in a
      word, so you had best go in and see the Harford monuments, and Bishop
      Swinfield&rsquo;s head which was rescued from Hereford Cathedral.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s no monument to Uncle Gabriel,&rdquo; said Mollie, wiping away her
      tears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My child, his body lies in the chancel, but Bosbury Cross is his
      monument, and he could not have a better,&rdquo; said the Vicar.
    </p>
    <p>
      As the two children entered the church he took from the pocket of his
      doublet a small note-book, and added a line to an epitaph he had been
      trying to write, smiling to himself over Bobbie&rsquo;s notion that it was a
      pity anybody died.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      I lay me down at expectation&rsquo;s door;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Weary and worn with age I crave no more. But
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Christus Jesus meus est omnia.
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      &mdash;Will. Coke, 1690.
    </p>
    <p>
      As he finished the verse, Dr. Harford, marvellously erect and active for
      his eighty-five years, crossed the churchyard and sat down beside him in
      the porch.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have come across a curious link with the past,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Chancing to
      be at Farmer Chadd&rsquo;s just now where Meg is laid up, as you know, she gave
      me this ring which her husband had found yesterday when digging in the
      orchard. I fancy it must have dropped from Colonel Norton&rsquo;s finger on the
      day of the duel, and have lain there unnoticed these five-and-forty years.
      The initials as you see are L. and N.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay,&rdquo; said the antiquary, putting up his glass and scrutinising the
      letters carefully; &ldquo;two L&rsquo;s for Lionel and Lucy. It must have been his
      wife&rsquo;s wedding-ring. And here is the posy
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      &lsquo;Till death us departe&mdash;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Nay not so deare harte&mdash;
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      Death shall us more truly unite.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Poor Norton!&rdquo; said the Vicar. &ldquo;He was a man who might have lived such a
      different life! Well, who knows but that on Naseby Field God&rsquo;s grace may,
      indeed, have delivered him from evil?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am always glad to think that he was one of Gabriel&rsquo;s first patients,&rdquo;
       said Dr. Harford, &ldquo;and that those poor imprisoned Quakers, suffering so
      bravely in the cause of peace, were his last. We may say truly that in
      helping them he gave up his own life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And God be thanked that since our peaceful Revolution there are no more
      persecutions for opinion,&rdquo; observed the Vicar. &ldquo;We have passed through
      rough waters, doctor, yet have each of us been blessed with a loving wife,
      and have lived to see our children and our children&rsquo;s children blessed in
      their career. But to my mind the noblest race was run by your son,
      Gabriel, who, indeed, died a hero of peace.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <h3>
      THE END.
    </h3>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2H_4_0048" id="link2H_4_0048"> </a>
    </p>
